[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "21"]

{In this lecture, we will discuss one of the most important pawn structures in
French Defense - The Exchange Structure. In my opinion, the Exchange Variation
was always very unpleasant for "french" players. In recent years, White has
discovered some new ideas, and the line has become a nasty weapon in the hands
of some very strong players, including Magnus Carsen. Still, in my opinion, in
most of the cases, White uses this variation when he wants to achieve a
"risk-free" position or when he plays with a higher-rated opponent. In this
lecture, I will show you mainly Black's plans and different ways to complicate
the game. I should mention that the plans in symmetrical structures are
similar for both sides. So any idea for White can be used by Black as well.
The important rule for playing for a win such positions is to gain small
advantages. You can't win by brutal force, but little by little. I will
provide you with my vision for the most interesting variations for both sides
and explain the move orders to you. In the database, you will find 19
commented games. I started with some classical game of Alekhine. I recommend
you study them well because they show how the game can go against lower-rated
opponents. The 4th world champion shows most of the ideas for Black. Later I
continue with modern games, which show different ways to imbalance the
position. In the end, I add eight games from other lectures. Four of them are
Mihail Marin's analysis for his fantastic trilogy about French Defence.
Another four are my analysis from the previous lecture about exchange
structures, where you can see some of White's ideas in the arising positions. 
Now, let's start with examining the move orders.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5
exd5 {In this position, White has four possible plans} 4. Nf3 $1 {This is
considered to be the best continuation for White} (4. Bd3 {is a bit premature
for two reasons} c5 $1 {Marin's choice leading to imbalanced IQP positions} (
4... Nc6 {I like this move a lot. It puts pressure on d4, but also threatens
Nb4 in many occasions.})) (4. Bf4 {with the idea Nc3, Qd2, 0-0-0. The
positions here are very sharp, but I believe that Black is doing fine after:}
Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd6 6. Qd2 O-O 7. O-O-O c6 {[%cal Rb7b5,Ra7a5]} (7... a5 {is Giri's
recommendation and also makes a lot of sense.})) (4. c4 {aiming for an IQP
position is not very accurate with the bishop still on f8. Black should
continue with:} Bb4+ {with a good game. You can find Mihail Marin's analysis
in this line later in the lecture.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {I like this idea a lot. The
drawback of this move is that it allows 5.Bb5.} (4... Bg4 $6 5. h3 Bh5 6. Qe2+
{Kasparov's move put some questions on 4...Bg4}) (4... Nf6 5. Bd3 c5 {This was
Marin's and Giri's recommendation and should be taken seriously} (5... Bd6 {
I think that probably Black equalizes here as well, but his task is much
harder and White can play risk-free positions} 6. Qe2+ (6. O-O)) 6. O-O Nc6 {
Marin} (6... c4 {Giri})) (4... c5 $2 {is a mistake} 5. Bb5+ $1 {and White is
better. This is one of the main differences with 4.Bd3}) (4... Bd6 {is another
popular line, keeps the option to play Ne7, but White can continue} 5. c4 Nf6 (
5... Ne7 $4 {is a well known mistake} 6. c5) 6. c5 {an interesting new attempt}
Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Be3 {White scores pretty well here}) 5. Bb5 Bd6 6.
c4 a6 7. Ba4 dxc4 8. d5 b5 9. dxc6 bxa4 10. O-O Ne7 11. Qxa4 {is a bit slow
and I believe Black has good dynamic chances here} (11. Nbd2 {allows c3 in an
appropriate momment}) *

