1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bd3 Bd6 {In this game Alekhine prefers
developing the kingside first.} 5. Nf3 {this move allows the unpleasant pin.}
Bg4 {Usually, Black has problems with his LightSquared bishop and in many
cases, Black's dream is to reach the "g4" square.} 6. Be3 {It seems that this
was the way to play this position in the past. Now we know that White should
delay developing his dark-squared bishop.} Ne7 7. c3 Nbc6 8. O-O Qd7 {When I
learned French defense for the first time. I was told that this is the ideal
setup for Black. He has two main plans: 1. Exchanging the light-squared
bishops by means of Bf5 and then trying to reach an endgame with a knight
against a dark-squared bishop. 2.Go for a kingside attack as Alekhine did in
the game.} 9. Nbd2 h5 $1 {I like this plan a lot. Now Black starts to advance
his pawns. In the meantime, it is hard for White to organize any counterplay}
10. Re1 f6 11. a4 (11. h3 $2 {I should mention that this move just create a
hook. Black will open the file on the kingside using g5-g4} Bf5 {[%cal Rg7g5,
Rg5g4]}) 11... h4 12. Bf1 g5 ({The engine suggests} 12... h3 13. g3 a5 {
leaving White without a clear plan}) 13. b4 Bf5 {Freeing the g4-square for the
pawn} 14. Nxg5 $4 {Panic move, after which White is just a lot. I can't see
any serious compensation for the piece. Alekhine converts his advantage with
ease.} ({after} 14. Nb3 $1 g4 15. Nfd2 {it is not easy for Black to create any
serious threats on the kingside}) 14... fxg5 15. Bxg5 O-O-O 16. a5 Rdg8 17. f4
Ng6 18. b5 Nxf4 (18... Nd8 {was good enough too}) 19. bxc6 Nh3+ 20. gxh3 Rxg5+
21. Kh1 Qg7 22. Nf3 Rg8 23. Ba6 Rg2 24. Re2 Be4 0-1

