1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 {As we discuss at the beginning of the
lecture. This is the best option for White} Bd6 5. Bd3 Bg4 6. O-O Ne7 7. Bg5 {
The typical idea in this structure is to exchange the dark-squared bishop by
means of Bg5-h4-g3. This exchange is strategically sound but takes a lot of
time.} f6 8. Bh4 Nbc6 9. c3 h5 {The same idea as in the previous game} 10. Nbd2
g5 11. Bg3 h4 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Re1 O-O-O 14. b4 Rde8 {freeing the d8-square
for the knight} 15. Qc2 Qf4 $2 {This move is objectively a mistake but works
very well in the game.} (15... Kb8 {[%cal Rg4c8,Rg5g4] this prophylactic move
was Black's best option}) 16. Re2 $2 (16. Re3 $1 $14 {[%cal Ra1e1] and White's
position is preferable. The idea Rae1 is not easy to meet.}) 16... Bxf3 $1 {
I believe Opocensky missed this strong move} 17. Nxf3 h3 18. Qc1 Qg4 19. Qf1
Nf5 20. Rae1 (20. Rxe8+ $1 Rxe8 21. Re1 $11) 20... Rxe2 21. Bxf5+ Qxf5 22. Qxe2
Nd8 23. g3 a6 24. a4 Kb8 25. Kh1 (25. Nd2 $1 {Black is better, but the game is
far from over}) 25... Re8 {Another easy win for Alekhine in the Exchange French
} 0-1

