1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. Ne2 {In symmetrical structures,
the ideas are the same for both sides. Here in similarity to Black's Ne7+Bf5,
White is trying to exchange his dark-squared bishop via Bf4.} Bd6 6. c3 {
The d4-pawn needs protection. Now White is planning to continue with Bf4.} Qh4
{Remember this idea; more often, we will see it with the reversed colors (Qh5).
Black is stopping 0-0 and Bf4.} 7. Nd2 (7. g3 {the engines are optimistic
about this move, but from a human point of view this weakens light squares too
much} Qh5 (7... Qf6 $5) 8. Bf4 Qf3 9. Rg1 Nf6 $13) 7... Bg4 8. Qc2 O-O-O 9. Nf1
g6 (9... Nf6 {looks more natural to me}) 10. Be3 (10. Ne3 {is more logical
followed by g3 and 0-0-0} Be6 11. Bd2 f5 12. g3 Qf6 13. O-O-O $14) 10... Nge7
11. O-O-O Bf5 12. Nfg3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 h6 14. f4 Qg4 (14... f5 {[%cal Rg3f1,
Rf1d2,Rd2f3,Rf3e5] weakens the "e5" square too much}) 15. h3 (15. f5 {is an
interesting attempt for White} Bxg3 16. Nxg3 Nxf5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. Bd2 {
with a decent compensation for the sacrificing material}) (15. Rhf1 $5 {
[%cal Rf4f5]}) 15... Qd7 16. Rhf1 h5 17. Ng1 h4 18. N3e2 Nf5 {Now Black gets
his dream position. The h4-pawn fixes the kingside. The f4-pawn is weak and
White has a lot of weak squares on the e-file.} 19. Nf3 f6 {of course, we will
cover the e5-square before starting any concrete actions.} 20. Nh2 Rde8 21. Bd2
Re6 22. Ng4 Rhe8 23. Rde1 R8e7 $1 {you will find this move as an exercise in
many books about strategy. When we triple our pieces, we put first the rooks
and the queen behind them.} 24. Kd1 Qe8 25. Qf3 {White is completely paralyzed.
Now it is time to activate our last passive piece.} Na5 $1 26. b3 Nc4 $1 27.
Bc1 Nce3+ 28. Bxe3 Nxe3+ 29. Nxe3 Rxe3 30. Qf2 Qb5 31. Nc1 Rxc3 {Black wins
material and the game is decided. The rest was a matter of simple technique}
32. Rxe7 Bxe7 33. Qe1 Kd7 34. f5 Re3 35. Qf2 g5 36. Re1 Re4 37. Rxe4 dxe4 38.
Kd2 Bd6 39. Kc2 Bf4 {Amazing performance by Aleckhine} 0-1

