1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Bg4 {an interesting move} 5. h3 Bh5 6.
Be2 (6. Qe2+ $1 {Later Kasparov shows the right way to handle this position
for White} Qe7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. g4 Bg6 10. O-O-O $14 {1/2-1/2 (58)
Kasparov,G (2770)-Short,N (2660) Tilburg 1991}) 6... Bd6 7. Ne5 {this move is
a bit premature. White should just continue developing} Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Ne7 9. O-O
O-O 10. Bf4 Re8 11. Qg4 Bxe5 $1 {Very important move to remember. One of
White's main idea in Exchange French is to enter an endgame with a knight
against a dark-squared bishop} 12. Bxe5 Ng6 13. Bg3 Nd7 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Qf3 c6
16. Qb3 Qb6 $1 {Even without queens on the board, Black has an advantage} 17.
Qxb6 axb6 18. a3 $2 {this mistake is hard to explain. The move is not that bad
, but why give Black a chance to make progress on the queenside.} (18. a4 $1 {
Fixing the weakness on b6} Ne4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. c3 {It is not clear how Black
can make progress here. The threat Bc7 is very unpleasant. For example:} Rae8
$6 21. Bc7 $1) 18... Ne4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. Rfd1 b5 $5 {Now Black can hope for
a play on the queenside} 21. Kf1 f6 22. f3 Re6 23. Re1 Kf7 24. Rxe6 Kxe6 25.
Re1+ Kd7 26. Ke2 $2 {This move is inaccurate and allows Black to fix the
kingside in his favor} (26. Bf2 h5 27. g4) 26... h5 $1 {Black's advantage
becomes significant} 27. Kd3 (27. h4 $1 {Still I believe that Gurevich should
allow Black's pawn on h4, even with a cost to put his  pawn on the dark square}
) 27... h4 28. Bh2 Ne7 29. Bf4 Nf5 {Black already did everything that he could
on the kingside and now it is time to penetrate the queenside} 30. Bd2 b6 31.
Re2 c5 32. Be3 (32. c3 {is more stubborn and Black still needs to work hard to
win the game.}) 32... b4 $1 {very nice pawn sacrifice, even approved by the
engine. Short is opening the a-file, but objectively speaking this is still
not enough to win the game.} 33. axb4 c4+ 34. Kc3 Nd6 35. Re1 Ra4 36. Kd2 (36.
Rb1 $1 {was the best chance} Nb5+ 37. Kd2 Rxb4 38. b3 {with good chances for
White to hold}) 36... Rxb4 37. Ra1 $2 (37. Kc1 Nf5 38. Bf2 Ra4 $17) (37. Rb1
Ra4 $17) 37... Rxb2 $19 {Now it is over} 38. Ra7+ Ke6 39. Rxg7 b5 40. Bf2 b4
41. Kc1 c3 42. Bxh4 Nf5 {[%cal Rf5e3]} 0-1

