1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bd3 c5 {This is one of the two systems which
I reccomend you after 4.Bd3. It leads to unbalanced positions with IQP and
gives Black a chance to take the initiative.} 5. dxc5 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. c3 (6.
Qe2+ Be7 7. dxc5 Nf6 {[%cal Re8g8] White can't keep his extra pawn and Black
is doing just fine in this line}) 6... Nf6 (6... c4 {also leads to an
unbalanced position.} 7. Bc2 Bd6 8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3 Nge7) 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. Re1+ Be6 10. Ng5 (10. Bg5 $5) 10... O-O {and Black gets the iniative})
5... Bxc5 {A rule here is that Black is always OK if his bishop comes to c5 in
one move.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 {This move stops Bg4, but weakens the
kingside} (8. Bg5 {is the main line}) 8... Nc6 9. Nbd2 $6 {this move is too
soft and Black takes the initiative after it} Qd6 $1 {The queen is heading to
g3} 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. c3 Bxh3 $5 {This move leads only to a draw, but it is
tough for White to remember all the defensive moves} (11... Re8 $5) 12. gxh3
Qg3+ 13. Kh1 Qxh3+ 14. Nh2 (14. Kg1 $2 Bc7 $19) 14... Ne5 15. Be2 Nf3 16. Bf4
Nh4 17. Bf3 {only move} Nh5 18. Bg3 $4 {This is a losing move} (18. Be5 Rae8
19. Rg1 Bxf2 20. Qf1 Qxf1 21. Rgxf1 Rxe5 22. Bxh5 Bb6 {Black has 3 pawns for
the piece. The game remains very complicated, but far from clear}) 18... Qxg3
$1 {now it is all over} 19. Rg1 (19. fxg3 $4 Nxg3#) 19... Bxf2 $1 20. Bxh5 Bxg1
21. Qxg1 Qe5 22. Bf3 Nxf3 23. Nxf3 Qh5+ {Black has a huge material advantage
and White's king is still weak. The game is practically over and Ulybin
converts his advantage with ease.} 24. Nh2 Rfe8 25. Nd4 Re5 26. Qg3 Rg5 27. Qe3
Qg6 28. Re1 h6 29. Ndf3 Rh5 30. Qf4 Rf5 31. Qc7 Qc6 32. Qg3 Qf6 33. Ng4 Qg6 34.
Nh4 Rh5 35. Kg2 Rxh4 0-1

