1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bd3 (5. Bb5 {Is the main
theoretical continuation} Bd6 6. c4 dxc4 7. d5 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. dxc6 bxa4 10.
O-O Ne7 {The end of the long forced line. Here White has two options 11.Nd2
and 11. Qa4. The modern engines didn't see anything wrong in Black's position.
I provide you with two recent examples where Black is doing well.} 11. Qxa4 (
11. Nbd2 Be6 12. Qxa4 Bd5 (12... c3 $5 {is probably slightly more accurate} 13.
bxc3 (13. Nc4 O-O 14. bxc3 Bd5 $11) 13... Bd5 $11) 13. Nxc4 Bxc6 14. Qd1 O-O
15. Nxd6 cxd6 {The weakness on d6 is compensated by Black's active pieces 0-1 
(79) Erdos,V (2615)-Jumabayev,R (2631) Abu Dhabi 2021}) 11... Rb8 12. a3 O-O
13. Qxc4 Rb5 (13... Be6 {this pawn sacrifice looks very promising} 14. Qxa6 Bd5
15. Nbd2 Ng6 $1 $17) 14. Bg5 Be6 15. Qc2 h6 {Black at least equalized here 0-1
(52) Harika,D (2511)-Maghsoodloo,P (2706) Kolkata 2021}) 5... Nb4 {I like this
move a lot} (5... Bg4) (5... Bd6) 6. Be2 (6. Bb5+ {This move doesn't pose any
problems} c6 7. Ba4 (7. Be2 Bf5 8. Na3 a5 9. c3 Na6 10. Nc2 Bd6 11. O-O Ne7 {
0-1 (59) Toufighi,H (2386)-Volkov,S (2628) Playchess. com INT 2006}) 7... Bd6
$11) (6. O-O Nxd3 7. Qxd3 Bd6 $11) 6... Bf5 7. Na3 Nc6 $1 {very tricky move.
Now Black's next move is Bxa3 against almost everything} 8. O-O (8. Nb1 {
makes a lot of sense, but White should admit that he can't play for an opening
advantage. Black can force the draw via} Nb4 $11 ({or continue the game after} 
8... Bd6)) 8... Bxa3 9. bxa3 Nge7 {Black gives his bishop pair, but now has a
long-term advantage. White's structure is ruined and it is not so easy to
prove enough compensation for that.} 10. Rb1 (10. Re1) 10... b6 11. Nh4 {
The beginning of the wrong plan, but it is not easy to suggest an improvement
for White.} Be4 12. f3 Bg6 13. f4 {This move weakens the structure even more.
It is pseudo-active and Black easily takes the initiative.} Be4 $1 14. f5 Qd6
15. g3 (15. f6 gxf6 16. Rb3 {I can't see White's compensation, but at least he
has some play.}) 15... O-O-O 16. Rb3 Qf6 (16... f6 {[%cal Rg7g5] I am not sure
why Volkov didn't play this simple move with an obvious advantage. Anyway, I
should admit that his way of handling the position was good enough.}) 17. Be3
Na5 18. Rc3 Nc4 $1 {very nice pawn sacrifice for freeing the -d5 square.} 19.
Bxc4 dxc4 20. Qg4 $2 {This move is a blunder} (20. Rxc4 Nd5 {just take a look
at White's pieces. All of them are somehow randomly placed.} 21. Bc1 Rhe8 $17)
20... Nd5 21. Qxe4 Rhe8 22. Qf3 Nxc3 $19 {Black is completely winning. Zaitsev
decides to play a few more moves, but they don't change the evaluation of the
position, and Volkov converts his advantage.} 23. Qa8+ Kd7 24. Qf3 Qc6 25. Qf2
Kc8 26. Nf3 Qe4 27. Re1 Qxf5 28. Qg2 Qd5 29. Qh3+ Kb8 30. Kf2 Qe4 31. Ne5 f6
32. Nf3 Qxc2+ 33. Kf1 Qd3+ 34. Kf2 Rxe3 0-1

