1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {You probably think that "The Exchange French"
is a way for White to make a draw, but the variation has its venom and it is
used quite successfully from some of the strongest players in the world. As we
will see this structure is not that simple to handle for Black.} 4. Nf3 $1 (4.
c4 {Is another way to handle the position, but here Black can put the bishop
on b4.} Bb4+ {0-1 (55) Safarli, E (2676)-Huzman, A (2571) Porto Carras 2018}) (
4. Bd3 {is not very good because it allows} Nc6 $1 5. c3 Bd6 {Black has good
chances to take the initiative in this line 0-1 (43) Manukian, A (2196)-Vidit,
S (2723) chess.com INT 2018}) 4... Nf6 {This position can be reached by
Petroff Defense as well.} (4... Nc6 5. Bb5 $1 Bd6 6. c4 dxc4 7. d5 a6 8. Ba4 b5
9. dxc6 {Is a long forced line, where Black needs to be very careful 1-0 (32)
Gelfand, B (2673)-Alekseev,E (2639) St Petersburg 2018}) (4... Bd6 5. c4 {
is possible}) 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. O-O {This is the first crossroad for White.
White's main idea in this line is to put his knight on e5 and to put some
pressure on Black's kingside. Another important positional idea is Nc3-e2
followed by Bf4. The rule in this position is that White wants to exchange the
dark-squared bishops and Black wants to exchange light-squared bishops.} (6.
Qe2+ {is very popular and poses some problems. I think this is the current
trend in the high-level games.}) 6... O-O 7. h3 $1 {The current trend in this
position. The French GM Etienne Bacrot is advocating for this line. White
makes a useful move and waits for Black to show his cards.} h6 {Black decides
to repeat White's play. The other continuations are examined in the next game.}
8. Re1 (8. Nc3 $1 {I think that this is the best move order. Now Black is
forced to break the symmetry. The threat is Nb5, so Black is almost forced to
play 8...c6} Nc6 (8... c6 9. Ne5 $1 {The point of White's idea. White manages
to install the knight on e5. Then Bf4, Qf3, Rae1, Ne2 is coming.}) 9. Nb5 {
seems slightly better for White}) 8... Re8 9. Nc3 c6 (9... Rxe1+ $5) 10. Ne5 $1
(10. Rxe8+ {If you think that White's position is super safe, I recommend you
to check the following miniature.} Nxe8 11. Ne5 Nd7 12. Bf4 Nf8 {White already
needs to be careful, because f7-f6 is coming.} 13. Qh5 Be6 14. Rb1 $4 {very
strange mistake by GM Nigel Short} f6 15. Ng6 Bf7 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 17. g4 (17. Qg4
$1 f5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. Nxf8 Nxd4 {leaves White in a worsе position, but
still alive}) 17... Ne4 $1 {Amazing win 0-1 (19) Short,N (2683)-Harikrishna,P 
(2664) Montreal 2007}) 10... Nbd7 11. Bf4 {Amazing position! It is still move
11, but it seems to me that Black is in serious trouble. At first, the engine
didn't see anything scary for Black, but if you give it more time, it starts
to understand that White has the initiative. White's plan is very simple: Qf3,
doubling the rooks on the e-file and transferring the c3-knight to the
kingside.} Qc7 $6 (11... Nf8 12. Qf3) 12. Qf3 $1 {the point of White's idea.
Black can't take on e5 without losing material.} Nxe5 (12... Re6 13. Re2 $16 {
[%cal Ra1e1]}) 13. dxe5 Rxe5 {a sad necessity} (13... Bxe5 14. Rxe5 $1 Rxe5 15.
Qg3 Nd7 16. Bxh6 $1 $18) 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. Re2 $1 (15. Bf5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 Bxc3
17. bxc3 Qd6 $13 {1-0 (44) Ehlvest, J (2536)-Manukian,A (2196) chess.com INT
2018}) 15... Bd7 16. Rae1 Bd6 17. Bf5 Bxf5 18. Qxf5 $16 {The rest is a matter
of technique. Of course, Black has some compensation for the exchange, but not
enough to maintain the ballance.} Qb6 19. Qd3 Rd8 20. b3 Bb4 21. Na4 Qa5 22. c3
Bd6 23. Qc2 b5 24. Nb2 Qxa2 25. c4 bxc4 26. bxc4 Rb8 27. Nd3 Qxc4 28. Qxc4 dxc4
29. Ne5 c3 30. Nxc6 Rb2 31. Rxb2 cxb2 32. Rb1 Ba3 33. Nxa7 Ne4 34. Nb5 Bc5 35.
Rxb2 g5 36. Rc2 Bb6 37. Kf1 Kg7 38. Nc3 Nf6 39. Ke2 h5 40. g3 Bd4 41. Nb5 Bb6
42. Rc6 Ba5 43. Nd4 Kg6 44. g4 hxg4 45. hxg4 Bb4 46. f3 Ba3 47. Nf5 Bb2 48. Kd3
Be5 49. Kc4 Kh7 50. Ra6 Kg6 51. Ne7+ Kg7 52. Nf5+ Kg6 53. Ne7+ Kg7 54. Ra5 Bc7
55. Rxg5+ Kf8 56. Nd5 Nxd5 57. Rxd5 Ke7 58. Rf5 f6 59. Kd5 Bb8 60. Rh5 Kf7 61.
Rf5 Ke7 62. Ke4 Ke6 63. Rb5 Bg3 64. Rb6+ Kf7 65. Kf5 1-0

