{[%evp 0,77,21,23,50,46,27,26,23,20,19,27,17,17,17,3,27,10,-16,-14,16,4,3,12,6,
-3,45,54,30,34,77,20,1,-13,28,-34,-27,-116,-25,-249,-13,0,0,-72,-72,-79,-62,
-84,79,-57,279,303,313,307,307,312,312,179,185,193,200,178,202,201,234,228,231,
200,212,156,180,169,225,229,375,414,546,690,715,576]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5
exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 Re8 {In this game, Black allows Bg5
} 8. Bg5 $1 h6 9. Bh4 {the pin on the diagonal is quite unpleasant for Black.}
Nbd7 (9... g5 10. Nxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Bf8 12. Qf3 {[%cal Rb1c3,Rc3e2,Re2g3] Do
not believe to your engine if he says 0.00. White's initiative is quite
serious and the position is probably just bad for Black.}) 10. Nc3 $1 {Once
again, White develops his knight on c3.} c6 11. Qd2 {To evaluate the position,
you can just compare the position of the bishops on c8 and h4.} Qc7 12. Rae1 $1
{The f-rook can be useful on the f-file} b6 13. Ne5 $1 {And again Ne5!} Bb7 (
13... Nxe5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qxh6 {game over!}) 14. f4 {the knight on e5 is a
monster. The situation in the centre is solid and White starts a devastating
attack} a6 15. g4 $1 c5 16. g5 hxg5 17. fxg5 cxd4 18. gxf6 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 (19.
fxg7 $1 $14) 19... Qxe5 20. Qg2 Qe3+ 21. Kh2 Qh6 22. Bg5 Qh8 (22... Qh5 $1 {
the computer finds some defense and even claims that Black has an advantage,
but we all know how hard it is to defend such positions in practice. My task
is not to critic the play of Bacrot, but to show you the main ideas of this
structure. For those who want to know the objective truth, I can recommend
checking the position after move 15.} 23. Ne2 Re5) 23. Rf4 $1 $18 Nxf6 (23...
dxc3 24. Rh4 $18) 24. Rxf6 Kf8 25. Rxb6 dxc3 26. Rxb7 Qh5 27. bxc3 Rac8 28. Qg4
Qxg4 29. hxg4 Rxc3 30. Bd2 {I'll leave you to enjoy Bacrot's technique without
comments.} Rc6 31. Kg3 Rce6 32. a4 g6 33. a5 Rc8 34. Kf4 Kg7 35. Be3 g5+ 36.
Kf3 Kh6 37. Rxf7 Rxe3+ 38. Kxe3 d4+ 39. Kf3 1-0

