{[%evp 0,100,20,13,25,22,22,18,41,25,44,24,24,24,13,17,17,17,14,18,3,4,-5,-10,
9,-6,27,6,30,40,63,19,64,37,33,40,34,27,27,27,39,31,49,23,46,28,44,17,34,28,41,
43,66,-16,18,-4,-20,-16,-7,-13,-20,-7,37,4,-38,-48,-30,-75,-75,-29,-13,-40,-86,
-165,-168,-95,-95,-95,-71,-86,-95,-103,-100,-79,-103,-116,-71,-73,-61,-66,-85,
-88,0,-47,-49,-114,-71,-122,-110,-366,-348,-348,-427]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3.
Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d3 Nf6 6. d4 d5 {This time we reach our tabiya, from
Petroff Defence} 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 $5 {Interesting
way to handle the position. We already saw that White usually put the knight
on c3, so why Black should try the same. Strangely enough, no other strong
player repeats Caruana's 10...Nc6.} 11. c3 g5 12. Bg3 (12. Nxg5 {This is
definitely the critical continuation. We can only guess if Caruana was
prepared for this position or he just bluffed his older opponent. In this case,
the sacrifice is not that strong, because White's knight can't enter the game
via Nc3-e2-g3} hxg5 13. Bxg5 Kg7 14. Qf3 Rh8 $1 {My engine claims that White
doesn't have enough compensation for the piece. I usually do not trust him,
but in this case, I decided to leave this question to the analysts.}) 12... Ne4
{I told you the plans of both sides are the same. The move Ne4 is usually good
for Black when it is possible.} 13. Bxd6 cxd6 $3 {The move which amazed me and
the reason why I choose this game. White doubled his pawns willingly.} 14. Nfd2
f5 {Black is defending the knight} 15. Na3 Be6 16. Nc2 Nxd2 $3 {another
non-trivial concept. Caruana exchanges his monstrous knight, but wins some
space on the kingside and prepares the kingside attack.} 17. Qxd2 f4 18. Rae1
Qf6 19. f3 {the computer says that this is a mistake, but I think 99% of us
will play this move without thinking. Engines are not bothered by f4-f3, but
for me, it looks super scary.} Rf7 20. Re2 Raf8 {All pieces should take part
in the game.} 21. Ne1 {What is Black's plan} Ne7 $1 {The knight is going to e3}
22. Bc2 a5 23. Bb3 Rg7 24. Qd3 Bd7 25. a4 Kh8 26. Qd2 h5 {White is without a
clear plan, while Black's idea is quite obvious} 27. Nd3 Nf5 28. Bxd5 Ne3 {
The game is practically over.} 29. Rxe3 fxe3 30. Qxe3 Bxa4 {the rest is a
matter of a simple technique} 31. Ra1 Re7 32. Qd2 Bb5 33. Rxa5 Bxd3 34. Qxd3
Re1+ 35. Kf2 Rfe8 36. Ra8 Qf4 37. Rxe8+ Rxe8 38. Qd1 Qxh2 39. Qd2 Qh4+ 40. Kf1
Qh1+ 41. Kf2 Qh4+ 42. Kf1 Ra8 43. Ke2 Ra1 44. Kd3 b5 45. c4 bxc4+ 46. Kxc4 Qf4
47. Qe2 Qc1+ 48. Kb5 Qc8 49. Kb6 Qb8+ 50. Kc6 Rc1+ 0-1

