1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. Qe2+ Qe7 (6... Be6 {
Black's hopes for equality are connected with this move.} 7. Ng5 Qe7 8. Nxe6
fxe6 {The critical position of the variation. I still prefer to be White here,
but some famous theoreticians claim equality for Black and I am not ready to
argue with them. I leave this position outside of this article because the
structure changed and it is not symmetrical anymore, but I will recommend you
to check the game ½-½ (49) Grischuk, A (2777)-Wang, H (2762) Ekaterinburg
2020}) 7. Qxe7+ Bxe7 (7... Kxe7 8. O-O Re8 9. Re1+ Kf8 10. Rxe8+ Kxe8 11. Nc3
c6 12. Bd2 h6 13. Re1+ Kf8 14. Ne5 (14. Ne2 {[%cal Rd2f4] is another option})
14... Nbd7 15. f4 $14 {1-0 (58) Carlsen,M (2838)-Akobian,V (2645) chess.com
INT 2017}) 8. Bf4 {This is exactly the type of position which one should avoid
against Magnus Carlsen. Risk-free advantage and slight initiative for White.
Let's check how the World Champion create one of his positional masterpieces.}
c6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bg4 12. Ne5 $1 {As simple as that - Ne5 is
always good in this structure} Be6 13. Nb3 a5 (13... Nbd7 {was suggested by
some commentators, but it doesn't change the objective evaluation of the
position. Black was scared of Na5 in an appropriate moment.}) 14. Nc5 $1 Bxc5
15. dxc5 Nbd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 {Let's stop and analyze the arising position.
White has a bishop pair in the open position, space advantage on the queenside,
and wonderful square for his bishop on d6. Magnus shows how one should handle
such positions, by limiting his opponent's pieces and then starting to improve
his position on both sides of the board.} 17. f3 $1 a4 18. Kf2 Be6 19. Bd6 Nd7
20. b4 axb3 21. axb3 $1 g6 22. g4 {Winning space on the queenside as well} b6
23. cxb6 {simple play is almost always the best} Nxb6 24. Kg3 Nd7 25. h4 Kg7
26. f4 d4 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 28. f5 gxf5 29. gxf5 Bd5 30. Re7 Ra7 31. Kf4 Rb7 32.
Be5+ Kf8 33. f6 {Another great game from the World Champion which shows the
danger to leave White with bishop pair in this structure.} 1-0

