{[%evp 0,9,18,14,43,27,29,30,28,18,18,13]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {
The Exchange variation has never enjoyed a good reputation, as it mainly looks
like an attempt to reach a draw without too many headaches. But for players
with black, it may be an irritating weapon, especially against a lower rated
opponent. When decades ago I confessed to an experienced Romanian trainer my
old desire (lasting ever since my teenage years and materialized only few
years ago) to include the French into my main repertoire, he answered: "I
don't even mention it is a passive opening, but just want to ask you, what you
would do against the Exchange?" Actually I believe the trainer was wrong in
both cases. The French can be treated according to each player's style (form
very passively to hyper-actively) while from the games against the Exchange
variation (most of them against players above 2400) I have a distinctly
positive score. But if this is true, it means that a player with good
understanding of the position can achieve at least the same results with white
as with black, so some detailed investigation is required. From all the
systems examined in these databases I have chosen this one to focus on the
sub-lines I consider most critical, as many games just show players pushing
pieces around with no clear idea nor ambition.} 4. Nf3 {The most natural move.}
({In the late '80s I was stunned about the excellent results obtained by the
Bulgarian IM Andonov with the exotic} 4. h3 {But this does not bother us too
much, as we can react exactly the same as in lines 14 and 15 below:} Nf6 5. Nf3
c5 6. Bb5+ ({After having wasted a tempo, White is not in time to transpose to
the aforementioned lines with} 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O {, as Black can play} cxd4 {
, reaching a confortable version of the French Isolani - if White manages to
retrieve the pawn, of course!}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 {once again reaching a
comfortable isolani position. This line generally compares favourably for
black to the system recommended in the database dedicated to 3.Nd2 c5, where
most typically Black needs to develop the knight to e7 instead of the optimal
f6-square.}) ({Actually the most popular move is} 4. Bd3 {, but after} c5 {
there is no effective way to avoid a transposition to the system recommended
in Lines 14 and 15.} 5. dxc5 (5. Qe2+ Be7 6. dxc5 {transposes to a comfortable
version of the Tarrasch 6.Qe2+ system, as the bishop is less active on d3 than
on b5:} Nf6 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nd2 Re8 9. Nb3 Nbd7 10. Nf3 Nxc5 $11) 5... Bxc5 6.
Ne2 {This original but not very active way of developing the knight is the
only justification for the previous move.} Nf6 7. O-O Nc6 {, with a
comfortable isolani.}) 4... Nf6 {I remember two high level examples in which
White (in both cases not 1.e4 players), being in need to reach a draw with
white for qualifying, played 1.d4 e6 2.e4 d5 3.exd5 and lost painfully. In
both cases Black went out of the symmetry on move 4:} ({Gurevich had been
among the leaders for most of the time at the 1990 Manila Interzonal. After
losing to Anand in the last but one round, he would have still qualified had
he drawn his last game. Unfortunately for him, his opponent needed to win.} 
4... Bg4 5. h3 Bh5 6. Be2 Bd6 7. Ne5 Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 Re8
11. Qg4 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 Ng6 13. Bg3 Nd7 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Qf3 {We can notice that
White has been mainly concerned with exchanging pieces. His position is still
OK, but soon he will push things too far.} c6 16. Qb3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 $6 axb6 18.
a3 Ne4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. Rfd1 b5 {, resulting in quite a promising ending with
a good knight versus a relatively bad bishop, Gurevich,M (2640)-Short,N (2610)
Manila (Izt) 1990 CBM 019 [Knaak,R] (0-1, 42)}) ({A similar situation arose in
a KO mini match some years later:} 4... Bd6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. c3 Bg4 7. O-O Nge7 8.
Bg5 Qd7 9. Bh4 O-O-O 10. Nbd2 Rde8 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 h5 {with a strong
kingside initiative, Andersson,U (2625)-Rozentalis,E (2600) Tilburg KO 1993  
(0-1, 32).}) ({The only way in which Black should not break the symmetry at
this stage is} 4... c5 $6 {, as this allows White to speed up his development
and gain the initiative:} 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 $16) 5. Bg5 {The main
lines are this move and 5.Bd3 examined below.} (5. Be2 {is even less effective
than 5.Bd3 against our planned} c5 {, as the later Re1 will be without check:}
6. O-O Nc6 7. Re1 Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bb5+ Be6 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 Qb6 {
and White already has some stability problems.}) ({Developing both knights in
front of the pawns does not work out well.} 5. Nc3 {would make more sense
after Bd3 or Be2.} Bd6 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. Bg5 c6 9. h3 Bh5 10. Re1 Nbd7 {
and Black's position is slightly more flexible.}) (5. c4 Bb4+ {basically
transposes to Line 16, 4.c4.}) *

