1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {This looks like an active
move, but it also exposes the bishop and is likely to leave Black with the
bishops' pair.} Be6 $5 {I have twice used this move, winning both times. I
drew my inspiration from a game won by Vaganian against my first opponent.} ({
If Black prefers to play safely, the popular} 5... Be7 {is quite OK. The
following game was played via the Petroff 5.d3 Nf6 6.d4 d5 move order:} 6. Bd3
O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. c3 c6 10. Qc2 h6 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Be5 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Nf4 $132 {Grischuk,A (2785)-Dominguez Perez,L (2757) Elancourt 2013 CBM
157 [ChessBase Website] (1/2-1/2, 30)}) 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4 (8. Bf4
g5 9. Be3 {is hardly an improvement:} Ng4 10. Nf1 (10. O-O Nxe3 11. fxe3 g4 12.
Ne1 Qg5) 10... Nxe3 11. Nxe3 Qf6 12. c3 O-O-O $36 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] /\.
..g4, ...h5-h4.}) ({During the second game I was slightly worried by} 8. Be3 {
, when Black does not have anything better than} Bd6 $11 {, after which the
extra tempo (...h7-h6) in a perfectly symmetrical position is not enough to
hope to unbalance the position if White displays a minimum of care. But these
worries were of a subjective nature, of course, since from the theoretical
point of view Black should be more than happy with the result of the opening.})
8... g5 9. Bg3 Nh5 10. Qe2 $146 {During the first game I had the feeling that
my opponent had done some preparation after her old game, but her last move
does not change the character of the position radically.} ({Vaganian's game
went} 10. c3 Bg7 11. Qc2 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Qf6 13. Nf1 O-O-O 14. Ne3 Kb8 15. Bf5 h5
$15 {Skripchenko (2460)-Vaganian (2623) Germany 2004 Skripchenko,A (2460)
-Vaganian,R (2623) Germany 2004 (0-1, 78)}) 10... Nxg3 11. hxg3 $146 {It is
always a good question which file White should open.} ({The first game went} 
11. fxg3 $5 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gh1f1,Gf1f7] <->f White opens the f-file in order
to try taking advantage of the weakness of the f5-square.} Bg7 {In principle,
Black would like to castle long, but it is better to keep some mystery with
respect to the final decision.} 12. O-O $6 {Almira played this after a long
period of thought. I thought that White should prepare a plan based on c2-c3,
Nd2-b3c5, dxc5 and Nd4, but this seems not so easy to implement.} (12. Nb3 c5
$1) (12. Qf2 Qe7 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Nb3 Kb8 15. c3 Qd6 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Qc6
18. Rac1 g4 $1 19. Nh4 h5 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. Bxf5 d4 $17) ({It is probably best
to prepare a slower attack with} 12. c3 Qe7 13. O-O O-O-O 14. b4 Kb8 15. Nb3
Rde8 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. bxc5 Bc8 18. Qc2 c6 $13 {Strategically, Black is doing
great, but due to the castling on opposite sides the position remains sharp.})
12... g4 13. Nh4 {The most principled continuation. White sacrifices a pawn
for the initiative. It will turn out that Black is in time to complete his
development with at least some advantage.} (13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qg5 15. Rae1
O-O 16. c3 c5 $15) 13... Bxd4+ 14. Kh1 Qg5 15. Ng6 (15. Bf5 O-O-O 16. Bxe6 fxe6
{[%csl Rd2] XNd2}) (15. Nf5 Bxb2 16. Rab1 Bc3 {[%csl Rd2]}) 15... Rg8 16. Nb3 (
16. Nf4 Qe5 17. Rae1 O-O-O 18. c3 Qxe2 19. Rxe2 Be5 $15) 16... Bb6 ({I thought
that there was no need for radical measures such as} 16... Bxb2 $5 17. Rab1 Bc3
18. Nf4 Qe5 19. Qf2 Rf8 $15) 17. Nf4 O-O-O ({Even stronger than} 17... Qe5 {
, when in Skripchenko,A (2429)-Marin,M (2583) Douglas 2014 (0-1, 40), White
could have hoped for equality after} 18. Rae1 {due to her complete development.
}) 18. a4 a5 (18... a6 19. a5 Ba7 20. Bxa6 $1 bxa6 $2 21. Qxa6+ Kb8 22. Qb5+
Kc8 23. a6 Nb6 24. Qc6 $18) 19. Nxe6 (19. Qe1 Qe5) (19. Qd2 Ne5 20. Nxa5 $2 Nc4
$1 $19) 19... fxe6 20. Qxe6 Rde8 21. Qf5 c6 $17 {Black has the better bishop
and the more active and safer king.}) 11... Bg7 12. c3 {[%csl Gd4]
Consolidating d4.} Qf6 {I kept playing according to the plans I was familiar
with.} ({But the radical} 12... c5 {, activating the bishop g7, was an
important alternative. During the game I did not seriously consider it because
of} 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Bb5+ {, but it seems that Black can safely give up the
right to castle:} Ke7 {The king feels safe here in short term. Later an
artificial castling with Rhe8 and Kf8 suggests itself.} 15. O-O-O ({This is
the most principled continuation, but a safer one is} 15. O-O a6 16. Qe3 Qc7
17. Be2 Rhe8 $11) (15. Nd4 Qb6 {does not make much of a difference.}) 15... Qb6
16. Nd4 a6 {Paradoxically, it will soon be the white king which will have to
endure the pressure of the g7-bishop and its colleagues.} 17. Nxe6 (17. Bd3
Bxd4 18. cxd4 Nxd3+ 19. Qxd3 Kf6 $1 {[%cal Ge6f5,Ga8c8] /\ Bf5}) (17. Nf5+ Kf6
18. Nxg7 Kxg7 {only helps the king to get away from the centre.} 19. Bd3 Rhe8
20. Qe3 Nxd3+ 21. Qxd3 d4 $36 22. cxd4 Qa5 $40 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Ge6f5]} 23. a3
$2 Rac8+ 24. Kb1 Bf5 $19) 17... fxe6 18. Bd3 Na4 $36 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3]}) 13. Nb3
{Not willing to give me a second chance to break the centre.} O-O-O 14. O-O-O (
{I planned to meet} 14. Na5 {[%cal Gd3a6] (threatening Ba6) with} Bg4 {[%csl
Ga6] , clearing the sixth rank for defensive purposes and the e-file for
active operations.}) 14... Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1] I could not refrain from ensuring
my queenside against the aforementioned attack while also creating a nasty pin.
} ({But maybe the last move is slightly premature, as Black could first
advance his h-pawn:} 14... h5 15. Rde1 h4 $132 16. Ne5 $6 hxg3 17. Rxh8 Rxh8
18. fxg3 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Qe7 20. Nd4 Kb8 $15 {[%csl Ge5,Gg3] x g3, e5}) 15. Rde1
h5 16. Nbd2 {Too passive.} ({White should have taken advantage of my move
order with} 16. Qe3 $5 {, since I was lacking the option ...g5-g4 followed by .
..Bh6. I planned} Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Bf6 {, followed by ...h5-h4,
thinking that the passed h-pawn would become dangerous later. But White seems
to have a way to neutralise Black's chances for a better ending:} 19. Bf5 Kb8
20. Rh3 h4 21. f4 $1 gxf4 22. gxh4 Rh5 $1 {An important intermediate move,
forcing the bishop to occupy a unfortunate square.} (22... Rxh4 23. Rxh4 Bxh4
24. Rh1 Be7 25. Rh7 $36) 23. Bg4 Rxh4 24. Rxh4 Bxh4 25. Rh1 Be7 26. Bxd7 (26.
Rh7 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rf6h7]}) 26... Rxd7 $11 {White's rook's activity
compensates for the irrelevant extra pawn.}) 16... h4 ({I once again refrained
from breaking with} 16... c5 {, this time not without considering it seriously.
I seem to have misevaluated the position after} 17. Qe7 Be6 $1 18. Qxf6 Bxf6
19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Be7 21. f4 gxf4 22. gxf4 {, when I overestimated the
positional threat f4-f5. After} Rdg8 23. f5 Bd7 24. Re2 Rg3 $36 {Black has a
strong kingside initiative while the white pawns are not too much of a threat
and potentially weak in the long run.}) 17. Qe7 (17. gxh4 {would clear the
g-file for my rooks, for instance:} gxh4 18. Qe7 Rdg8 $15) 17... hxg3 18. Qxf6
(18. Rxh8 {offers Black a pleasant choice between two similar endings with or
without rooks on the board.} Rxh8 ({During the game I was more inclined to
avoid mass simplifying with} 18... Bxh8 19. fxg3 Be6 20. Qxf6 Bxf6 $15) 19.
Qe8+ {I was afraid my winning chances would not be too high after} Rxe8 20.
Rxe8+ Qd8 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. fxg3 Bf6 $15 {but the bishop pair and the
weakness of the doubled pawns offer Black a long-term advantage.}) 18... Bxf6
19. fxg3 Be6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg5g4] Black plans ...g5-g4 with an obvious
advantage, even though converting it into a win was a long process, Vedmediuc,
S (2437)-Marin,M (2580) Mamaia 2015 (0-1, 63).} *

