{[%evp 0,32,36,36,44,36,36,32,26,-54,-52,-38,-31,-37,-37,-22,-9,-61,-61,-61,
-50,-68,-33,-33,9,36,37,-27,31,0,26,11,21,50,26]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5
exd5 4. c4 {From the point of view of the way I have built this repertoire,
this is a psychologically unpleasant move. For once we have to fight against
the French Isolani ourselves! But actually, the extra tempo resulting from
reversed colours rarely turns an equal position into a better one for White.
What is entirely satisfactory for Black many times is just slightly
dissapointing for White. Still, some concrete examining is called for, as
players like GM Miezis use this as their main line against the French.} Bb4+ {
Following the pattern of the 3.Nd2 c5 system, where White usually plays Bb5 (+)
.} 5. Nc3 {The most active way to parry the check.} ({Simplifying with} 5. Bd2
{offers less chances to maintain the tension.} Bxd2+ 6. Nxd2 (6. Qxd2 $6 Nf6 7.
Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 (8. Nc3 Re8+ 9. Be2 Bg4 10. O-O dxc4 {causes White some
problems.}) 8... Ne4 9. Qc2 Bf5 $36 {Noirot,L-Avram,S Zalaegerszeg 1988 (0-1,
16)}) 6... Nf6 7. Ngf3 O-O 8. Be2 Bg4 9. O-O Nc6 10. h3 Bh5 11. Rc1 Re8 12.
cxd5 Nb4 13. Bb5 Re7 14. Qb3 Nbxd5 15. Rfe1 c6 16. Bc4 Nb6 $11 {Miezis,N (2532)
-Ehlvest,J (2638) Dhaka 2001 (1/2-1/2, 22)}) (5. Nd2 {is too passive to be
challenging.} Ne7 $5 6. Ngf3 O-O 7. a3 Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nf5 $11) 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 {
As we know from our own isolani lines, this is the best way to develop the
king's knight.} ({It makes little sense to imitate the main 3... c5 line,
where Black HAS to develop the knight to e7.} 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Nge2 dxc4 8. Bxc4
c5 $5 {This is the kind of move White would not consider in the position with
reversed colours, as after the pawn exchange it would just lead to equality.}
9. a3 (9. d5 Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6 11. b3 (11. Qd3 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 a6 13. a4 b5) 11...
a6 12. a3 Ba5 13. a4 Bf5 $132) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Be6 12. Bd3 (
12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. O-O Nc6) 12... Bf5 13. O-O (13. Bxf5 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxf5 15.
O-O Nc6 $15) 13... Bxd3 14. Qxd3 {Miezis,N (2519)-Luther,T (2545)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (1-0, 36)} Nd5 15. Ng3 Nc6 16. Nf5 Qf6 17. Rb1 b6 $11)
6... O-O 7. a3 $5 {An interesting try to keep the tension at the cost of a
move.} (7. Bd3 dxc4 {transposes below.}) (7. Be2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bg4 9. O-O (9.
Be3 c5 10. dxc5 (10. d5 Nbd7 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Ne5 $17) 10... Qxd1+ 11.
Rxd1 Nbd7 12. c6 bxc6 {The double pin and Black's activity in general
compensate for the relative weakness on c6.}) 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxd4 11. Qxb7
{Otherwise White would at most have just reasonable compensation for the pawn
as Black has normal development and no weaknesses.} Qxc4 12. Qxa8 Bd6 {UPDATE
- January 2020} 13. Qxa7 (13. Qf3 {does not parry the threat while also
refraining from grabbing a pawn.} Bxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qxf1 15. Rb1 Qc4 16. Bf4 c5
17. Rd1 Nbd7 {with just reasonable compensation for the pawn in Vlassov,N  
(2384)-Bharat,K (2304) Ahmedabad 2019 (0-1, 84)}) 13... Bxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qxf1 15.
f3 Qe1 16. Qxc7 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Qe1+ {1/2-1/2 Gleizerov,E (2557)-Ulybin,M (2533)
Stockholm 2012 There is a chance that this was a pre-agreed draw. as to my
knowledge the opponents are good friends, but the line is objectively correct.}
) (7. Bg5 Re8+ 8. Be2 dxc4 9. O-O Be6 10. d5 Bg4 11. Bxc4 Nbd7 12. h3 Bxf3 13.
Qxf3 h6 $15) 7... Re8+ 8. Be3 ({UPDATE - January 2020} 8. Be2 $2 {just loses a
pawn due to the pin.} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ne4 10. Bb2 dxc4 11. O-O Nd6 12. Ne5 Be6
$17 {Kazakov,K (2369)-Kazhgaleyev,M (2578) Almaty 2019 (½-½, 82) Chapter
16-4.c4}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ng4 ({ANother way of fighting against White's
central structure is} 9... Bf5 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Nb6 12. c5 Nc4 13. Bg5 h6
14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Re1 b6 $11) 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. cxd5 (11. Bd3 Na5 $17 {Borsos,B 
(2350)-Bareev,E (2590) Dortmund 1990 (0-1, 29)}) 11... Na5 $5 $146 12. Rb1 Bf5
13. Rb4 Be4 14. Bb5 (14. c4 c6 $1 15. dxc6 $2 Nxc6 16. Rb2 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nxd4
$1 $17) 14... Re7 15. O-O Nxe3 16. fxe3 Qxd5 $11 {Black's piece pressure
compensates for the massive white centre.} *

