1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 {This is a major
tabiya of the Winawer. Traditionally, White chooses between the main and the
most principled 7.Qg4, the simple 7.Nf3 and the cunning side pawn moves 7. h4
and 7.a4.Let's briefly discuss the merits of the theoretical moves and the
general plans of both sides here.7. Qg4 attacks the g7-pawn and forces an
immediate decision from us. Against it, I recommend sacrificing the g7 pawn
with Qc7.} 7. Qg4 {This is by far the main move and understandably so. White
immediately goes after our weakest spot in the position - the g7 pawn.} Qc7 8.
Qxg7 {8.Bd3 is another move here.} (8. Bd3 c4 {It is also cd4 but it leads to
more forcing endgame, which is not exactly what we have in plan.} 9. Be2 Qa5 {
looks counter-intuitive at first but if it works, it works!} 10. Bd2 Nf5 11. a4
{A logical move for White, stopping Qa4.} (11. h4 {Pushing the pawn to h5 is
always a plan to reckon with.} Qa4 {I like this move for the strategic purpose
of blocking the a4, Bc1-Ba3 plan. Here I think we can afford to spend a tempo
on it too.} 12. Bd1 {Guarding the pawn on c2.} Nc6 {We develop as usual here.})
(11. Nf3 Qa4 {Nh4-Nf5 is not a big threat, but if White manages to get a4 in
as well, in the long run, we are facing a tough defense, as White will lock up
the center with f4 and activate the c1-bishop via a3.} 12. Ra2 {Preparing Nh4.}
Nc6 13. Nh4 Rg8 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. Qh4 h6 {With effortless play, especially now
that Bc1-Ba3 is not on the cards. We are rock solid and in the long run, g7-g5
is our idea.}) 11... Nc6 12. Nf3 Bd7 {It is also possible to go for the
b5-bxa4 idea, but it is not necessary.} 13. O-O {This is what Sergey Karjakin
played in an online game. His lesser-known opponent showed good understanding
of the Winawer!} O-O-O 14. Rfb1 f6 {and the black player even managed to win
this game! Karjakin-Livaic, online 2020.}) 8... Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2 Nbc6
11. f4 dxc3 12. Qd3 (12. Nxc3 {This is very conscientious and highly critical.}
Nd4 13. Bb2 {The main move, defending the c3-knight and preparing to castle
long.} (13. Qd3 {This is another serious move.} Nef5 14. Bb2 Bd7 15. O-O-O Rc8
{Black makes all the useful moves. The question is, if the knight on d4 is an
asset or a liability? Both, of course.} 16. Kb1 Qb6 17. Ka2 Qa5 18. Qd2 {
[%cal Gc3e4]} Qc5 19. Bd3 b5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4]}) 13... Bd7 14. O-O-O
Ndf5 {This holds in some correspondence games. The following line is more or
less forced.} 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. Bxb5+ Kf8 {White has the bishop pair and a pawn,
but his queen is out of play for now and Black will try to get something going
on the queenside.} 17. Bd3 Qc5 18. Rd2 Ne3 {This position needs more
investigation, but people held in correspondence chess.} 19. Qh3 {White also
tried including 19.Qh6+ Ke8 , but Black held there too.} (19. Qh6+ Ke8 20. Qh3
b5 {Giving up a pawn with a check to open the b-file.} 21. Bxb5+ Kd8 22. Re1 (
22. Bd3 {This loses spectacularly.} Rb8 23. Re1 Rxb2 24. Kxb2 d4 {Black will
just mate.}) 22... Nxg2 {Regaining one pawn.} 23. Rxg2 Rxg2 24. Qxg2 Qxb5 25.
Re3 Qc4 26. Qf3 Nf5 {With a beautiful knight that proved enough compensation
for the pawn in 1/2 (34) Hrubcik,M (2406)-Doren,D (2366) ICCF email 2017.})
19... Rc8 20. Re1 Nc4 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. c3 {In this position, Black just wants
to push b5, a5 and b4, while White will push g4-f5. Black's king looks weaker
to me, but the correspondence boys managed to draw here.} Ke8 {Intending to
meet g4 with Rd8!.} 23. Red1 {This leads to a long forced line which ends in
Black making a draw. Barely, but making it.} (23. Qf3 b5 24. g4 a5 25. f5 Nd5
26. Rf1 Rc7 27. Rfd1 Rc8 28. h3 Qe3 29. Rf1 Qxf3 30. Rxf3 Rh8 {And Black held
this pawn down endgame in 1/2 (48) Gorzkiewicz,L (2462)-Garau,B (2352) ICCF
email 2017.}) 23... b5 24. g4 a5 25. f5 Qxe5 {Black has to get distracted and
defend.} 26. Qh4 exf5 27. gxf5 Qxf5 {And Black holds his own in further
complications:} 28. a4 b4 29. Re1 f6 30. Rf2 Qg5+ 31. Qxg5 Rxg5 32. Rxf6 Rg2 {
This endgame holds - there is too little material left.}) (12. h4 Bd7 (12... d4
$2 13. h5 b6 14. h6 Bb7 15. Qxg8+ $1 {This is an important trick which we
should remember all the time.} Nxg8 16. h7) 13. h5 O-O-O 14. Qd3 d4 15. h6 Rg6
16. h7 Rh8 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Bc6 {This usually just ends with us picking
up the h7-pawn, White trading the light-squared bishop for the f5-knight and
some sort of a draw in the opposite-colored bishop endgame. 1/2 (40) Kulaots,K
(2560) -Radjabov,T (2759) Dortmund 2019.}) 12... d4 {This line is the reason
why the Winawer started going through a renaissance almost a decade ago, as
the lines arising after 12...Bd7 have always been considered quite risky and
good enough only in faster time control.} 13. Nxd4 (13. h4 {This is not the
right moment to play h4, which could and should have been played a move
earlier. Here we can transpose with 13...Bd7 to what we know, but also play b6
which is completely fine as well.} Bd7 14. h5 O-O-O {Transposes}) (13. Ng3 {
This was one of the moves that were tried initially, using the fact that Black
weakened the e4-square, but all White gets is a check.} Bd7 14. Ne4 O-O-O 15.
Nd6+ Kb8 16. Rb1 b6 17. Nxf7 Rdf8 18. Nd6 Nf5 19. Nxf5 Rxf5 {And next up is a
brutal sac on e5!}) 13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bd7 15. Rg1 Nf5 16. Qf2 Qc6 {White is
ready for g2-g4, so the queen comes to rescue!} 17. Bd3 {The main move,
although there is an alternative.} (17. g4 {This is met with} Qe4+ 18. Qe2 {
[%cal Gg8g1] Now the knight no longer hangs and we can retreat.} Qd5 19. Bg2
Qc5 20. Qf2 {Forced.} Nd4 {Also forced, as the endgame would be bad, because
the b7-pawn was hanging after 20...Qxf2 21. Kxf2 Rxg4} 21. Be4 {The only move
as well.} O-O-O {With the idea to go Bc6 next, Black is completely fine here.})
17... Qd5 {Ready to meet g4 with Nd4 and otherwise to intend to get the bishop
on the long diagonal with Bc6.} 18. Rb1 {The main theoretical move, but there
are alternatives.} (18. Bxf5 {is a harmless attempt to play for equality
shamelessly. Not very impressive.} exf5 19. Be3 O-O-O 20. Qf3 Qc4 {and White
drew a bunch of correspondence games here. Black can choose to trade queens or
keep them with Qc4, in both cases with complete dominance on the light squares
and very little things to worry about.}) (18. a4 {This move, with the idea
Ra3-xc3, is very sensible.} O-O-O 19. Ra3 Kb8 20. Rxc3 Bxa4 {One drawback of
having the pawn on a4 for White is that we can now grab it.} 21. Qc5 (21. Ra3 {
This can be met with} b5 {which looks quite desperate but does serve the need
of covering the a7 pawn.}) 21... Qd7 22. Qb4 Bc6 23. g3 {We are following some
correspondence game.} Nd4 24. Kf2 Qd5 $44) 18... Bc6 {The long diagonal is
where the bishop belongs.} 19. Rb3 O-O-O 20. Rxc3 Kb8 {This is one of the main
positions of the entire Qg4 system} 21. g4 (21. Qc5 Rxg2 {This led to a draw
in Duda-Bartel 2015.} 22. Qxd5 Rxg1+ 23. Kf2 Bxd5 24. Kxg1 Rg8+ {The endgame
is equal.} 25. Kf1 Ne7 {The easiest, avoiding the trade.}) (21. Rc5 {This
forces a strong reply.} Qa2 22. Rxc6 bxc6 23. Qc5 Rxd3 24. cxd3 Rxg2 {This led
to a draw in Ganguly-Shulman 2011.}) 21... Nd4 22. Rg3 Qh1+ 23. Bf1 {The
ambitious attempt.} (23. Qf1 {This allows easy simplifications.} Nf3+ 24. Kf2
Qxh2+ 25. Qg2 Qxg2+ 26. Rxg2 Ne1 {Easier than Nd4, which also eventually does
it.} 27. Rg3 Nxd3+ 28. cxd3 Rh8 {This is completely drawn. With White having
no passed pawns, the extra pawn is not so relevant in this opposite-colored
bishop endgame.}) 23... b6 {Preparing to meet Be3 with Nf3+. A very important
move!} 24. a4 {A nasty little move, introducing the idea of Ba3-Bd6 and also
preparing Rgd3 which here would have been met with Bb5!. Black must act fast.}
(24. Bb2 Be4 25. a4 {Here we can include Rh8 h3, but the important idea to
know is:} Rd5 26. Ba3 Rc8 {This was all played in Leko-Caruana 2012.} 27. Bd6+
Kb7 28. Rxc8 Kxc8 {Fabiano included a check here before capturing, which was
bad.} 29. Rc3+ Kd7 {Fabiano must have been scared of this position, but Black
is ok here.} 30. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4e7]} (30. Rc7+ Ke8 31. Rc8+ Kd7 32. Rc7+ $11)
30... Nxc2+ {This is important:} 31. Rxc2 Rd1+ 32. Kxd1 Qxf1+ {with a draw:})
24... Qe4+ {It is important to distract the rook from g3 , as the immediate 24.
..Qd5 fails to 25.Bg2!} 25. Rge3 Qd5 {The two pawns are hanging and 26.Ba3
allows a mate in two after Nf3+.} 26. Red3 Qa5 {Another only move,
nicely-getting out of the pin. 26...Qe4+? would leave us without ideas after
27.Kd1!} 27. Ba3 {The show must go on. Bd6 is a lethal threat.} Nb5 28. Qd2 {
Attacking the rook on d8 and diffusing the a5-e1 pin at the same time. But now
we just trade everything and end up in a completely equal endgame.} Rxd3 29.
Rxd3 Nxa3 30. Rxa3 Qxd2+ 31. Kxd2 Rxg4 {The smoke has cleared up and we are
still a pawn down. However, all of White's pawns are quite weak, which gives
us enough counterplay for a draw.} *

