1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. a4 Qc7 8. Nf3
h6 {This is sort of a prophylaxis against h4-h5-h6 and that's the most obvious
plan for White.} 9. h4 b6 $1 {Once again with the idea of Ba6} 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11.
Bd3 (11. Be2 Bc8 $1 {You shouldn't be too worried about losing this tempo as
White also lost a move with Be2} 12. a5 (12. O-O Ba6 13. Bb5+ Bxb5 14. axb5 {
Once again it transposes to h4 systems} a6) 12... Ba6 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qe2
cxd4 15. O-O $1 Qc4 16. Qxc4 dxc4 17. Nxd4 Nd5 $11) 11... Nbc6 12. O-O c4 13.
Be2 a5 $1 {Not the only way to play this line but it's quite direct and if you
know it you can easily surprise your opponent.} (13... f6 $6 {I Would love to
make this work but because White has played a4 now he gets an idea with Ba3-d6}
14. Ba3 $1 $14 {[%cal Ga3d6]}) 14. Ba3 Na7 15. h5 (15. Bxe7 $6 Kxe7 16. h5 Rag8
$1 17. Nh4 Kd8 18. Bg4 Nc8 $10) 15... Qd8 $1 {Prophalaxis against Bd6 also
intending to take on e7 with the queen if white plays Be7} 16. Qd2 b5 17. axb5
(17. g4 bxa4 18. Bc5 Nb5 19. Qe3 a3 20. Nd2 g6 21. hxg6 fxg6 $10) 17... Nxb5
18. Bc5 Nc6 19. Rfe1 (19. Ra2 Nb8 20. Rfa1 Bc6 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black is able to
get rid to this bishop and after that I don't see any problems for black.})
19... Nb8 $1 {with the idea of Na6} 20. Qf4 Na6 21. Qg3 Rg8 22. Bd6 Nac7 $1 23.
Nh4 (23. Bc5 Na6 $10) 23... Nxd6 24. exd6 Nb5 25. Bf3 (25. f4 Qb8 26. f5 Qxd6
$10) 25... Bc6 26. Ng6 Qxd6 27. Ne5 Nxc3 28. Re3 Ne4 29. Bxe4 dxe4 $44 {
Although White has some compensation but holding this shouldn't be too
difficult for Black.} *

