1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. Bd2 Qa4 8. Nf3
c4 9. h4 Nc6 10. h5 h6 11. g4 Bd7 12. Nh4 O-O-O 13. f4 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gg4,Gh5]
This is a type of structure we should avoid with Black.} Nge7 14. Be3 g6 15.
hxg6 fxg6 16. Be2 Rdf8 17. Kd2 $1 {The king sits snugly here. Best square for
the king.} Nd8 18. Qb1 Ndc6 19. Qb2 Rf7 20. Rh2 $5 {It seemed as if the rook
would come to b1 to attack, but White figures out that the real targets lie on
the kingside, so he decides to double the rooks down the h-file.} Rhh7 21. Rah1
Rhg7 22. Nf3 Ng8 23. Nh4 Nge7 24. Rf2 Rh7 25. Nf3 Ng8 26. Bf1 {Transferring
the bishop to the h3-c8 diagonal.} Rf8 27. Bh3 Rhf7 {Black has left a very
limited space and no counterplay on the kingside. Unless and until White
breaks on the kingside, Black can not do anything on the kingside.} 28. Rhf1
Nge7 29. Nh4 Qa5 30. a4 $1 Qd8 {Bringing the queen back into the game.} (30...
Qxa4 31. Ra1 $18) 31. Qa3 b6 32. Qc1 Kb7 33. Qe1 Rh7 $2 {[%csl Rf5] Finally
Black makes a mistake and lets white push f5} 34. f5 $1 {An extremely strong
break.} exf5 35. gxf5 gxf5 36. Bxf5 Nxf5 37. Nxf5 Rxf5 38. Rxf5 Bxf5 39. Rxf5
$16 {The material is still the same, but with the strong passed pawn in the
centre and with more active pieces White is pushing.} 1-0

