{[%evp 0,9,39,28,28,22,42,6,6,-9,-9,-6] For this lecture, I have prepared a
selection of games that will help you grasp the most important concepts and
plans for both sides in the Advance French structure.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{White grabs space in the center, so Black should counterattack as fast as
possible. The first move is very easy.} c5 $1 {Of course, Black tries to put
pressure on d4, and normally White continues with} 4. c3 {Consolidating the
position. Black usually increases the pressure on d4 with} Nc6 {and White
replies with} 5. Nf3 {Now, we will divide the study of this middlegame taking
into account 4 different scenarios: a) Black changes the pawn structure by
playing .. .f6. b) Black changes the pawn structure by playing ...c4. c) Black
keeps the tension and doesn't change the pawn structure d) Black changes the
pawn structure by playing ...cxd4. We are going to focus on scenarios a) and b)
, as they are the most common ones in the modern practice.} Bd7 (5... Qb6 {
is another major branch of theory} 6. a3 c4 (6... Bd7 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 {
represents scenario d)})) 6. Be2 f6 (6... Nge7 7. O-O Ng6 {is case c) where
Black keeps the tension}) 7. O-O fxe5 *

