{[%evp 0,34,39,31,28,22,19,6,6,-9,-9,-6,-3,-19,6,6,6,-11,10,-3,-4,-34,-2,-17,
26,8,21,-27,-27,-34,-43,-35,-35,-31,-31,-41,-29] I believe this game is a nice
starting point as it illustrates the typical plans and ideas in the structure.
} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O fxe5 8. dxe5
{[%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f7]} Qc7 (8... Nh6 {Modern theory recommends developing the
knight first since it is a more flexible move order: Black does not hurry to
put the queen on c7}) 9. Na3 $2 {[%cal Ga3b5] This move is only good once
Black already castled queenside! However, knowing Kupreichik's aggressive
style, it comes as no great surprise} a6 (9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Bb5 $44
O-O-O {It is not clear where White's compensation lies}) 10. Bf4 Nh6 $1 {
[%cal Gh6f7,Gf8e7] The standard way to play: Black intends to develop with Nf7,
Be7 and then, depending on the opponent's actions, decide which side to castle.
} (10... Nge7 {[%cal Ye7g6] also perfectly playable} 11. Nc2 Ng6 12. Bg3 Be7
13. Ne3 {Black needs to be really careful or the game might end up in a
disaster rather quickly. For example,} O-O $2 (13... Qd8 {[%cal Rg3c7] Black
always has to be on the lookout for tactics against the queen. Next, he can
continue developing normally}) 14. Nxd5 {[%cal Rg3c7]} exd5 15. Qxd5+ Kh8 16.
e6 $18) (10... Nf6 {The problem with this move is that it does not have a
suitable square after} 11. Re1 Ne4 (11... Nh5 12. Bg5) 12. Bd3 {[%cal Yd3e4]})
(10... h6 {[%cal Gg7g5] can be played too but, in my opinion, it is too slow}
11. h3 (11. Nh4 Nge7 12. Bh5+ Kd8 {can be tricky to play as Black in practice})
11... g5 12. Bh2 Nge7 13. Nc2 Bg7 14. Ne3 $14) 11. Nc2 (11. Bxh6 {is not
advisable} gxh6 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh8g8] White opened a line against his
king, gave up the bishop pair and has problems defending e5}) 11... Nf7 {
A critical position! White has to choose a course of action and this will
determine the dynamics of the game} (11... Be7 {[%cal Gh6f5] is preferable
because it keeps open ideas with Nf5}) 12. c4 (12. b4 $1 {[%csl Bc2,Bf3,Gd4] A
fantastic move that aims to open the d4 square for the knights!} c4 (12... cxb4
13. Nxb4 (13. cxb4 Nfxe5) 13... Ncxe5 (13... Nxb4 14. cxb4 Bxb4 15. Rc1 $44 {
[%cal Gf3d4,Ge2d3] White has a great compensation for the pawn: all his pieces
are on active positions and have targets to shoot at. Black is going to have
problems along the light squares after Nd4, Bd3}) 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bh5+ $18 {
[%cal Gf1e1,Gb4d5] White has a huge initiative after Re1 and possibly Nd5 next
move}) (12... b6 $2 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Ge8c8] once b6 is played Black can never
castle on the queenside} 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. Ne3 $16 {[%cal Ge3d5]}) 13. Nfd4 $16
) 12... d4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gb2b4] A very ambitious approach- Black secures a
passed pawn and a better structure for a future endgame. However, it is
generally not a great idea to go for it, if White is able to create
counterplay promptly with b4! In such case, Black's position can rapidly
become dangerous to navigate} (12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 O-O-O {[%cal Bf8e7] is
objectively best}) 13. Bd3 {Too slow. White has to be extremely accurate,
otherwise Black will get an advantage due to his better pawn structure.} (13.
b4 {A necessary move! White undermines the Black pawns and gets a lot of
active play in the center} cxb4 14. Ncxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 {[%csl Re6][%cal Be2g4]
} Nxe5 16. Bg4 $18 {[%cal Gd4e6,Gf4c7,Gg4e6]}) 13... Be7 14. Qe2 g5 $1 {
Grabbing space on the kingside! White may also have problems protecting e5
after g4 in the future} 15. Bg3 O-O-O 16. b4 {Too late: Black's attack is
faster} h5 $19 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gg5g4]} 17. h4 {[%cal Gc5b4]} Nxb4 {Clearing c6
for the bishop} 18. Nxb4 cxb4 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 19. Nxd4 gxh4 20. Bf4 Rdg8 21. c5
Rg4 {Black has a tremendous advantage and ultimately won the game} 22. Qe3 Bxc5
23. Rfc1 Kb8 24. f3 Rg7 25. Nc6+ Bxc6 26. Qxc5 Rhg8 $19 27. Be3 Nxe5 28. Be2 h3
29. Kf1 h2 30. Qa7+ Kc8 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

