{[%evp 0,32,19,38,43,18,28,11,-4,-1,-6,13,-9,-2,21,28,19,13,19,20,8,17,26,-8,0,
28,11,-2,22,-3,25,28,28,-21,-17]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3
Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O fxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 {[%cal Gf2f4]} 10. f4 $2 {
At first glance, this move seems so logical...but in fact, it only helps
Black! White's position becomes too static and it gets increasingly hard to
create the initiative. Black finishes his development without any trouble} (10.
Re1) ({or} 10. Bf4 {are promising continuations for White}) 10... Nh6 $1 {
[%cal Gh6f5]} 11. Na3 (11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3] is what I would prefer in a game})
11... Be7 12. Nc2 O-O 13. Be3 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6] Black comes at a cross road:
he has a couple of good choices but one of them stands out} Be8 $1 {A classic
and positionally sound solution- Black is looking to improve the position of
its bishop} (13... Nf5 14. Bf2 g5 $13 {is very interesting too but leads to a
more dynamic type of play}) (13... g5 {may come as a little premature} 14. Qd2
Nf5 15. fxg5 {[%cal Gd2e3]} Qxe5 16. Bf4 Qg7 $14 {According to the engine, the
position is better for White, but in practice all three results are possible})
14. Bd3 Rd8 15. Qf3 Nf5 16. Qh3 Bg6 $15 {Black achieved a great position out
of the opening- he has good control over the center and all his pieces are
active} 0-1

