{[%evp 0,28,39,39,43,19,26,6,6,-9,-8,-6,-3,5,6,6,6,-5,13,-22,38,27,11,-35,26,
23,49,23,15,11,40]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6
7. O-O fxe5 8. dxe5 Qc7 $2 {This move only helps White.} 9. Bf4 O-O-O 10. Na3
$1 a6 11. b4 $1 {A typical idea, aimed at breaking the queenside} c4 12. Rb1 $5
(12. Nc2 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gc2d4] This would be the positional way, almost everyone
would play like this...but not Shirov.}) 12... h6 13. b5 {Consistent.} Bxa3 14.
bxc6 Qxc6 15. Nd4 $1 Qc7 16. Bg4 $1 {It is very instructive to see how Shirov
manages to activate all his pieces.} Re8 17. Nf5 {Incredible move, making use
of every tactic.} Rf8 (17... exf5 18. e6 Qxf4 19. exd7+ Kxd7 20. Qxd5+ $18) 18.
Nxg7 $1 {Probably Black was only expecting Nd6.} Rxf4 (18... Qc6 $1 {would
have been the most stubborn defense.}) 19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. Bxe6+ Kb8 21. Bxd5 b6
22. g3 $1 {Extremely accurate move.} (22. Qa4 $2 Ne7 $1 {and the bishop on d5
doesn't have a safe place where to go.}) 22... Rf8 23. Qa4 $1 Ne7 24. Bg2 $1
Bc5 25. Qxa6 Qa7 26. Qb5 $1 Rc8 27. a4 {Now the pawn enters the party.} Rhd8
28. a5 Qd7 29. axb6 Qxb5 30. Rxb5 Nd5 31. Ra1 Nxb6 32. Ra8+ Kc7 33. Rxc5+ {
A total masterpiece played by Shirov!} 1-0

