{[%evp 0,107,31,32,32,32,32,14,14,5,5,5,5,-5,40,14,19,22,10,0,2,12,0,13,6,6,18,
3,0,27,31,51,27,57,95,59,84,40,52,20,20,18,26,18,29,25,28,32,11,45,53,56,58,45,
52,7,82,55,111,91,91,70,82,114,99,103,94,81,94,83,100,101,112,105,80,106,111,
47,37,70,87,67,82,48,75,80,50,35,48,54,39,36,142,47,186,197,257,259,259,236,
236,236,229,169,256,232,310,219,889,889]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 $1 {Stopping White's pawn break. Now, White
has two plans, both of them connected with the bishop on f1: a) White develops
the bishop to e2. b) White plays g3 and then develops the bishop to g2 or h3.}
(7... Bd7 $2 {This would be a mistake.} 8. b3 cxb3 9. Nxb3 $16 {[%cal Ga1b1,
Gc3c4] White has the initiative}) 8. g3 $5 {White's idea is to place the
bishop on h3. From this position, the bishop fights against the pawn break ...
f6.} Bd7 9. Bh3 h6 (9... O-O-O {this move was possible as well.}) 10. O-O O-O-O
11. Rb1 Ne7 {Now, White has to decide what to do next} 12. Ne1 $1 {[%csl Ra4,
Rb3][%cal Ge1g2,Gg2e3,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gc8b8,Gb6c7,Ge7c8,Gc8b6,Gd7a4] Very
important move! White is planning to play Ng2 followed by Ne3. From this
position, the knight supports the breakthrough f5.} (12. b3 $2 {does not work
out tactically} cxb3 13. Nxb3 Ba4 $1 $17) (12. Re1 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ga5b3,
Gd7a4] with the idea to play Nf1, Ne3 is also possible. However, I prefer to
keep the knight on d2 and prevent the Black pieces from infiltrating White's
camp after Nb3, Ba4}) 12... f5 $2 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf2f4] This move is only
good once the f2 pawn is on f4! The key difference is that after exf6, gxf6,
White has strong pressure on e6} (12... Kb8 {This is one possible and standard
plan for Black.} 13. Ng2 Qc7 14. Ne3 Nc8 {Black maneuvers his pieces to try
and exploit White's weaknesses on the queenside} 15. f4 (15. b4 cxb3 16. Nxb3
Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Nb6 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gb6a4,Gb6c4] The knight stops all of
White's play against the king}) 15... g6 $1 {is the way to go! Black manages
to keep White's aggression under control.} (15... Nb6 $2 16. f5 $1 {White has
to play this move as soon as possible.} ({On the other hand, after let's say} 
16. Kh1 {,} f5 $1 {works out to perfection as d5 is well-protected} 17. exf6
gxf6 18. f5 $2 e5 $15 {[%csl Rd5]})) (15... f5 $2 16. exf6 gxf6 17. f5 $1 {
[%csl Rd5] Black didn't defend d5 properly which allows White to crash through}
) 16. g4 {The inclusion of g4 and g6 means that the White king will be weaker
once he pushes f5} Be7 {Now Black threats to play the move ...f5!} 17. f5 (17.
Kh1 $2 f5 18. exf6 Bxf6 $15) 17... gxf5 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bxf5 Be6 {[%csl Rg1]
[%cal Gc7d7,Gd8g8]} 20. Kh1 Qd7 {Black stabilized his position. Both sides
have chances}) (12... Nec6 {This is another possible plan.} 13. Ng2 Kb8 14. Ne3
Be7 15. f4 Ka8 {The most normal way.} (15... Nxd4 $5 16. cxd4 Qxd4 17. Re1 Rc8
18. Nf3 Qb6 {This is a very interesting piece sacrifice for Black.}) 16. Kh1 (
16. f5 $2 Nxe5 $1) 16... g6) 13. exf6 $1 (13. f4 $2 g5 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh6h5]})
13... gxf6 {[%csl Re6]} 14. b3 $1 cxb3 15. Nd3 {[%cal Gd3c5,Gd3f4] This knight
is perfectly placed.} (15. Nxb3 Ba4) 15... Ng6 (15... Bb5 16. Nxb3 Bxd3 17.
Qxd3 Nxb3 {[%cal Gb1b6]} 18. Qc2 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb1b3,Gf1e1] White regains
the piece and will also soon get the e6 pawn}) 16. Nxb3 Nxb3 (16... Ba4 17. Qh5
$1 $18) 17. Rxb3 Qc7 18. Re1 f5 (18... e5 19. Bxd7+ Rxd7 20. Qg4 {Black's
position falls apart}) 19. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd1b1,Ge1c1,Gc3c4] Followed by Qb1
and a well-timed c4, Black would be in huge trouble.} ({Instead,} 19. Bf4 {
was the game continuation} Nxf4 20. Nxf4 Re8 21. Ng6 Rg8 22. Nxf8 Rgxf8 23. Qh5
Ba4 24. Rbb1 $16 Qf7 25. Qe2 Bc6 26. c4 Kb8 27. Bg2 Qf6 28. Qb2 Ka8 29. Re5 f4
30. cxd5 exd5 31. Bxd5 Bxd5 32. Rxd5 Re7 33. Rb5 Rfe8 34. Re5 Rd8 35. Rc1 Red7
36. Rec5 b6 37. Rc6 Qf5 38. Qe2 fxg3 39. hxg3 Rxd4 40. Rxh6 Rd2 41. Qe3 R2d3
42. Qe1 Qf3 43. Rhc6 Kb7 44. Rc7+ Ka6 45. Qf1 R8d6 46. a4 Qe4 47. R1c3 b5 48.
axb5+ Kb6 49. R3c6+ Rxc6 50. Rxc6+ Kb7 51. Qg2 Rf3 52. Rc1 Kb6 53. Qh3 Rf7 54.
Qc8) 1-0

