{[%evp 0,85,30,30,41,22,20,11,11,0,0,0,21,6,14,11,14,14,14,10,-12,3,14,2,5,-8,
-6,-11,20,20,20,14,31,23,32,34,74,9,5,15,57,62,80,66,66,51,73,68,80,85,92,12,
16,-6,18,8,40,32,32,27,0,3,12,12,55,53,151,151,151,128,253,223,239,239,555,548,
186,298,207,284,374,216,192,397,445,992,29995,29996]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. Be2 {The plan with Be2 was
invented by the Soviet GM Sveshnikov who has even written a book on the
Advance Variation in the French} Bd7 9. O-O Ne7 10. Rb1 {This position is very
important} Rc8 $2 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge8a8] After this move, the Black will
never find a safe place for his king. His position is already tough.} ({
During the game Black was probably afraid of} 10... O-O-O 11. b3 cxb3 12. Bd3 {
[%cal Gd2b3,Gd3c2]}) ({One point to remember is that} 10... h6 {[%csl Rf7]
[%cal Gf3g5,Gg7g5,Gd7a4] is almost always a useful move. It prevents a Ng5
jump and prepares an attack with g5 in the future. Additionally, it can also
serve as a waiting move until Black decides where to put his king}) 11. g3 h6
12. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4g2,Gg2e3,Ge8d8,Gd8c7,Gc7b8] Now is Black's chance to
evacuate the monarch: it simply cannot stay on e8!} Bb5 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gd7c7]}
13. Ra1 Nb3 {[%cal Gc1e3] In my opinion, this is dubious as it only opens up
the White bishop} 14. Nxb3 Ba4 15. Be3 Qxb3 16. Qd2 Rc6 {[%cal Gb3c2,Ge2d1,
Gd1a4]} (16... Qc2 $4 {fails to} 17. Bd1 Qxd2 18. Bxa4+ $18 {[%cal Ye3d2]}) 17.
Bd1 (17. Ng2 Qc2) 17... Qb5 18. Bg4 {White is better: f4-f5 is coming and
Black has nothing to oppose it} Rb6 19. Rab1 h5 20. Be2 Qb3 21. Bd1 Qb5 22. Bf3
Qb3 23. Bg5 Qa2 24. Ng2 Qb3 25. Nf4 $2 (25. Rfe1 Qc2 26. Bd1 $1 $18) 25... Qc2
$1 {Probably, White didn't realize that the queen on d2 is hanging now.} 26.
Qe3 Qf5 27. h4 f6 28. exf6 gxf6 29. Bxh5+ Rxh5 30. Nxh5 fxg5 31. hxg5 Bc2 32.
Rbc1 Rxb2 33. Nf6+ Kf7 34. g4 Qg6 35. Rfe1 Be4 36. Qf4 e5 37. dxe5 Kg7 38. Re3
Nc6 39. Rh3 Bc5 40. Rf1 Qf7 41. Qh2 Bg6 42. Rh8 Qe7 43. Rh7+ {1-0 Black
resigns.} 1-0

