{[%evp 0,28,19,38,43,18,28,11,-4,-1,-6,13,-6,0,29,27,19,17,14,-17,8,-42,-42,
-12,31,19,19,19,23,-19,7]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6.
a3 c4 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. Rb1 Bd7 9. h4 {This is the new way of playing: White
grabs space and doesn´t yet define the place of Bf1. The other idea is to
prepare b4. While the two moves might seem unrelated, with the pawn on h4
White can defend the c3 with Rh3.} (9. b3 cxb3 10. Nxb3 Ba4 11. Nfd2 {[%cal
Gf1d3,Gd3c2]} (11. Nxa5 {is not good enough either} Bxd1 12. Rxb6 axb6 13. Bb5+
(13. Nxb7 {[%cal Gb7d6]}) 13... Ke7 14. Kxd1 bxa5 $13 {According to the
computer, this is not so bad. Still, I think the bishop pair does not fully
compensate for the sacrificed exchange}) 11... Rc8 $17 {[%cal Gc8c3] White is
in trouble}) 9... h6 (9... O-O-O {[%cal Gc8b8,Gd8c8] is what I suggest as an
improvement}) 10. b4 cxb3 11. Nxb3 Nxb3 {White needs to be precise to get the
advantage. Exercise:} (11... Ba4 12. Nfd2 Rc8 13. Rh3 $1 {[%csl Rc3] The key
difference!} Ne7 $6 14. Nxa5 Bxd1 15. Rxb6 axb6 16. Nxb7 $1 $18 {[%cal Gb7d6]
Ne7 blocks the dark-squared bishop, so Nxb7 is essentially a double attack here
}) 12. Qxb3 $2 {In this pawn structure, White relies on activity to keep the
position in balance. Generally, a transition into an endgame favors Black} (12.
Nd2 $3 {keeping the queens on board} Ne7 13. Nxb3 Ba4 14. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gd3c2]
} Rc8 15. Bd2 {White is much better}) (12. Rxb3 Qc7 $14) (12. Bd3 {runs into}
Nxc1 13. Rxb6 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 axb6 $19 {Black has a lot of material for the
queen}) 12... Qxb3 13. Rxb3 b6 14. Bb5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gc6a5] Black should be
slightly better. In the game though, Black eventually lost. 1-0} 1-0

