[SourceQuality "1"]

{The break ...f7-f6 is one of Black's most powerful weapons in the French
structures. Before, examining concrete examples, I would like to make some
general considerations. Thanks to the book My System by Aaron Nimtsovitsch,
it's common knowledge that we should attack the base of the opponent's pawn
chain. Nevertheless, since chess knowledge has been constantly developing,
nowadays we need to have a more nuanced understanding of the game. In one of
his numerous articles, the famous Moldavian trainer and theoretician
Chebanenko made an interesting observation. He states that when the opponent's
pawn chain consists of only 2 pawns, attacking it by the head is a more
effective strategy. Let's try to explain this unusual concept by providing a
concrete example. The position on the diagram occurred in the game Luis Sieiro
- Mikhail Gurevich, 1986. Preparing the advance ...f7-f6 is Black's most
promising plan. After ...f7-f6 followed by ...fxe5, White has two possible
options: 1) if he takes with a pawn, the d5-pawn will be a protected passed
pawn 2) before taking with the knight, White should reckon with the
vulnerability of the d4-pawn These 2 major problems are based on the fact that
White's pawn chain consists of only 2 pawns. In the game, Gurevich prepared
his strategy by means of the precise} 14... Ne7 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge7c6] Since
the pressure on d4 turns out to be ineffective, Black would like to increase
the pressure on the centre by transferring his knight to c6.} 15. Rhc1 f6 $1
16. Rc5 Kd8 $1 {A very important strategic idea. In general, by putting
pressure on e5, Black wants to provoke the move exf6. In such a case, the play
on the g-file as well as the strong pawn centre will be very powerful.
Nevertheless, it's important to first eliminate White's counterplay along the
c-file. Exchanging a pair of rooks is a typical device to do so. With his last
move, Black not only supports ... Rc8 but also makes the e8-square available
for the bishop. The maneuver ... Be8-h5 (g6) is a typical way of activating
the problematic bishop in French structures.} 17. Bd3 Rc8 $1 18. Rac1 Rxc5 19.
Rxc5 Be8 {Black is playing according to the plan. Now, Gurevich wants to
further weaken the white centre by playing ...Bh5, thus attacking the knight.
White played} 20. Ne1 {in order to prepare f2-f4 but this retreat makes the
centre even more vulnerable -} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Gf6e5,Gc6d4] After
this move, White is forced to make a concession.} 21. exf6 gxf6 {Black is
already better. The next step of his plan is the preparation of the advance ...
e6-e5. Therefore, the perfect square for the black king is d6.} 22. Ke3 Ke7 {
[%cal Ge7d6,Ge6e5]} 23. f4 Kd6 24. Rc1 Rg8 {Besides his central strategy,
Black starts putting pressure on the g-file. The idea is to provoke g2-g3 and
then initiate a minority attack by means of .. .h7-h5-h4. At this point, White
immediately went wrong -} 25. Bxh7 $2 {This mistake allows the invasion of the
black rook.} ({White should have played} 25. g3 {when despite Black's slight
advantage, his position would have been fully defendable.}) 25... Rh8 26. Bc2
Rxh2 27. Ba4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6e4] The bishop is heading for the e4-square.} 28.
Bxc6 {This capture only improves Black's central control. Nevertheless, it's
not easy to provide White with good advice.} bxc6 29. Kf2 Rh4 30. Ke3 Be4 {
Black enjoys complete domination. Gurevich converted his advantage in a few
moves.} 31. Rc3 Rg4 32. Ra3 Rg3+ 33. Nf3 Rxg2 34. Nd2 Rg3+ 35. Ke2 Rxa3 36.
bxa3 c5 {White resigned.} 0-1

