{People who have no prior knowledge of the French endgames would say that
White is slighly better in this position. The reason is that they will mainly
pay attention to White's control of the c-file and the passive c6-knight.
Nevertheless, we know that Black has a straightforward plan of playing for an
advantage. After exchanging a pair of rooks, he will maneuver his knight to c6.
Then the advance ...f7-f6 comes on the agenda. Lenderman played the logical} 
20... Rfc8 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e8,Ge8d7] immediately exchanging a pair of rooks.
It's important to occupy the c8-square with the f8-rook in order to clear the
way of the king to d7-square. The next few moves are quite logical -} 21. Rac1
Rxc6 22. Rxc6 Kf8 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge8d7] The king is heading to d7. From this
square, besides preparing the manoeuvre...Nb8-c6, the king will also prevent a
possible invasion via the c-file.} 23. Kf1 Ke8 24. Ke2 Kd7 25. Rc2 Nb8 {
[%cal Gb8c6] Strangely enough, Black has already a huge advantage in this
position. White can do nothing to prevent the idea of ...Nc6 followed by ...
f7-f6. It turns out that there are no good squares for the white knights in
this pawn structure.} 26. h4 Nc6 27. Kd3 f6 {Black accomplished his idea. Now,
White is facing a difficult decision regarding the modification of the pawn
structure.} 28. g3 {This move is designed to make sure that the h4-pawn is
never hanging. On the other hand, however, with his last move, White weakens
the f-file, thus making the f3-knight vulnerable.} ({The alternative} 28. exf6
gxf6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ga8g8,Gg8g4] does not solve the problems either. As we know
from the previous example, Black's main idea is to build a strong centre with .
..e6-e5. Additionally, the pressure along the g-file can be very annoying.
With a pawn on h4, at any moment, Black can consider the option of playing ...
Rg8-g4. Later on, White finally went for this pawn structure.}) 28... Rf8 {
Very logical. Black follows his strategy.} ({Nevertheless, since White cannot
improve his kingside position, it makes sense to open a second front of action
-} 28... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb6b5,Gb5b4] After fixing White's queenside with ...
a5-a4, Black can either prepare the advance ...b6-b5-b4 or manoeuvre the
knight to c4.}) 29. exf6 gxf6 {White does not have any way of preventing the
advance ...e6-e5.} 30. Ng1 e5 31. Ne2 Bd6 32. Nb1 e4+ 33. Ke3 {White's last
hope is to establish a blockade on the f4-square. Nevertheless, Black has an
elegant way of fighting this idea.} Ne7 {The knight goes to the kingside in
order to support the advance ...f5-f4. Additionally, Black is ready to answer
Nf4 with ...Nf5+.} 34. Nbc3 Bb8 $6 {A dubious decision, providing White with
an excellent chance for a draw.} ({Black should have played} 34... Rg8 {
which is a prophylactic against f2-f3.}) 35. Kd2 $2 {After this move, White is
in a big trouble.} ({Better would have been} 35. f3 {when after} f5 36. Nf4 Rg8
37. Nce2 {it seems that White is holding the blockade.}) 35... f5 36. Rc1 $2 {
This move allows ...f5-f4 without putting any resistance.} ({Necessary was} 36.
Ke3 {Nevertheless, after} f4+ 37. gxf4 h5 $1 $17 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gd7e6] Black is
close to winning. He is going to follow with ...Ke6 and ...Nf5.}) 36... f4 37.
gxf4 Bxf4+ 38. Nxf4 Rxf4 39. Ke2 Rxh4 {Black is already winning. Lenderman
converted his extra pawn without difficulties.} 40. Rg1 Ke6 41. Rg7 Nf5 42.
Rxa7 Nxd4+ 43. Kd2 Rh2 44. Rb7 Rxf2+ 45. Ke1 Rxb2 46. Na4 Nf3+ 47. Kd1 Rd2+ 48.
Kc1 e3 49. Rxb6+ Ke5 50. Nc3 e2 51. Nxe2 Rxe2 52. Rxh6 d4 53. Rh8 d3 54. Re8+
Kf4 55. Rd8 Re1+ 0-1

