{In French structures, Black usually plays on the queenside while White is
trying to build up a kingside attack. The next game is a typical example of
Black's queenside strategy.} 18... Qb4 $5 19. Rc3 ({Maybe} 19. Rxc8+ Rxc8 20.
Qxb4 axb4 21. Rc1 Nc6 22. Rc2 $11 {[%cal Gb2b3] was stronger than text.}) 19...
Rxc3 20. bxc3 (20. Nxc3 Rc8 $36) 20... Qc4 21. Rb1 b5 22. g3 {[%cal Gf3h4,
Gh4g2,Gg2e3]} Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gb5b4] An important move. Black is preparin .
..Nc6 followed by ...b5-b4.} 23. Nh4 (23. Qb2 Nbc6 24. Qxb5 $140 $2 Rb8) 23...
Nbc6 24. Ng2 b4 {Slowly but surely Mikhail Gurevich overplayed his young
opponent and got initiative.} 25. Ne3 (25. Rc1 b3 $5 {[%csl Ga5]}) 25... Qa6 (
25... bxc3 26. Nxc4 cxd2 27. Nxd2 Rb8 $11 {leads just to equality.}) 26. Kg2
Rb8 27. Ng1 (27. cxb4 axb4 28. Nc1 $5 {[%cal Gc1b3]}) 27... Rb7 $1 28. Rb2 (28.
Rc1 b3) 28... bxc3 29. Qxc3 Rxb2 30. Qxb2 Qd3 $36 {[%csl Gc6,Gd3,Rd4,Rh5][%mdl
4096] Black's advantage is obvious, his queen is very active and it is
difficult already to protect white's pawns/} 31. Ne2 (31. Nf3 Qe4 32. Qc3)
31... Nf5 32. Nxf5 Qxf5 33. Qc3 (33. f3 Qd3) 33... Qe4+ 34. Kf1 (34. Qf3 Qc2)
34... Nb4 35. a3 Nd3 $17 {[%csl Rf1]} 36. Qd2 $8 Qf5 37. Ng1 $1 (37. Nc3 Qf3 {
[%cal Gf3h1]}) 37... Qe4 38. Ne2 a4 $1 {[%csl Ra3]} 39. Qe3 ({Maybe} 39. Nc3 $5
Qf3 (39... Qh1+ 40. Ke2 Nc1+ 41. Ke3 Nb3 42. Qd1) 40. Qe3 $140 Qh1+ 41. Ke2 Nb2
{[%cal Gb2c4] was better chance.}) 39... Qh1+ 40. Ng1 Nb2 $1 41. Qc3 Nc4 {
[%csl Ra3]} 42. Qb4 (42. g4 Qh4 43. f3 Qe7 $1) 42... Qe4 43. Ne2 (43. Qxa4 $2
Nd2#) 43... Qc2 $19 {Rest is simple.} 44. Nf4 (44. f3 Qb3 $19) 44... Qd1+ 45.
Kg2 Qxd4 46. Kg1 (46. Qb8+ Kh7 47. Qb1+ Qe4+) 46... Qxe5 47. Qxa4 Qa1+ 48. Kg2
Qxa3 49. Qe8+ Qf8 50. Qd7 Qa8 51. Kh2 Ne5 52. Qc7 Nf3+ 53. Kh3 d4 54. Qd6 Qe4
55. Kg2 d3 {The technical part of the game was greatly conducted by Gurevich}
56. Kf1 0-1

