{In French positions with c-pawns exchanged (usually after ...cxd4 cxd4), the
control of the open c-file is very important. In the next model game, we are
going to witness how one of the biggest French experts GM Thomas Luther uses
the c-file for the purposes of his strategy. The first important position
arises after the move 15.fxe5. I decided not to cut the opening moves just to
illustrate that we get French structures out of many openings.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4
e6 3. Bf4 Bd6 4. e3 Bxf4 5. exf4 Ne7 6. c3 b6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Ba6 9. Qe2
Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. O-O c5 12. Rfe1 Rc8 13. Ne5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nxe5 15. fxe5 {
The position has been finally clarified. Having a space advantage on the
kingside, White's main plan is to create an attack against the king. Such an
attack, however, is impossible here. You should know one very important
principle that is often neglected. When there is an open file that is not
under our control, a kingside attack does not work. In this position, Luther
played the precise} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c2] immediately taking the control of the
c-file and preparing ...Qc2 on the next move.} 16. Nf3 Qc2 17. Qa3 {Of course,
White cannot accept the exchange of the queens. The next few moves are quite
logical and do not require comments.} Rc7 18. Rad1 Rfc8 19. h3 h6 20. Rd2 Qf5
21. Red1 Nc6 $1 {A thematic idea in the fight for the c-file. Black wants to
provoke the advance b2-b3 by means of ...Na5 on the next move. Provoking b2-b3
is important for Black since in this way he gets access to the c3-square.} 22.
Qe3 {Before playing b2-b3, White wants at least to get his queen closer to the
centre.} ({Fighting for the c-file with} 22. Rc1 $2 {does not work tactically
in view of} Nxd4 23. Rxc7 Qb1+ 24. Kh2 Nxf3+ 25. Qxf3 Rxc7 $19) 22... Na5 23.
b3 {Mission completed! Now, Black redirects his knight to b4} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]
Once again, White cannot play Rc1 due to the familiar tactical trick.
Therefore, he went for the passive} 24. Ne1 Nb4 25. Qe2 {Now, however, Black
played} Rc3 {immediately making use of the newly weakened c3-square.} 26. a3 {
White wants to exchange the knights in order to reduce Black's annoying
pressure. The problem, however, is that in French structures, endgames with
heavy pieces are usually favourable for Black. This rule is even more valid in
positions where Black has full control of the c-file.} Nc2 27. Nxc2 Rxc2 28.
Qd3 $2 {A mistake in a very difficult position.} (28. Rxc2 Qxc2 29. Qxc2 Rxc2
30. Rd3 $17 {Even though Black has a big advantage, White still has some
chances to save the game.}) 28... Qxd3 29. Rxd3 Ra2 30. a4 Rcc2 31. Rf3 a6 {
[%cal Gb6b5,Gb5b4] A precise move. In the endgame, it's very important to win
space and fix the weaknesses of your opponent. With his last move, Black is
planning ...b6-b5-b4, fixing the b3-pawn.} 32. g4 Rd2 $2 {This is already a
mistake. It's impossible to improve the position of the rooks. Therefore,
Black should have kept seizing space on the queenside.} ({Black should have
exchanged a pair of rooks after improving his position to the maximum. For
example, after} 32... b5 33. axb5 axb5 34. Kg2 b4 35. h4 g6 36. Kg3 Kg7 37. Kg2
{Black can already play} Rd2 38. Rxd2 Rxd2 $19 {winning the d4-pawn. This time,
White cannot activate his rook since the c3-square is under control.}) {
In the game, after} 33. Rc1 Rac2 34. Rxc2 Rxc2 35. Rd3 b5 36. axb5 axb5 37. Kf1
b4 38. Ke1 {White managed to stabilize the position. It's not easy for Black
to make progress. Later on, GM Thomas Luther managed to win by using the
mistakes of his opponent.} Rb2 39. Rf3 Kf8 40. Kd1 Ke7 41. Ke1 f6 42. exf6+
gxf6 43. Re3 Kf7 44. f4 Rg2 45. Rf3 h5 46. gxh5 Rg8 47. Kf2 Rh8 48. Re3 Rxh5
49. Kg3 Rh8 50. Kg4 Rg8+ 51. Kf3 Rg1 52. Ke2 Rb1 53. Rg3 Rb2+ 54. Ke1 Rh2 55.
Re3 Rg2 56. Rd3 Kg6 57. Kf1 Kf7 58. Re3 Rb2 59. Ke1 0-1

