{The light square strategy is another major idea in French structures. Black
usually uses this strategy after exchanging his dark-squared bishop for the
white knight. In this case, he immediately gets superior control of the light
squares. A model game featuring the light square strategy in French positions
is Mohrlok - Ivkov, 1967. Even though the position seems to be equal, Black is
slightly better due to his superior control of the light squares. While Black
can control the light squares with 2 pieces, only 1 white piece can do the
same. Very often in such positions, the white dark-squared bishop tends to be
useless. At the same time, in the endgame, White's space advantage is not a
significant factor. Ivkov started with the move} 19... Kd7 {As we have already
seen, in French endgames, d7-square is the perfect spot for the king. Black's
first task is to create stable squares for his knights. Afterwards, he will
get a favourable kingside structure by employing the advance ...f7-f6. Since
one pair of rooks has been already exchanged, White does not have counterplay
along the c-file.} 20. Kf1 h5 $1 {[%cal Ge7f5] A very typical move in French
structures. The idea is to secure the f5-square for the knight.} 21. Ke2 Nf5
22. Nf3 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8c6] The other knight is heading for c6.} 23. Kd3 Nc6 {
[%cal Gf7f6] After optimally arranging his knights, Black is preparing the
thematic ...f7-f6 advance.} 24. Ne1 f6 $1 25. f4 {Sustaining the space
advantage but further restricting the e3-bishop. Additionally, the advance
f2-f4 makes the light squares even more vulnerable.} ({On the other hand, the
alternative} 25. exf6 gxf6 {[%cal Ge6e5] gives Black to build a strong centre
by means of ...e6-e5.}) 25... Rc8 $1 {A very nice intermediate move. Before
proceeding with his kingside strategy, Ivkov takes the control of the c-file
by using a nice tactical trick. Now, the threat is 26...Nxe3 27.Kxe3 Nxd4! 28.
Rxc8 Nf5+! followed by ...Kxc8. Therefore, White decided to surrender the
c-file by playing} 26. Rb1 g5 $1 {This is the thematic way of fighting against
the advance f2-f4. White is now forced to accept certain structural
concessions.} 27. g3 {White keeps weakening the light squares and restricting
his own bishop.} ({In such structures, Black often answers} 27. exf6 {with} g4
$1 {seizing more space and restricting White's pieces. The f6-pawn is doomed
anyway. After taking it, Black will prepare the advance ...h5-h4-h3, the idea
being to provoke g2-g3. The knights will be perfectly placed on f5 and e4.})
27... g4 $1 {We already know this typical idea. Black's next idea is to
prepare ...h5-h4.} 28. Ng2 Rf8 29. Rb2 Nce7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gh5h4] The most
consistent continuation. The knight is going to g6 in order to prepare the
advance ...h5-h4.} 30. Bd2 Ng6 31. Rc2 {White keeps waiting.} ({Probably,
better would have been} 31. a4 {trying to initiate queenside counterplay.})
31... fxe5 $1 {In order to win the game, Black should find a way to invade
with his rook. The last move is designed to open the f-file for invasion. If
White recaptures with the e-pawn, then the d5-pawn will be a protected passed
pawn.} 32. dxe5 ({After} 32. fxe5 $2 h4 $1 {Black is winning by force. The
following sequence is a perfect illustration of Black's light square strategy.}
33. Ne3 hxg3 34. hxg3 Nxg3 35. Nxg4 Rf3+ 36. Be3 Nf4+ 37. Kc3 Ne4+ 38. Kb2 Nd3+
39. Kb1 Rg3 $19 {winning a piece.}) 32... h4 {It turns out that the rook will
invade via the h-file.} 33. Be1 hxg3 34. Bxg3 Rh8 35. Ne3 Nxe3 36. Kxe3 Ne7 {
[%cal Ge7f5]} 37. Kf2 Nf5 {At the end of the day, White remained with his
useless dark-squared bishop. The black knight enjoys full domination.} 38. Rc1
a5 $1 {A very instructive idea. Ivkov basically applies the principle of two
weaknesses. The idea of his last move is to weaken the light squares on the
queenside with the move ...a5-a4. If White plays a3-a4 himself, Black will
then open a file by means of the break ...b6-b5.} 39. Kg2 Ra8 $6 {This move is
not necessary.} ({More precise would have been} 39... a4 $1 {when after} 40. b4
{Black immediately occupies the newly created weakness on c4. He should play}
Ne3+ 41. Kf2 Nc4 42. Rc3 Rc8 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8f7,Gf7g6,Gg6f5] Later on, Black
will transfer his king all the way to f5. White cannot hold this position. A
beautiful illustration of the light square strategy.}) 40. Bf2 a4 41. bxa4 $2 {
This is losing on the spot.} ({The lesser evil would have been} 41. b4 {
Nevertheless, after} Rh8 42. Bxb6 Rh3 43. Rc7+ Ke8 44. Rc8+ Kf7 45. Bf2 Rxa3
$19 {Black should be winning.}) {The next moves are quite logical.} 41... Rxa4
42. Bxb6 Rxa3 43. Rc7+ Ke8 44. Rc8+ Kf7 45. Rc7+ Kg6 46. Rc6 Nh4+ 47. Kf2 Ra2+
48. Kf1 ({After} 48. Kg3 Kh5 {White is losing immediately due to the mating
threats.}) 48... Kf5 {Black is already winning.} 49. Bf2 Nf3 50. Bg3 Nxh2+ {
White resigned.} 0-1

