{Let's briefly take a look at another instructive fragment featuring the light
square strategy. This position occured in the online blitz game Nicolas
Brunner - Dmitry Krakvin, 2020. Once again, we can see White's useless
dark-squared bishop. Despite the short time control, the Russian grandmaster
employed his light square strategy very convincingly.} 23... f6 $1 {By now,
everyone should be familiar with this idea. Black wants to either provoke
f2-f4 or force White the give the centre away with exf6.} 24. exf6 ({After} 24.
f4 Kf7 25. Ke2 {Black will play the thematic} g5 $1 {Regardless of what White
does, Black will get an open file for his a8-rook.} 26. g3 ({Even worse is} 26.
exf6 {when after} gxf4 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Ga8g8] Black will follow with ...Rg8,
targeting the already fixed g2-pawn.}) 26... gxf4 27. gxf4 Rg8 28. Kf3 Rg6 $17
{[%csl Rf4,Rh2][%cal Gg6h6,Gc4c8,Gc8g8] Black is better due to White's
vulnerable kingside structure. White should always reckon with ...Rh6.
Additionally, Black is planning to bring the other rook to the kingside.})
24... gxf6 25. f4 Kf7 ({The immediate} 25... f5 {was possible as well.}) 26.
Kf2 f5 27. Ke3 h5 $17 {[%csl Gf4,Gf5,Gg2,Gh2,Gh5][%cal Rg2g3,Gh5h4] A very
thematic structure in the French endgames. Black's general plan is to conduct
the so-called minority attack. If he manages to provoke the advance g2-g3, by
means of the thematic .. .h5-h4 he will create a kingside weakness. Even if
White manages to keep his pawn on g2, Black will fix it with ...h5-h4.} 28. g3
Rg8 29. Kf3 {At this point, the best would have been} h4 ({The game followed
with} 29... Rc6 30. Be1 Rgc8 31. Rc3 Nf6 32. Rac1 Rxc3+ 33. bxc3 Rc4 34. Rb1
Nd7 35. Ra1 Ke7 36. Ke3 Kd6 37. Kd3 Kc6 38. Bd2 Nf6 39. Bc1 Ng4 40. Ra2 Nf6 41.
Ra3 Ne4 42. Bd2 Kb7 43. Bc1 Kc6 44. Bd2 Nf2+ 45. Ke2 Ng4 46. h3 Nf6 47. Be1 Ne4
48. Kd3 Kb7 49. Ra1 Rc7 50. Ra2 Rg7 51. Rg2 Nd6 52. Re2 Rg6 53. Rg2 Kc6 54. Rb2
Ne4 55. Rg2 Nd6 56. Rb2 Rg8 57. Rg2 b5 58. axb5+ Kxb5 59. Re2 Ne4 60. Rb2+ Kc6
61. Ra2 Ra8 62. c4 dxc4+ 63. Kxc4 Nd6+ 64. Kb3 Kb5 65. Rc2 a4+ 66. Ka2 Nc4 67.
Re2 Ra6 68. Bc3 Rc6 69. Re1 Nb6 70. Rb1+ Kc4 71. Ba1 Nd5 72. Ka3 Ra6 73. Re1
Kd3 74. Rc1 Ke2 75. Rc8 Kf3 76. Rh8 Kxg3 77. Rxh5 Nxf4 78. Rg5+ Kxh3 79. Bc3
Nd5 80. Be1 f4 81. Rg6 Ne3 82. Bf2 Ng4 83. Be1 f3 84. Rg8 f2 {and Black won.})
30. Rb5 h3 {[%csl Rh2] Pushing the pawn all the way to h3 is a very typical
concept nowadays. Due to the potential vulnerability of the h2-pawn, the white
king will be tied to the kingside. Besides his eventual pressure on h2, Black
can often consider knight sacrifices on g3 followed by the promotion of the
h-pawn. A possible line would be} 31. Rb3 Rc6 $19 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6e4] Keeping
the b6-pawn and planning to transfer the knight to e4. White cannot hold such
a position since he has targets on both wings.} 0-1

