{We shall now take a look at series of examples featuring one of the most
recurring motifs in the French structures - the bad light-squared bishops.
Hopefully, after studying the the examples, the reader will understand that
this bishop is not always so weak. As the Romanian grandmaster Mihai Suba used
to say, the bad bishops protect the good pawns. Therefore, it's not a surprise
that exactly this bishop keeps Black's fortress. Let's start with a model game
illustrating all the drawbacks of the passive light-squared bishop. The
position on the diagram is obviously favourable for White due to his better
minor pieces. Actually, if we remove the minor pieces from the board, Black
will have an advantage due to the semi-open files for his rooks. These
exchanges, however, are not easy to achieve. Black's other problem is his
overextended queenside pawn structure. By means of the break a2-a3, White will
manage to create targets on the queenside. A thematic move for such positions.
Leko immediately starts preparing a2-a3.} 19. Ra1 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3]} a5 20. a3
Nc5 21. axb4 axb4 22. Kf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2e3] The king is heading to e3 just at
the right moment.} Rfc8 ({The position arising after} 22... Nxd3+ 23. cxd3 {
[%csl Gb2,Gc2,Gc3,Gc4,Gd3,Gd4][%cal Gf2e3] is strategically winning for White.
The d4-knight enjoys full domination over the bishop. Additionally, in French
structures, the construction Nd4+d3 is very strong. Besides further
restricting the bishop, this construction controls a lot of squares on the
queenside. Black does not have his usual target on c2. At the same time,
harassing the knight with ... Rc4 is never an option. After exchanging the
rooks, White will just collect the b4-pawn.}) 23. g4 b3 {Black is getting rid
of his queenside weakness but allows the formation of a distant passed pawn on
the queenside.} 24. Ke3 bxc2 25. Rxa8 Rxa8 26. Bxc2 Kf8 27. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc5]
[%cal Gc2g6,Gc1c5] A very clever move. By creating the threat of Bxg6, White
forces Black to play} Rc8 {The point behind 27.Rc1! is to answer this move with
} 28. Ra1 $1 {[%cal Ga1a7] forcing the exchange of the rooks in view of the
possible invasion.} Ra8 29. Rxa8+ Bxa8 30. b4 {White is winning in this
endgame. Besides having more active minor pieces, he is practically a pawn up.
While the d5-pawn is completely useless, the b-pawn will decide the game.} Na6
31. b5 Nc5 32. Nb3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} Nd7 {Of course, Black cannot exchange his
only active piece.} 33. Kd4 Ke7 34. Nc5 Nb6 35. h4 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gg4g5,
Gh4h5,Gh5h6] An important moment. Once again, we see a pure application of the
principle of the two weaknesses. It's not easy to win the game only on the
queenside. Therefore, White needs targets on the other wing. If possible, the
second target should be far away from the queenside. Hence, the h7-pawn is
White's perfect target. With his last move, Leko indicates his intention of
advancing the h-pawn all the way to h6.} Kd8 36. Bd3 {Of course, White can
shuffle around with his pieces as long as he wishes. Black has no counterplay
whatsoever. Therefore, until move 43, Leko was probably trying to add time on
the clock.} Ke7 37. Be2 Kd8 38. Bf1 Ke7 39. Bd3 Kd8 40. Bc2 Ke7 41. Bd1 Kd8 42.
Be2 Ke7 43. g5 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] Finally! Everything is ready for the
advance h4-h5-h6.} Kd8 44. h5 Ke7 45. h6 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc5d3,Gd3f2,Gf2g4,
Gg4f6] The h7-pawn has been fixed. Now, White will manoeuvre his knight all
the way to f6. The game is over. In a few moves, Gurevich resigned.} Kd8 46.
Bd3 Ke7 47. Bc2 Kf8 48. Nd3 Nd7 49. Nf2 Ke7 50. Ng4 1-0

