{[%evp 0,115,35,35,38,38,30,21,36,36,26,20,20,19,19,27,24,18,25,30,22,13,21,-1,
7,6,1,2,0,-10,-8,-2,5,9,10,13,16,26,18,28,49,32,35,26,26,43,42,48,51,56,73,69,
73,63,70,74,87,67,43,7,2,0,0,0,33,37,30,19,23,45,20,16,16,10,7,24,0,0,0,0,71,
70,57,55,74,88,85,58,79,61,60,60,40,31,23,2,2,35,38,18,54,49,55,90,88,34,111,
97,111,73,73,73,73,73,73,73,73,73] This is another example showing how
difficult is to play with a passive light-squared bishop when the queenside is
overextended.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7.
Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 {[#] Not trying to win a pawn on b2. This is a more
classical line, but not very popular nowadays.} 9. Qd2 O-O ({There were some
interesting attempts by Nisipeanu to trick his opponents and save a tempo on
the short castle with} 9... a6 10. O-O-O Nxd4 ({In case of} 10... Qc7 {White
can still play} 11. h4 Nxd4 (11... b5 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2d4]}) 12.
Bxd4 b5 13. a3 $5 {with a transposition.}) ({Giving the dark-squared bishop
away by means of} 10... Bxd4 {reduces Black's chances of obtaining counterplay.
} 11. Bxd4 O-O 12. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4] Important positional idea. White
is preparing the typical manoeuvre Ne2-d4. The following line is quite
straightforward.} b5 13. Ne2 b4 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 a5 16. g4 Ba6 17. Bg2 Qc7
18. Kb1 $1 {Before proceeding with his kingside attack, Anand is taking care
of his queenside. With his last move, he is preparing the prophylactic 19.Rc1.}
Rfc8 19. Rc1 Rab8 20. f5 {White's advantage is obvious. 1-0 (36) Anand, V 
(2755) -Gurevich,M (2634) Bastia 2002}) 11. Bxd4 Qc7 {Now I like} (11... O-O
12. Qf2 {leads to a transposition.}) 12. h4 (12. Qe3 b5 13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 a5
15. Bb5 O-O 16. Bxd7 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd7 18. h4 a4 19. Kb1 f6 20. exf6 Rxf6 21.
g3 Rc8 {was good for Black in the recent game 0-1 (48) Bosiocic, M -Nisipeanu,
L Skopje 2019}) 12... b5 13. a3 $5 {preventing b5-b4 and playing vs. black's
white square bishop.} O-O ({The tempting} 13... b4 {runs into} 14. axb4 Bxb4
15. f5 $36 {when White manages to develop a strong attack.}) 14. Rh3 {This is
a key move in White's concept. Along the third rank, the rook can participate
in the attack as well as in the defence. The concrete lines seem to work fine
for White.} Rb8 ({Once again, the direct} 14... b4 {does not work well -} 15.
Bxc5 bxc3 ({After} 15... Qxc5 16. Na4 Qa7 17. Qxb4 {White is a healthy pawn up.
}) 16. Rxc3 Nxc5 17. Qd4 {White is winning.}) 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 {[#] We have a
typical position for this pawn structure. Black is preparing the advance ...
b5-b4. At this point, White should go for the thematic} 16. b4 $1 {a bit
surprising positional idea. It turns out that Black cannot easily make use of
the weakened queenside. At the same time, White's kingside initiative tends to
be rather dangerous.} Nd7 17. Ne2 Nb6 18. Nd4 {It becomes clear that Black has
run out of resources on the queenside.} Bd7 ({After} 18... Nc4 {White can
follow with} 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. h5 {trying to provoke ...h7-h6, thus creating a
target for the pawn contact ...g2-g4-g5.}) 19. h5 f6 20. Re3 fxe5 21. Rxe5 {
[%csl Rd7] White has tremendous domination on the dark squares. 1-0 (37)
Karjakin,S -Lomasov,S Douglas 2018}) 10. O-O-O ({Possible calm option} 10. g3
$5 a6 11. Bg2 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Ne2 a5 14. a3 {But normally white should
not afraid to castle long after 7...cd with such pawn structure.}) 10... a6 ({
Once again, the exchange of the dark-squared bishop is dubious.} 10... Bxd4 11.
Bxd4 Qa5 (11... a6 12. Be3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4] Leads to a transposition.}) 12.
Kb1 Rb8 {Black is planning to prepare the advance ... b7-b5 without ...a7-a6.
In this way, he can consider exchanging the light-squared bishops via a6.} 13.
Nb5 {Going for an endgame is the safest way to get a slight advantage in this
position.} ({After} 13. Be3 b5 14. Ne2 b4 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Ba6 {Black
gets enough counterplay on the queenside.}) 13... Qxd2 14. Rxd2 a6 15. Nd6 Nxd4
16. Rxd4 f6 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Nxc8 Rbxc8 19. Bd3 $14 {White has a better pawn
structure and his bishop is superior to Black's knight.}) ({The plans with} 
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 a6 12. h4 {have already been examined.}) 11. Qf2 $5 {
This is really a nice move. I think I learned it from Kramnik in Linares back
in 2003 when he played it against Radjabov. Nowadays, everyone plays it
automatically with White.} ({Before, people used to play} 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4
b5 13. h5 b4 {when it is not clear at all who attacks first.}) 11... Nxd4 {
Black has different moves here for searching for some active play. In general,
White is trying to combine some prophylactic play with an activity on the
kingside.} ({One of his main lines was} 11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Be3 Qa5 {
Black prepares the advance ...b5-b4 and prevents White from playing Na4.} ({
After} 13... b4 {White should play} 14. Na4 {taking control of the dark
squares on the queenside and stopping black pawns.} a5 15. h4 $1 {This is a
typical idea. Before going for f4-f5, White is trying to provoke ...g7-g6. Of
course, this can be done by means of h2-h4-h5-h6.} Ba6 16. h5 Qc7 17. h6 g6 18.
g4 $36) ({The plan with} 13... Bb7 {seems to be rather slow. A typical
position would arise after} 14. Bd3 Nb4 15. Bd4 Rc8 16. Kb1 Nxd3 17. Rxd3 {
Black's counterplay is far from obvious. White's space advantage gives him
good chances for an attack on the kingside. He is currently preparing the
advance f4-f5.}) 14. Kb1 b4 15. Ne2 Qc7 16. Ng3 $5 {This is a rare and
original concept. White is planning to create a piece attack on the kingside.
He can follow with Nh5, Qh4 and Bd3.} a5 17. Nh5 a4 ({A bit risky is} 17... f6
{when after} 18. Qg3 Rf7 19. Bb5 fxe5 20. fxe5 Ba6 {1-0 (37) Wei,Y (2734)-Vovk,
Y (2628) Baku 2015, White could have played} 21. Rdf1 $1 Ndxe5 22. Bxa6 Rxa6
23. Bh6 {with a dangerous attack.}) 18. Qh4 {[%cal Gf1d3]} Qd8 19. Qg3 g6 20.
Bb5 Qc7 21. Rd3 Ba6 22. Bxa6 Rxa6 23. Nf6+ Nxf6 24. exf6 Rc8 25. Rc1 Qd8 26.
Qh4 Na5 27. f5 $14 {and White has an initiative.}) 12. Bxd4 b6 ({The game that
I mentioned before was} 12... Qc7 13. Bd3 b5 {looks like Black is doing the
same as in the case of 11.h4. But} ({Another interesting option is} 13... Bxd4
14. Qxd4 Qc5 15. Ne2 {You should know that the endgame arising after the
exchange of the queens is favourable for White due to the strong d4-knight and
the difference in the activity of the bishops. Of course, Black can delay the
exchange and gain space with} b5 {In this case, I like the following subtle
idea:} 16. Kb1 b4 17. Rc1 $1 {The point can be seen after} Qxd4 18. Nxd4 Nc5
19. Rhd1 {[%cal Gc2c3] Now, White is ready to open the c-file by means of
c2-c3. In the future, the queenside pawn majority, as well as the possible
penetration via c7, would give White an advantage.}) 14. Qh4 $1 {This is the
idea behind the move 11.Qf2.} h6 ({After} 14... g6 15. Ne2 {[%cal Gh4h6,Gh2h4]
White has a dangerous idea at his disposal: Qh6 followed by h2-h4-h5.}) 15. Ne2
{[%csl Rg8,Rh6][%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5]} f6 16. Qg4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 18. Qg6 Nxd3+
19. Rxd3 Qc4 (19... fxe5 20. Nxe6 Bxe6 21. Qxe6+ Qf7 22. Qxe5 d4 {was probably
lesser evil for Black.}) 20. Rhd1 Ra7 21. Kb1 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Gd4,Rg8] 1-0 (36)
Kramnik,V -Radjabov,T Linares 2003}) 13. Qe3 Bb7 14. Bd3 {Now, White should
not worry about a possible attack on the queenside. Due to the passive
b7-bishop, White has a small, but stable advantage here.} Bxd4 15. Qxd4 f6 16.
exf6 Qxf6 17. Qxf6 Rxf6 18. g3 Re8 19. Rhe1 b5 20. Bf1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ge1e8]} (
20. a4 $5 bxa4 (20... b4 21. Bxa6) 21. Nxa4 Bc6 22. Nc3 Nc5) 20... Nb6 21. Rd4
Bc6 22. a4 $5 {Trying to create more weaknesses in Black's camp.} Nxa4 23. Nxa4
bxa4 24. Bxa6 Ra8 25. Bd3 h6 26. Rb4 Ra7 {[#] I think I played a good game
until this moment} 27. Kb1 $2 {But this move is a bit slow and allowed my
opponent to consolidate his position.} ({I should have played something like} 
27. Rb6 Bd7 (27... Rc7 28. h4 Kf7 29. Kd2) 28. f5 Kf7 29. fxe6+ Rxe6 30. Rexe6
Bxe6 31. Ra6 Rxa6 32. Bxa6 Bd7 (32... d4 33. Kd2 Kf6 34. Bb5) 33. Kd2 Ke6 34.
Kc3 Ke5 35. Bd3 $18 {and the bishop endgame is winning for White.} d4+ 36. Kb4
g5 37. Bb5 Bf5 38. Bxa4 Ke4 39. Kc5 Kf3 40. b4 Kg2 41. b5 Kxh2 42. b6 Bc8 43.
Kxd4 Kxg3 44. c4 $18) 27... Kf7 28. Ka2 Ke7 29. f5 Kd6 30. fxe6 Rxe6 31. Rxe6+
Kxe6 {Now, Black's king is just on time to defend his weak pawns.} 32. Ka3 Kd6
33. Bb5 (33. c3 Rf7) 33... Bxb5 34. Rxb5 Rf7 35. Kxa4 (35. c3 Rf2) 35... Rf2
36. Rb6+ Kc7 37. Rg6 Rxc2 38. b4 Rxh2 39. Kb5 d4 40. Rxg7+ Kd6 41. Kc4 h5 42.
Kxd4 h4 43. Rg6+ Kc7 44. g4 h3 45. Ke5 Rb2 46. Rg7+ (46. Rh6 Rxb4 47. g5 Kd7)
46... Kd8 {The only move. But good enough for a draw.} 47. Kd6 Ke8 48. Kc5 h2
49. Rh7 Rg2 50. b5 Kf8 51. b6 Kg8 52. Rh5 Kg7 53. b7 Rb2 54. Kc6 Rc2+ 55. Kb6
Rb2+ 56. Kc6 Rc2+ 57. Kb6 Rb2+ 58. Kc6 {½-½ Ponomariov - Ni Hua, Khanty
Mansiysk, 2011} *

