{The next two examples are dedicated to the domination of the knight over the
bishop in French endgames. Diagram # On the diagram position, we have a
typical French ending where the white knight dominates the opponent's bishop.
The way in which White managed to convert his advantage is highly instructive.
First of all, the white king should invade the opponent's camp.} 24. Kf2 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Gf2e3,Ge3d4,Gd4c5] The king is heading for c5-square.
Obviously, Black couldn't stop this idea.} Ke7 ({The attempt to create a
counterplay on the kingside by means of} 24... Kf7 {could be easily prevented -
} 25. Ke2 $1 Kg6 {[%cal Gg6f5]} 26. Ne3 Kg5 27. g3 $18 {[%csl Rb6,Rd6,Ge3,Rf4,
Rf5,Gg3,Rh4][%cal Ge2d3,Gd3d4,Ge3f5,Gg3f4,Gg3h4,Gd4c5,Gc5b6,Gc5d6] Diagram #
Black couldn't make a progress on the kingside while the white king is ready
for an invasion. White is already winning.}) 25. Ke3 Kd8 26. Kd4 Kc7 27. Kc5
Bc8 28. Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb4d3,Gd3f4,Gf4h5,Gh5g7] Diagram # Now White
should execute the second part of his plan - provoke the opponent making a
kingside weakness. In order to win in such kind of endgames, we need at least
two weaknesses that could be simultaneously attacked by our knight (the
opponent's bishop should be tied to their defence). Moreover, there should be
an opposition between the kings. In this way, our opponent will be in zugzwang.
If he makes a move with the king, he allows an invasion. If he plays with the
bishop instead, then one of the weaknesses will be lost.} Bb7 29. g3 Bc8 30.
Nd3 Bd7 31. Nf4 {Óãðîæàÿ Nh5.} g6 32. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3g5] Diagram #
Now White is planning to proceed with 33.Ng5. Black should further weaken his
kingside.} h6 33. Nf4 g5 34. Nh5 Be8 35. Nf6 Bf7 36. Ng4 h5 37. Ne3 $1 {
[%csl Re6,Rh5][%cal Gh2h4] Diagram # White's mission is almost accomplished.
Now Black has two potential weaknesses - h5 and e6. In order to attack them
simultaneously, White should transfer his knight to f4-square.} Bg6 ({After} 
37... g4 38. Ng2 Bg6 39. Nf4 Bf7 40. b4 $18 {[%csl Gc5,Gc7,Re6,Rf7,Rh5][%cal
Gf4h5,Gf4e6] Black is in zugzwang.}) 38. h4 $1 {Diagram # White fixes the
h5-pawn and frees the f4-square for his knight.} gxh4 39. gxh4 Be4 40. Nf1 ({
Even simpler was} 40. Nd1 $1 Bd3 41. Nf2 Bf5 42. a3 {and White knight reached
the f4-square.}) 40... Bf3 41. Nd2 Be2 42. Nb3 Bg4 43. Nd4 Bh3 44. Ne2 Bf5 45.
Nf4 Bg4 46. b4 {Diagram # Zugzwang. White is simply winning.} Kd7 47. Kb6 Bf3
48. Kxa6 Kc6 49. Nxe6 1-0

