{Diagram # Here is another ending that arose from the French Defense. Given
the fact that almost all black pawns are placed on the colour of the bishop,
White's advantage is out of question. Almasi converts his advantage in a very
precise way.} 58. Nh7 Be8 59. Nf8 Bf7 60. h4 {Diagram # White fixes Black`s
kingside pawns.} Kb5 61. d4 $1 {Diagram # After this advance, White could use
the c5-square for his knight.} Ka4 62. Kb2 Kb5 63. Kb3 Kb6 64. Nd7+ Kb5 65. Nc5
Kb6 66. Kc3 Kc6 67. Nd3 Kb5 68. Nb2 $1 {Diagram # Now the knight prevents the
penetration of black king and White can transfer his king to g5.} Kc6 69. Kd2
Kd7 70. Ke3 Ke7 71. Kf4 Be8 72. Kg5 Kf7 73. Nd3 {[%cal Gd3c5,Gc5b3,Gc5b7]
Diagram # The next step in White`s winning plan is to force a5-a4 in order to
create another weakness in Black`s position.} Ba4 74. Nc5 Bc2 75. Nb7 a4 76.
Kh6 Kf8 77. Nc5 Kf7 78. Kg5 Bb3 79. Kf4 Bd1 80. Ke3 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ge3d2]}
1-0

