{Some French lines are directly related to the endgame. A typical example was
seen in the game Andreikin - Pelletier, 2019. After the moves} 1. e4 e6 2. d4
d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 {
Black immediately forced the transition into an endgame by means of} Bxd4 10.
Bxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qb6 12. Qxb6 Nxb6 {A very important endgame for the
understanding of the French Defence. White usually tries to establish a
blockade on the d4-square by means of the manoeuvre Nb5-d4. The bishop will be
perfectly placed on d3. Then White will try to win space on both wings. On the
other hand, Black usually tries to strike on the kingside with ...f7-f6 or ...
g7-g5 (sometimes these breaks are being combined). Another typical idea for
Black is to close the queenside and exchange the minor pieces. Andreikin
started with the natural} 13. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d4] bringing the knight to d4.} Ke7
14. b3 {This move is not one-sided. Despite restricting the knight, White
wastes an important tempo, thus giving Black the possibility to organize his
kingside counterplay.} f6 {By all means, a logical decision.} ({Even more
energetic would have been} 14... g5 {when after the natural sequence} 15. g3
Bd7 16. Nd4 gxf4 17. gxf4 f6 18. exf6+ {Black should find the thematic} Kd6 $1
{[%cal Ga8f8,Gf8f6] planning to take the f6-pawn with the rook. With the black
rook being on f6, White should always pay attention to the vulnerable kingside
pawns. An exemplary line would be} 19. Kd2 Raf8 20. Bd3 Rxf6 21. Ke3 Nc8 22.
Rhg1 Rhf8 23. Raf1 Rh6 $11 {The counterplay against h2 and f4-pawns gives
Black enough counterplay in this position.}) 15. Kd2 Bd7 16. Nd4 fxe5 {Black
was not forced to immediately clarify the kingside structure.} ({In my opinion,
a more flexible option would have been} 16... Raf8 {[%cal Gg7g5] keeping the
opportunity of striking with ...g7-g5.}) 17. fxe5 Raf8 18. g3 {White managed
to restrict Black's direct counterplay. Therefore, he is already slightly
better.} g5 $6 {This is already a mistake. White can now activate his rook by
playing h2-h4.} ({Better would have been} 18... Be8 {[%cal Gb6d7] planning ...
Nd7. The knight has no job on b6.}) 19. h4 $1 Rhg8 $2 {This move allows White
to exchange the kingside pawns as well as a pair of rooks. In this case, Black
will be deprived of any counterplay. As we are going to see, White can even
consider exchanging both rooks due to the obvious superiority of his minor
pieces.} ({Black should have played} 19... gxh4 20. Rxh4 h5 {[%cal Gd7e8,Gh8g8]
followed by ...Be8 and ...Rhg8. In this way, he keeps some potential for
counterplay.}) 20. hxg5 Rxg5 21. Rxh7+ Rf7 22. Rxf7+ Kxf7 23. Bd3 Rxg3 24. Rf1+
Ke7 25. Rh1 {[%cal Gh1h7] Now, Black cannot prevent the white rook from
invading via the h-file. As pointed out earlier, the exchange of the rooks
does not help Black. White enjoys the tremendous activity of his minor pieces.
Additionally, the king can easily reach the c5-square. This is what more or
less happened in the game.} a6 26. Rh7+ Kf8 $2 {This move allows White to
force the transition into a winning endgame.} ({A good saving chance would
have been} 26... Kd8 {[%cal Gb6c8,Gc8e7] keeping the bishop protected and
planning to bring the knight into play via the route c8-e7. It's not clear how
White can breakthrough. A typical example of a case when the passive "French
bishop" is holding the position.} 27. Rh8+ Kc7 ({But not} 27... Ke7 $2 28. Rb8
$18 {when White is winning on the spot.} Bc8 {will be met by} 29. Bxa6 $1 $18)
28. Rh6 Rg5 29. Nf3 ({After} 29. Nxe6+ $2 Bxe6 30. Rxe6 Nd7 $11 {Black regains
the e5-pawn with a draw.}) 29... Rg2+ 30. Ke3 Nc8 {Black should activate the
knight even at the price of the e6-pawn. After} 31. Nd4 Ne7 32. Nxe6+ Bxe6 33.
Rxe6 Nc6 $14 {/= It should be a draw. White cannot activate his rook.}) 27. a4
{[%cal Ga4a5] This is the point. The threat is a4-a5.} Rg7 28. Rh8+ Rg8 29.
Rxg8+ Kxg8 30. a5 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3b4,Gb4c5] Fixing the b7-pawn
before bringing the king towards the c5-square.} Nc8 31. Kc3 Kf7 32. Kb4 Ke7
33. Kc5 Be8 34. c4 $1 {The final finesse. After exchanging the d5-pawn, White
makes the e4-square available for the bishop.} dxc4 35. bxc4 {[%csl Rb7][%cal
Gd3e4] Black resigned since the b7-pawn will be lost after Be4.} 1-0

