{[#] In the previous example, we have seen that even when not playing in the
most accurate way, Black enjoys a big safety margin in this endgame. Now, we
shall take a look at an example featuring Black's best possible play. The
position on the diagram occurred in the game Socko - Gurevich. In this
position, the big French expert Gurevich played the subtle and very instructive
} 15... a6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c8,Gc8a7,Ga7c6] This move introduces a very deep
concept. Black wants to manoeuvre his knight to c6 via the route b6-c8-a7-c6.
The exchange of the knights dramatically reduces White's winning chances.
Black's second thematic idea is to neutralize White's kingside play.} 16. Bd3
Nc8 17. g4 Na7 18. c3 Nc6 19. Nf3 {Being an experienced player, Socko refrains
from the exchange of the knight. Now, however, the f4-pawn, as well as the
f3-knight, are vulnerable. Therefore, Gurevich immediately plays} Raf8 {
[%cal Gf7f6] indicating his intention of following with ...f7-f6.} 20. g5 h6
21. h4 h5 $1 22. Kd2 g6 {The kingside is already closed. Now, White does not
have winning chances since Black didn't make any concessions on the queenside.
The next step is to provoke the exchange of the knights.} 23. Ke3 Rc8 24. Rh2
Rc7 25. Rc2 Rhc8 26. Rdc1 Kd8 27. a3 {[%cal Gc3c4] After taking the b4-square
under control, White is preparing his only constructive idea - the advance
c3-c4. Of course, nobody is going to allow that.} Na5 28. Nd4 Ba4 29. Rf2 Ke7
30. Rb1 Nc6 {Finally, Black manages to force the exchange of the knights.} 31.
Nxc6+ Rxc6 {The position is completely equal. White, however, should make sure
that the bishops will not be exchanged. In the rook endgame, Black is going to
have a slight advantage, due to the semi-open c-file and White's overextended
structure. Additionally, Black will start preparing the advance ...b5-b4.} 32.
Rd2 Bb3 33. Be2 Bc4 34. Bf3 Rb6 35. Bd1 Bb3 36. Be2 Ba4 37. Rc1 Bb5 38. Bd1 Bc4
39. Rb1 Bb5 40. Rc1 Bc4 {The draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

