{Sometimes, Black manages to exchange his light-squared bishop by tactical
means. This position occurred in the game Volokitin - Luther, 2014. White has
just played the natural 16.Bd3, failing to see the intention behind Black's ...
a7-a6.} 16... Bb5 $1 17. Bxb5 $6 {This is already a serious inaccuracy.} ({
Actually, after} 17. Rhe1 {Black should play the precise} g6 $1 {preventing
f4-f5.} ({The position arising after} 17... Bxd3 $6 18. Rxd3 {[%cal Gd3b3] is
not so easy to hold. In general, knight endgames are favourable for the side
with a space advantage. Therefore, Black should handle such positions with a
lot of precision. Now, the threat of Rb3 is very annoying.} Rab8 ({After} 18...
Nd7 19. Rb3 Nc5 {The knight is usually misplaced on c5 since it's impossible
to exchange the d4-monster. After} 20. Rb6 Rhc8 21. Re3 Rc7 22. Rc3 Rac8 {
White can keep winning kingside space by means of} 23. f5 $16 {Black is under
huge pressure.}) 19. Rb3 Nd7 {[%cal Gg7g6] Black would be doing fine if he is
allowed to play ...f7-f6. Unfortunately, White is the first to strike} 20. f5
$14 {with a slight but lasting advantage.} (20. Kb1 g6 $11)) 18. Bxb5 axb5 19.
a3 {It turns out that Black has time for} Ra4 {[%cal Gb5b4] planning ...b5-b4.}
20. c3 {Due to the unprotected f4-pawn, Black can execute the thematic
manoeuvre} Nc8 21. Rf1 Na7 $11 {[%cal Gh7h5] followed by ...h7-h5. After
overprotecting the b5-pawn, Black will play the thematic ...Nc6.}) 17... axb5 {
[%cal Gb5b4] When the b-pawn does not drop by force, this recapture is an
improvement of Black's pawn structure. Besides bringing the a8-rook into play,
Black has the possibility of gaining queenside space by means of ...b5-b4,
thus fixing the pawns on a2 and c2.} 18. Kb1 {This move allows ...b5-b4.} ({
Probably, Volokitin initially calculated} 18. a3 {It turns out, however, that
after} b4 $1 19. axb4 Nc4 $1 {[%cal Ga8a1]} 20. Kb1 Ra4 {[%cal Gh8a8] White
cannot keep his extra pawn in view of the doubled threat ...Rfa8 and ...Rxb4.
A possible follow-up would be} 21. b3 Rxb4 22. Rhe1 Ra8 23. Re2 Na3+ 24. Kb2
Nb5 $1 {Exchanging the knights and solving all possible issues.} 25. c3 Nxd4
26. Rxd4 Rxd4 27. cxd4 $11 {with a draw.}) 18... b4 19. Ne2 Nc4 20. Rd4 Rhc8 {
[%cal Gc8c6,Ga8c8] With a pawn on b4, putting pressure on c2 is a thematic
idea. Black is planning to double the rooks. Nevertheless, White has enough
resources to keep control.} 21. Rc1 Rc6 22. Re1 {Lacking any constructive
ideas, White sticks to the waiting policy.} Rac8 23. Nc1 Rb6 24. Nd3 b3 $1 {
Even without queens, Luther keeps finding attacking possibilities on the
queenside.} 25. cxb3 Nd2+ 26. Ka1 Rbc6 {Black's overwhelming activity provides
enough compensation for the pawn.} 27. f5 Rc2 (27... Ne4 $132) 28. fxe6 fxe6
29. Rf4 g5 30. Rf6 Ne4 31. Rh6 Kf7 32. g4 $4 {So far, both players were
playing in the best possible way, thus keeping the position balanced. The last
move, however, is a blunder.} ({After} 32. a4 Rxg2 33. Rxh7+ Kg6 34. Rxb7 $11 {
The position remains complex but dynamically equal.}) 32... Kg7 $1 {This
intermediate move decides the game. The idea is to meet} 33. Rxe6 {with} Nf2
$19 {making use of the weak backrank. Black is already winning. Volokitin
resigned in a few moves.} 34. Re7+ Kg8 35. Rxb7 Nxd3 36. Rb1 Nxe5 37. a4 d4 38.
Re1 Rc1+ 39. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 40. Ka2 d3 41. Rb8+ Kf7 42. Rd8 Nc6 0-1

