{[#]} 24... a5 $1 {This is the right approach to the position. Black is
planning to fix White's queenside by means of ...a5-a4, thus making the
squares c4 and b3 available for his knights.} 25. f4 a4 26. Nd2 Na5 {[%cal
Gb6b5,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] White's pieces are already tied to the defence of the
queenside weaknesses. The next step is to expand on the queenside with ...
b6-b5 followed by ...Nb6. White has to stick to the waiting strategy.} 27. Rab1
b5 28. Ke2 Nb6 29. Nd3 Rc2 {[%cal Gb6c4] with ...Nbc4 to follow. Even though
White's position remains defendable, Black is the one fighting for a win.} ({
The game continued} 29... Rc2 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 30. Rdc1 Rxc1 31. Rxc1 Rxc1 32.
Nxc1 Nbc4 33. Nd3 g6 34. Nb1 gxh5 35. gxh5 Nc6 36. Nc3 Na7 37. Bc1 Kg7 38. Kf3
f5 39. exf6+ Bxf6 40. Be3 Kf7 41. Ne5+ Ke7 42. Ng4 Bg7 43. Bc1 Nd6 44. Ne5 Nf5
45. Be3 Kd6 46. Bf2 Kc7 47. Ke2 Kb6 48. Nd7+ Kc7 49. Ne5 Bf6 50. Kd3 Be7 51.
Nd1 Nc6 52. Ng4 Bd6 53. Nde3 Bxf4 54. Nxf5 exf5 55. Be3 Bxe3 56. Nxe3 Ne7 57.
Ke2 Kd6 58. Kf3 Ke6 59. Kf4 Kf6 60. Nd1 Nc6 61. Ke3 Kg5 62. Nc3 f4+ 63. Kd3
Kxh5 64. Nxd5 Kg4 65. Nc3 f3 66. Ke3 Kg3 67. Ne4+ Kg2 68. d5 Ne5 69. Kf4 Nc4
70. Kg4 f2 71. Nxf2 Kxf2 72. Kh5 Ke3 {0:1, Molina, R - Tran, Minh Thang, 2016.}
) *

