{[#]} 24... a5 $1 {A typical way of undermining White's queenside structure.
Now, White is forced to accept queenside weaknesses.} 25. bxa5 bxa5 26. Bf2 a4
$1 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gc6a5] Another very important move, fixing the a3-pawn.
Black's next move is going to be ...Na5.} ({The game continued} 26... a4 $1 27.
f5 Na5 28. fxe6 fxe6 29. h3 Nc4 30. Qg6 Qf7 31. Qg4 Nxe5 32. Qd1 Nc4 33. Nxc4
dxc4 34. Rc3 Qd7 35. Bg3 Bd6 36. Bxd6 Qxd6 37. Kh1 Qd5 38. Qxa4 Qxd4 39. Qb4
Qf4 40. Rf3 Qe5 41. Qb7 Rb8 42. Qf7+ Kh7 43. Qf4 Qxf4 44. Rxf4 Rc8 45. Rf2 Kg6
46. Kg1 c3 47. Rc2 Kf5 48. Kf2 Ke4 49. Ke2 Kd4 50. Kd1 Kd3 51. Rf2 Rb8 52. Kc1
Rb7 53. Rf3+ Kc4 54. Rf4+ Kb3 55. Rf8 Kxa3 56. Kc2 Kb4 57. Re8 Ra7 58. Rb8+ Kc4
59. Rc8+ Kd4 60. Rd8+ Ke4 61. Kxc3 Ra3+ 62. Kc4 Ra2 63. Rd4+ Ke3 64. Rg4 Ra4+ {
