{[#] We already know this multi-purpose move. Black wants to fix the queenside
structure by means of ...a5-a4.} 18... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 19. Rc2 Na7 {
[%cal Ga7b5,Ga5a4] Another thematic move. After ...a5-a4, the b5-square is
usually very suitable for the knight.} 20. Rdc1 a4 21. Bd2 Rxc2 22. Rxc2 Rc8
23. Rxc8+ Nxc8 {After exchanging all the rooks, Black has a stable risk-free
advantage without any counterplay for White. Now, his idea is to put maximum
pressure on d4 in order to force the white pieces into passive positions.} 24.
Ne1 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8a7,Ga7b5] The knights are going to occupy the squares
c6 and b5. Remember this thematic knight play in the endgame.} 25. Nd3 Nc6 26.
Ne2 N8a7 27. Ne1 Nb5 28. Nc2 f6 $1 {After improving the position to the
maximum, Black opts for this typical break. In order to keep his centre, White
should play the commital} 29. f4 {when after} f5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Gh7h5,
Gh5h4] Black is ready to open a second front of action by gaining space on the
kingside. Even though White's position is holdable, the defence is annoying.} (
29... f5 30. Kf2 Kf7 31. Ke3 h6 32. Kd3 g5 33. g3 g4 34. Nc3 Nxc3 35. Bxc3 Ke8
36. Ne3 Kd7 37. Nd1 b5 38. Bd2 Kc7 39. Nf2 Kb6 40. h4 h5 41. Nd1 Na5 42. Bxa5+
Kxa5 43. Nc3 b4 44. axb4+ Kxb4 45. Na2+ Kb3 46. Nc3 Bb4 {Black won in the game
Isha, S - Goryachkina, A, 2020.}) *

