{Black's last move ...bxc6 was a terrible mistake. Now, Black is just lost in
view of his passive bishop and terrible queenside structure.} 22. Kd4 {[%cal
Gd4c5] The king is heading to c5. White should never allow the advance ...
c6-c5.} Rhb8 23. Kc5 Kd8 24. Ra4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b4] Both white rooks will use
the b4-square as a springboard.} Kc7 25. Rha1 Bc8 26. Rb4 Rxb4 27. Kxb4 Rb8+
28. Kc5 h4 29. Ra4 $1 {Zugzwang. Black is forced to surrender the b-file.} Bb7
30. Rb4 Rd8 31. Rb6 Ra8 32. g3 {Since Black is completely tied to the
queenside weaknesses, White can start playing on the other wing. Once again,
we see the principle of two weaknesses.} hxg3 33. hxg3 Ra7 34. b4 $1 {[%csl
Ra6,Rc6][%cal Gc5d4,Gd4e3,Ge3f3,Gf3g4,Gb4c5] Before bringing the king to the
kingside, White fixes the queenside structure. The rest is simple. White
managed to win in the game Yospeh, T - Grachev, B, 2020} *

