{[#]} 27... Rc6 $1 {Very well played. In this structure, Black's main idea is
to create a central passed pawn with ...e6-e5. Beforehand, however, he wants
to exchange a pair of rooks.} 28. Rbxc6 Nxc6 29. Kf2 Kd6 30. Ke3 e5 31. dxe5+
Kxe5 {Even though the position remains balanced, Black's play is easier due to
his central passed pawn. On the other hand, White's kingside majority is not
that mobile.} (31... Kxe5 32. Rc1 Re8 33. Kd2 Kd6 34. Ng3 Rf8 35. Re1 Ne5 36.
b3 a5 37. Ne2 a4 38. Nd4 axb3 39. axb3 Ra8 40. f4 Ra2+ 41. Bc2 Nc6 42. Nb5+ Kc5
43. Nc3 Ra5 44. h3 Kd6 45. g4 Nd4 46. Kd3 Ne6 47. f5 Nf4+ 48. Kd4 Nxh3 49. b4
Ra3 50. Nxd5 Ng5 51. Re3 Ra2 52. Rc3 Bc6 53. Nb6 Ra1 54. Nc4+ Ke7 55. Ne5 Kd6
56. Nc4+ Ke7 57. Ne5 Kd6 58. Nc4+ {The draw was agreed in the game Can, E -
Gurevich, M, 2006.}) *

