{[%evp 0,42,25,30,30,33,46,46,47,44,57,49,49,25,33,17,18,11,39,45,45,51,51,51,
51,48,27,30,29,24,24,-16,-4,-28,-21,-29,-29,-34,-15,-23,-18,-56,-56,-60,15]} 1.
e4 {In this file, I tried to give an overview of the various plans in the 4+2
vs 3+3 pawn structure. It is one of the most common ones as it can arise from
multiple openings: most often from the French Defense or the Caro-Kann. I am
will focus on the position specifics from Black's side of view (the side with
4+2 pawns) and provide some general guidelines on how to navigate it. As a
reminder, the idea of this session is not to focus on theory but rather to
analyze typical middlegames.} e6 (1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 (
4... Nf6 5. Ng3 e6) 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ng3 (6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {[%cal Ye7e6,Yc6c5]})
6... e6 {[%cal Yc6c5] achieves the same structure}) 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 {The
typical position we are interested in can be reached if Black takes on e4 or
plays the 3...c5 line} dxe4 (3... c5 {I find this line to be the most
trustworthy for Black} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3
Nf6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 $11 {White regains the pawn and thus we arrive at
the 3+3 vs 4+2 structure. If one is interested in how to navigate the position
from White's point of view, I recommend studying the games of GM Sergey
Tiviakov who is a big expert here}) 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ng3 (6. Nxf6+ $5
Nxf6 7. Bd3 (7. c3 Be7 {At some point Black has to play c5 and transform the
structure} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O b6 {A very interesting way of playing- Black
delays c5 in order to develop his pieces and better prepare it} 10. Bg5 Bb7 11.
Qe2 {Black has two viable alternatives:} Qc8 {[%cal Yc7c5] or} (11... c5 12.
dxc5 Bxc5 {The first critical position for the game: White has to settle on a
plan} 13. Rfe1 (13. Rad1 {The most direct continuation} Qc7 {Oftentimes Black
leaves White the option to take on f6 in exchange for the dark-squared bishop.
Black has enough resources to defend his king after gxf6 as White does not
have a direct attack.The game evaluation is about equal- the crippled pawns on
the kingside are compensated by the strong bishops} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Be4 Rfd8
{[%cal Yc5f8,Yf8g7]}) (13. Ne5 Be7 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Bf4 {This specific move
order White forces Black to play Bd6 as Qc8 is undesirable due to it blocking
Ra8}) 13... Be7 14. Rad1 {A most natural way of developing for White. Next, he
is planning to jump Ne5, play Bb1, Qc2 and build up pressure against the Black
king. Additional ideas he has, include doubling the rooks along the d-file and
get a grasp on the dark squares with Bf4 at some moment. For these reasons,
Black needs to be very careful with his next moves, or he risks ending up worse
} Qc7 15. Ne5 Rad8 16. Bf4 Bd6 {Somewhat forced} 17. Bg3 {At first glance, it
appears that Black doesn't have any good options- he cannot take on e5, Nd5 is
pointless, etc. However, there is a very interesting continuation that ensures
Black retains the balance:} (17. Bb1 Rfe8 18. Qc2 $4 Be4 (18... h6 19. a3 Be4
$3 $17 20. Rxe4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Bxe5 $19) 19. Rxe4) 17... Ba8 $3 $11 {The idea
is to open up a square for the queen. After Qb7, White will be forced to make
a concession of some sort: either impair his structure with f3/ f4 or bind a
piece to defend g2} (17... Rfe8 {is also possible but after} 18. Bb1 {Black
needs to play Ba8 again as there is no other good plan}) 18. Bc2 Qb7 19. Nf3 (
19. f3 {The major problem with this move is that it weakens the dark squares
on the kingside. Another drawback is that it allows Black to activate his
knight:} Nh5 (19... Qc7 {[%cal Yg3c7] Black always needs to look out for this
tactic} 20. Rxd6 Rxd6) (19... Bc5+)) (19. Qf1 Bc7 $11 {Black stands great-
over the next couple of moves he will start trading pieces along the d-file
and use the more active position of his queen}) (19. f4 {is overly optimistic.
White does not have the necessary control of the center to start such an
attack: a lot of pieces will be traded soon and f4 will become a weakness.} Be7
{I use this move to make a more general point} (19... Bc5+ $15 {is better in
this particular position}) 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Rd1 Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 Nd7 23. Nxd7
Qxd7 24. Ba4 {The played moves serve to get to a position with the right piece
balance. Black's goal is: to reach an endgame where f4 will constantly need
protection} Bc6 25. Bxc6 Qxc6 26. Bf2 g6 {The fact that White's pawns are on
the same color as his bishop makes Black's position preferable} (26... Bf6))
19... Bxg3 20. hxg3 {As a general guideline, the exchange of the dark-squared
bishops benefits Black because his king cannot come under serious attack
anymore. The position is objectively equal, but in practical terms, it is
easier to play as Black. White's defect in the pawn structure might not seem
like a lot but is a potential weakness} Qc7 21. a4 $2 Bxf3 $1 (21... a5 22. Nd4
) 22. gxf3 g6 (22... a5) 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Rd1 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Kf8 (25... h5)
26. Qd4 Ke7 $15) (11... h6 {maybe the most precise} 12. Bh4 Qd5 $11 {[%cal
Yd5h5]}) 12. Rad1 c5 13. Bb1 (13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Ne5 Rad8 15. Rfe1 (15. Bxf6
Bxf6 $17 16. Nd7 $4 Rxd7 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Rxd7 Qc6) 15... Qc7 16. Bf4 Bd6 17.
Bc2 Ba8 $132 18. Bg3 Qb7 19. Nf3 (19. f3 Qe7 $132) 19... Bxg3 20. hxg3 Qc7) (
13. Rfe1 Bxf3 (13... Rd8) (13... cxd4) 14. Qxf3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nd5 $36) 13...
Qc6) 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 b6 10. c3 (10. Bxf6 $2 Bxf6 11. Be4 Rb8 12. c3
c5 (12... Bb7 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Re1 c5 (14... Qc8) 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Qxd8 Rxd8)
13. dxc5 bxc5 $17 14. Qe2 Qb6 15. Rab1 Ba6 16. Bd3 Bb7 17. c4 (17. Be4 Qa6 $3
$17 18. Rfe1 Qxe2 19. Rxe2 Ba6) 17... Bxf3 $1 $19 (17... Rbd8 18. Be4) 18. Qxf3
Bd4 19. Rfe1 g6 20. Qe4 a5 21. Bc2 Rbd8 22. h3 h5 23. Qe2 h4 24. Qg4 Bf6 25.
Qf3 Kg7) 10... Bb7 11. Qe2 c5 $5 (11... Qc8 $5 12. Rad1 (12. Rfe1 c5 13. dxc5 (
13. Rad1 Bxf3 $1 {An important decision that changes the character of the
position. Black is doing well as he is able to block the pawn with Nd5 and
proceed with g6, Bf6 (White needs to avoid the exchange of dark-squared
bishops)} (13... cxd4 {is playable as well}) (13... c4 $2 {is bad for a number
of reasons: 1) if White takes the pawn, Black has no compensation 2) even if
he retreats the bishop, he stands positionally much better and all the
opportunities to start an attack on the kingside} 14. Bxc4 (14. Bc2) 14... Bxf3
15. gxf3 $18) 14. Qxf3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nd5 (15... Qd7 16. Bb1 Nd5 17. Qd3 g6 18.
Bh6 Rfd8 $11) 16. Bc1 Bf6 17. Qe4 g6 $11) 13... Qxc5 14. Bh4 (14. Rad1 $4 {
loses a piece} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxg5) 14... Rfd8 (14... Rad8 15. Rad1 Qc7 {
The queen will need to go back to c7 at some point} 16. Ne5 Ba8 {Again the
familiar idea!} 17. Ba6 {If White prevents Qb7, Black has other tricks up his
sleeve:} Ne4 (17... Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 {is the dry equalizer approach}) 18. Bxe7
Qxe7 $11) 15. a4 (15. c4 $2 Rac8 16. Qe5 Qxe5 17. Nxe5 Nd5 (17... Rd4 $17 {
[%cal Ye7d6]}) 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Rad1 f6 20. Ng4 Kf7 21. Ne3 e5 22. b4 Nc6 (
22... a5 23. a3) (22... g6) 23. Be4) 15... Rac8 16. Qe5 Qxe5 17. Nxe5 Nd5 18.
Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Rad1 f6 20. Ng4 Kf7 21. Ne3 e5 22. Be2 (22. c4 a5) 22... Kf8 23.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. b4 Rc8 25. c4 Nc6 (25... a5) 26. Rb1 Nd4 $15) 12... c5 13. dxc5
Qxc5 14. Ne5 Rad8 15. Bc2 Qc7 16. Rfe1 (16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Rd1 $2 Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1
(18. Qxd1 Qxe5) 18... Bd6 $17 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nf3 f5 21. h3 Be7 22. Bb3 Bf6
$17) (16. Bf4 Qc8 (16... Bd6 17. Rfe1 (17. Rxd6 $2 Rxd6 18. Nc4 Qc6 $1 $19)
17... Ba8 $3 $11 18. Bg3 Qb7 19. Nf3 (19. f3 Nh5) 19... Bxg3 20. hxg3 Qc7 21.
Bb3 Bxf3 22. Qxf3 h5 $15 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Rd1 Rxd1+ 25. Bxd1 Qe5 26. Qe2 Qd6
27. Bc2 g6 $15) 17. Rfe1 Ba8) 16... Ba8 $3 17. h3 Qb7 18. f3 (18. Nf3 Rxd1 19.
Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 21. Qd3 (21. Qd2 Be7 22. c4 h6 23. Bf4 a5 24. a3 Qc6 (
24... Qd7 25. Qxd7 Nxd7) 25. Bd3 a4 $1 (25... Nd7) 26. Qe2 Nd7 27. Bc2 Bf6 (
27... Nc5) 28. Bc1 Nc5 $15) 21... Qd5 22. Qxd5 Bxd5 23. Nd2 h6 24. Bxf6 (24.
Bh4 g5) 24... Bxf6 25. Bb3 Bc6 $17 26. Bc2 h5 27. Be4 Bb5 (27... Bd7) 28. c4 $2
Bd7 29. b3 g5 30. Nf3 Kf8 $17) 18... Qc7 19. Bxf6 Bxf6) 12. dxc5 bxc5 (12...
Bxc5 13. Rad1 (13. Rfe1 Be7 14. Rad1 Qc7 $14) 13... Qc7 $14) 13. Rad1 Qc7 14.
Rfe1 (14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Be4 Bxe4 (15... a5 16. Nd2 Ba6 17. Bd3 Bb7 18. Nc4 Rad8
19. Be4 Ba6 20. Bd3 g6 21. h3 h5 22. Bxg6 (22. Rfe1 Bxc4 23. Bxc4 h4 $17)) 16.
Qxe4) (14. c4 Rad8 (14... Bxf3 $2) 15. Ne5 Ba8 (15... Rd4 $15) 16. f4 g6 17.
Rfe1 Nh5 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Qf2 Rd4) 14... Rad8 15. Bc2 (15. Ne5 Ba8 16. c4 Qb7
17. f3 Qc7 $14) (15. c4 Qc6 $3 16. Bc2 h6 17. Bh4 (17. Bxf6 Bxf6 $17) 17...
Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. Qd3 Be7 21. Bxf6 $2 Bxf6 $17 22. Qh7+ Kf8
23. Qd3 (23. Qh8+ Ke7) 23... Qb6 24. b3 Bxf3 $1 25. Qxf3 Qd8 26. Qd3 Bd4 (26...
Qc8 27. Qd6+ Be7 28. Qd3 g6 29. Qc3 Kg8 30. Qe5 h5 31. h3 h4 32. Be4 a5 33. Bf3
Qd8 34. Qe3 Qd6 35. Qe2 Bf6 36. Qd1 Bd4 37. Qd2 Qc7 38. a3 Qd8 39. b4 axb4 40.
axb4 cxb4 41. Qxb4 Qc7 42. Qd2 Bc5 43. Qd1 Qf4 44. Qe2 Kg7 45. Qb2+ Bd4 46. Qe2
Qc1+ 47. Qf1 Qc3 48. Qe2 Kf8 49. Qf1 f5 50. Qe2 Kf7 51. Qf1 Kf6 52. Qe2 e5 53.
Bd5 e4) 27. Qd2 (27. g3 Qf6 28. Qe2 g6 29. Kg2 Kg7 30. Qf3 Qd8 31. Qe2 Qa5 32.
Bd3 Qc7 (32... Qc3 33. Qc2) 33. h4 h5 34. Qd2 a5 35. Qe2 Qd6 36. Bc2 f5 37. f4
Qb6 38. Qd2 Qc6+ 39. Kh2 Qf3 40. Qg2 Qe3 41. Qb7+ Kf6 42. Qg2 Qc1 43. Bd3 Qa1)
27... h5 $1 28. h3 $2 h4 29. Qf4 (29. Qe2 g6 30. Qf3 Kg7 31. Qe2 Qg5 32. Qd1
Qf4 33. Qe1 a5 34. Bd3 f5 35. Bf1 e5 36. Bd3 e4 37. Bc2 Kf6 (37... Be5)) 29...
Kg8 30. Be4 g6 31. Bc2 Kg7 32. a3 a5 33. Be4 Bf6 34. Qc1 Qd4 35. Bf3 Be5 36.
Qd1 Qb2 37. a4 Bd4 38. Be2 f5) (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Be4 Bc8 $1 (16... g6 17. Bxb7
Qxb7 $15) 17. h3 Qb6 18. Qc2 (18. Bc2) 18... g6 19. Nd2 Ba6 $15) 15... Qc6) ({
Some sample lines to illustrate the typical ideas in the position} 6. Bg5 $5
Be7 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Again, it is in Black's interests to trade the dark-squared
bishops. The reason is that after such an operation the defender of the king-
Nf6- will be invulnerable} 8. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Quiet position where it is more
important to have a good plan} 9. Bd3 (9. Bb5+ c6 {Black has plenty of tempi
to develop and push c5 after. The absence of the dark-squared bishops means
that there is no danger for the Black king} (9... Bd7 10. Bd3 $11) 10. Bd3 O-O
11. O-O b6 12. c3 Bb7 13. Qe2 Qc7 {Black got comfortable play out of the
opening} 14. Rad1 c5 $11 {An already familiar position} 15. dxc5 (15. Rfe1 $2 {
A positional mistake that can only be good for Black in the long run} Bxf3 $1
16. Qxf3 cxd4 17. cxd4 Qd6 $15 {A perfect square for the queen from where it
controls a lot of important squares. From d6, it is always ready to assist an
attack on either side of the board}) 15... Qxc5 $1 (15... bxc5 $11 {also
playable but a bit unnecessary. Such an approach is justified when the
dark-squared bishops are already exchanged}) (15... h6 {Played for
illustrative purposes- the idea is to analyze the structure when White has
pushed c4} 16. c4 bxc5 {The following structure is much better for Black as he
is able to neutralize White's queenside majority with c5 and a5. The c4 pawn
restricting the bishop and the semi-open b-file are other pluses he can try to
take advantage of} (16... Bxf3 $3 $17 17. Qxf3 bxc5) 17. Ne5 a5 18. f4 {
is an example of overextending} Rad8 19. g4 $2 {White only weakens his king} (
19. Rfe1 Rd4 $17 {There is not a single Black piece that isn't active. Black
controls the center and has a clear plan: doubling the rooks on the d-file.} (
19... Nd7 {serves as an example to show that even such a passive approach does
not give White anything} 20. Nxd7 $6 Rxd7 $17 21. Qf2 Rdd8 22. Bf1 {The
computer says the position is equal but such an evaluation does not take into
account that humans do not always make perfect moves. In practice, it is
trickier to play here as White because his pawns need constant protection}))
19... Nd7 $17) 16. Bc2 Rad8 {I want to focus on a typical endgame that might
arise here:} 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Rd1 Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 {Black wants to keep the
queens on board since White's king is more vulnerable} g6 {Opening a square
for the king and blocking Bc2} 20. h3 Bxf3 $1 {A very sound strategical
decision after which Black does not ever risk losing! The White bishop is
restricted in his actions whereas the black knight is free to maneuver around}
(20... Kg7 21. Qe2 Bxf3 $15 {Black prevents the knight from coming to e5} 22.
Qxf3 a5 {Placing the pawns on dark squares so they cannot be attacked} (22...
Qc8 {The passive moves are played on purpose to illustrate that even if the
White queen gets to infiltrate Black's camp it cannot do anything} 23. Bd3 Qd8
24. Bf1 h6 25. Qb7 a5 {Objectively, the position is equal but in a practical
sense it is more pleasant for Black}) 23. Qe2 g5 {A typical idea to gain space
on the kingside. Nf6 perfectly protects the light squares meanwhile the queen
and g5 pawn take care of the dark ones} 24. Qd2 Qe5 {Centralization is critical
}) 21. Qxf3 Kg7 22. a4 $2 (22. Qd1 $17 Qd5 $2 (22... Qe5) (22... h5 23. h4 (23.
a3 h4 $1 24. Qc1 g5 $3 25. Qd2 Qe5) 23... Qc4 24. Bb3 Qxh4)) 22... a5) 9... O-O
10. O-O b6 11. c4 $6 {A bad move- White cannot afford such active operations
without the support of his dark-squared bishop} (11. c3 {More solid course of
action} Bb7 12. Qe2 Qe7 {Black prepares c5 instead of pushing it directly} (
12... c5 13. dxc5 Bxf3 {keeps the position equal} (13... bxc5 14. Ne5 {Here,
the c5 pawn may become weak. Another factor that favors White is the position
of the c pawn- from c3 (and not c4) it supports the creation of a passed pawn
in a future endgame} (14. c4 {is a terrible positional mistake} Bxf3 15. Qxf3
Qb6)) 14. Qxf3 bxc5) (12... Qd5) (12... Qc8 $5 13. Rad1 c5 14. dxc5 (14. Rfe1
$6 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qd7 $15) 14... Qxc5 15. a4 (15. Ra1 h6 16. a4
Bxf3 (16... a5 17. Nd4 Rad8 $15) 17. Qxf3 a5 $11)) (12... Bxf3 {is unnecessary
here} 13. Qxf3 Qd6 {Even though the position is still very much playable for
Black, this version is not as good compared to the one with a pawn on c4}) 13.
Rfd1 c5 14. dxc5 (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qd6 $15) 14... Qxc5 15.
Bc2 (15. a4) 15... Rad8 (15... Qc6 $5) 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Rd1 Rxd1+ 18. Qxd1 g6
{[%cal Yg8g7,Yb7f3,Ya7a5] Once again, we get to this topical endgame. As
mentioned before, Black is doing more than fine and is on track to improve his
pieces} 19. h3 (19. Qe2 Kg7 (19... Bxf3 {is a practical chance Black can go for
} 20. Qxf3 Qe5 21. g3 a5 22. Kg2 Kg7 23. a3) 20. c4 $2 (20. Qe5 {Black should
keep in mind that if he wants to play for a win, he has to keep the queens on
board!} Bxf3 (20... Qxe5 21. Nxe5 {is just equal, and things have to go
horribly wrong for Black in order for him to lose. White's queenside majority
does not mean anything by itself})) 20... Bxf3 21. gxf3 a5 22. Ba4 Nh5 23. Bb5
Qg5+) 19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Kg7 21. a4 a5 (21... b5 22. axb5 $6 Qxb5 23. b4 $17
Qc4) 22. Qe2 Qd5 23. b4 $2 Qd6 24. bxa5 bxa5 25. Qb5 Qd2 $19 (25... Qc7 26. c4
Nd7 (26... Kg8 $2 27. c5 Nd7 28. c6) 27. Qb2+ Qe5 (27... Kg8 28. Qb5 Nc5 29.
Qe8+ Kg7 30. Qb5 h5 31. Qb2+ e5 32. Qc1 Qd6 33. Qb1 Qd4 (33... Qd2 34. Qb5) 34.
Qb5 e4 35. Qxa5 Qxc4 (35... Nd3 36. Bxd3 exd3)) 28. Qxe5+ Nxe5 29. c5 (29. Bb3
Nd3))) 11... Bb7 12. Be2 (12. Re1 c5 {Let's suppose Bxf3 isn't possible for
the sake of the example} (12... Bxf3 {is devastating for White} 13. gxf3 c5 14.
dxc5 bxc5 $17 15. Qe2 Qc7 16. Rad1 a5 17. Qc2 Rad8 18. Be4 g6 19. Kg2 Nh5) 13.
dxc5 Bxf3 {An important intermezzo: the move ensures that White is left with a
bad bishop on d3. Note: Bxf3 is a strong idea when the dark-squared bishops
have already been exchanged} 14. Qxf3 bxc5 {Black has great control over the
dark squares while White has nothing to show for that} 15. Re3 (15. Be4 {
is just a one-move threat} Rc8 16. Rad1 Qb6 17. b3 $15 Rcd8 18. g3 a5 {Black
placed all his army on dark squares and is gradually taking over after Rd4,
Rfd8. He is the side with an active plan- e.g. a5-a4 or g6, f5, e5 at some
point in the future}) 15... Qc7 (15... Qb6 16. Rae1 Rad8 17. b3 Rd4 $15)) 12...
Qc8 (12... Qe7) (12... c5) 13. Qd2 c5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Qd6 (16.
h3 Rad8 17. Qg5 $2 Bxf3) 16... Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Rfd8 18. Rfd1 Rxd6 19. Rxd6 Kf8
20. b3 Ke7 21. Rd1 Rc8 {The position is equal but if White is not careful he
will face problems} (21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Rc8 $15) 22. Ne5 g5 23. Nf3 (23. Bf3
Bxf3 $15 24. Nxf3 g4 25. Ne5 Rc5 26. Nd3 Rc7 27. Kf1 h5) 23... h6) 6... c5 7.
Be3 cxd4 8. Bxd4 Bc5 $1 (8... Qc7 $1 9. Bd3 Bc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bxd4 (11...
b6 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. c3 Bxf3 $1 $15 14. Qxf3 Bxd4 15. cxd4 Qd6 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17.
Qxe4 Nf6 18. Qe3 Rac8 19. Be4 Rfd8 20. g3 Nd5 21. Bxd5 Qxd5) 12. Nxd4 a6 13. c3
b6 14. Qe2 Bb7 15. Rad1 Nc5 (15... b5 $15) 16. Bc2 Rad8 $11) 9. Bxc5 (9. Bxf6
$2 Nxf6 (9... Qxf6) 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. O-O-O+ Ke7) (9. Bb5 $4 Qa5+ $19) 9...
Nxc5 10. Qxd8+ (10. Bb5+ Ke7 $15) 10... Kxd8 11. O-O-O+ Ke7 12. Bc4 b6 13. Rhe1
g6 14. Ne5 Bb7 15. f3 Rhd8 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 $15 17. Rd1 Rc8 $3 18. c3 g5 $3 (18...
h5 19. h4) (18... a6 19. Kb1 b5 20. Bf1 Nd5) 19. Kb1 h5 20. Bf1 h4 21. Ne2 Rg8
$15 0-1

