{[%evp 0,70,30,33,33,46,30,32,49,55,55,55,55,55,61,20,23,45,32,26,35,17,21,14,
14,-2,8,2,-8,-13,10,11,11,10,4,-7,0,0,23,-6,10,2,12,-50,-56,-7,-2,-29,-28,-29,
-11,-26,-11,-12,-15,2,-5,-17,15,-27,-21,-62,-62,-42,0,-56,-41,-55,-15,-21,-24,
-17,-27] The following game presents a masterclass on the art of keeping the
bishops} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 (5. dxc5)
5... cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd8 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 a6 11. c3 Qc7
12. Bb3 Bd6 $11) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Bd3 c5 {Georg Meier is a
great connoisseur of the French Defense and his games can be used as a base to
study the opening} (6... Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bg5 Qd6 (8... Be7 $6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6
10. Qd3 $3 c6 11. O-O-O $14)) 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 {Forcing
the knight to retreat to b3} 10. Nb3 Bd6 11. Be3 (11. Bb5+ {Temporarily
keeping the king in the center is not a problem: Black follows up with Ke7,
Qc7, and Rd8 and finishes his development quickly. White is not in time to
organize an attack} Ke7 12. c3 Qc7 13. h3 Rd8 $11 14. Qe2 a6 15. Bd3 b6 (15...
Bh2+ 16. Kh1 Bf4 $11) 16. Bg5 (16. Nd4 Kf8) (16. Be3) 16... Bh2+ 17. Kh1 Bf4
18. Bxf4 Qxf4 19. Rad1 Bb7 20. Kg1 Kf8 21. Nd4 Qc7 $11) 11... O-O 12. Qe2 (12.
Bc5 {As White, an unexperienced player might think he is getting rid of his
bad bishop but, as we previously discussed, such a trade suits Black's
interests} Bxc5 $15 13. Nxc5 b6 (13... Qc7 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bd7) (13...
Qb6 $1 $15 {A more ambitious move! Black pushes the knight back to b3 in hope
to exploit its isolation later in the game} 14. Nb3 Bd7 15. Qe2 a5 $15 (15...
Ba4 16. Rad1 Bxb3 {A curious solution making sure that White never creates a
passed pawn} 17. axb3 Rfd8 18. Bc4 g6 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rd1 a5 21. g3 Rxd1+
22. Qxd1 Kg7 23. Qd2 Qc5 24. c3 (24. Bd3 b6) 24... b6 $17 (24... b5))) 14. Ne4
(14. Qf3 Rb8 15. Na6 Bxa6 (15... Bb7) 16. Bxa6 Qc7 (16... b5) 17. c3 Rbd8 18.
Bd3 Rd5 19. Rad1 Rfd8 20. Bc2 h6 (20... g6) (20... a5) 21. a4 a5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5
23. Rd1 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 g5 (24... Kf8) 25. g3 Kf8 (25... Qc5) 26. Qd4 Ke7) (14.
Nb3 Bb7 15. Nd4 Qc7 16. c3 h6 17. Nf3 Rad8 18. Qe2 Bxf3) 14... Bb7 15. Nd2 (15.
Nxf6+ $2 Qxf6 $15 {Black has very comfortable play} 16. c3 Rad8 {Let's pretend
for a second Qg5 does not lead to anything} (16... Qg5 $19 {is winning} 17. g3
Qd5) 17. Qe2 Rd6 18. Be4 (18. a4 Rfd8 19. Be4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 a5 {Preventing
White's breakthrough} 21. h3 h5 22. Rfe1 g6 $15 {Black has more active pieces
and a better game}) 18... Bxe4 19. Qxe4 {The position is dry and some might
argue that it will all end in a draw in a matter of moves. However, such an
assumption is very simplistic as the side that controls the only open d-file
is a favorite!} Rfd8 20. Rfe1 g6 $17) 15... Qc7 16. Nf3 Bxf3 $2 (16... Ng4 $3
$19 17. Bxh7+ Kh8) (16... Rad8 $17 17. h3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Rd4 19. c3 Rd5 20. Rad1
Rfd8 21. Bc2 h6 (21... h5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Rd1 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 h4 25. Qd2 Qe5 (
25... g6 26. a3 Qe5 27. Bb1 g5 28. Qc2 Kg7 29. Qd3 Nd5 30. Qh7+ Kf8 31. Qh6+
Ke7) 26. Qd8+)) 17. Qxf3 Rad8 18. Rad1 Rd5 19. Be4 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Rxd8+
Qxd8 22. Bd3 g6 23. Qb7 (23. a4 $2 a5 24. g3 Kg7 25. c3 Qd6 26. Qe2 h6 27. Qd2
Qd8 28. b4 Qc7 29. bxa5 bxa5) 23... a5) 12... Qc7 13. h3 Nd5 {The German GM
shows ambition and starts fighting for the advantage} (13... Bh2+ 14. Kh1 Bf4
15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. a4 b6 (16... Bd7 17. Bb5 Rfd8) 17. a5 Bb7 $11) (13... b6 $11
{is playable and leads to an equal position}) 14. Bd2 Nf4 15. Bxf4 Bxf4 {
Black takes a risk to delay his development in order to create some imbalance
in the game} 16. Rad1 g6 (16... b6 $5 17. Qe4 g6 18. Qxa8 Bb7 19. Qxa7 Ra8 $11
(19... Bh2+ $5 20. Kh1 Bxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Qxa7 22. Kxh2 Qxa2 23. Rb1 Rd8 $132 24.
Rfd1 (24. Nd2 Qd5 25. Ne4 Kg7 26. Ng3 Qe5 27. Kg2 h5 28. Rfe1 Qc7) 24... Rxd3 (
24... Kg7 25. Nd2 Qd5) 25. Ra1 Qxb2 26. Rxd3 Qxc2 27. Rf3 Qe4) 20. Qxa8+ Bxa8
21. a3 (21. Rfe1) 21... f5 22. Rfe1 e5 23. Bf1) 17. c3 a6 $1 (17... b6 $5 {
Surrenders Black's pride of the position: namely the bishop pair} 18. Ba6 Bd7 (
18... Bxa6 19. Qxa6 Rad8 20. Nd4 $15) 19. Bb5 $1 (19. Rfe1 $6 Bc6 $1 20. Bb5 (
20. a3 Rad8 21. Bb5 Ba8) 20... Bd5 $1 21. Bd3 h5 (21... Rad8) 22. c4 $6 $15 (
22. Be4 Bc4 $5 (22... Bxb3 23. axb3 Rad8 24. h4 a5) 23. Bd3 (23. Qf3 Rad8)
23... Bxb3 24. axb3 h4 25. Bc2 $6 (25. Qg4 $14) (25. Bxg6 $17 fxg6 26. Qxe6+
Qf7 27. Rd7 Qxe6 28. Rxe6 Rf7 29. Rxg6+ Kf8 30. Rxf7+ Kxf7 31. Rg4 (31. Rc6 Rd8
) 31... Bc1) 25... Rad8 26. Be4 a5 27. Rxd8 Rxd8 28. Rd1 Rxd1+ 29. Qxd1 Bd6 30.
Qe2 Bc5 31. Qf3 Qd6 32. Qd3 Qf4 33. Qc2 Kf8) 22... Bb7 23. Bxg6 $4 fxg6 24.
Qxe6+ Qf7 $19) 19... Bxb5 20. Qxb5 Rac8 21. Nd4 Rfd8 $15) 18. Be4 Rb8 19. Qf3
Bh2+ $1 {A common idea: pushing the king to h1 and then retreating the bishop
to a central square} (19... Bd7 {is a tactical blunder} 20. Rxd7 $18) 20. Kh1
Be5 21. Rd2 Bf4 $1 $15 {Black prepares to finish his development and stays
true his goal of keeping the bishop pair at all costs} (21... Bd7 22. Nc5 $4
Bb5 $19) 22. Rdd1 (22. Rd3 $4 f5 $19) 22... Bh6 23. Rd4 Bg7 24. Rd2 Bd7 {
At last, Black manages to bring his bishop out} 25. Rfd1 (25. Nc5 $4 Bb5 $19
26. Nd3 f5) 25... Ba4 $1 26. Bc2 Rfc8 $3 {Re-organizing the Black forces: the
idea is to include the rook into play and open up the safe e8 square for the
bishop} (26... Rfd8 {results in the loss of a pawn} 27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28. Rxd8+
Qxd8 29. Qxb7) (26... Bc6 27. Be4) (26... h5) 27. Nd4 Be8 $15 28. Bb3 $1 Kh8 $1
{moving away from potential sacrifices on e6} 29. Ne2 (29. Nxe6 fxe6 30. Bxe6
Rd8 $19) (29. Bxe6 fxe6 30. Nxe6 Qe7 31. Nxg7 (31. Rd8 Qxe6) 31... Qxg7 $19)
29... b5 30. Ng3 Bc6 31. Qe3 Rd8 $1 32. Bc2 Rxd2 33. Qxd2 Be5 34. Be4 (34. Ne4
Bd5 35. a3 Kg7 $17) 34... Be8 35. Ne2 a5 $1 36. a3 Kg7 $1 $17 37. Nd4 Qb6 38.
Nf3 Bf6 39. Kg1 (39. Qd6 Qxd6 $17 40. Rxd6 b4 41. axb4 axb4 42. cxb4 Rxb4 $19)
39... b4 40. axb4 axb4 41. Nd4 (41. cxb4 $2 Qxb4 42. Qxb4 Rxb4 $19 43. Rd2 Rxe4
$19 (43... Rxb2 {Analyzing the 4 vs 3 endgame} 44. Rxb2 Bxb2 45. Nd2 Bb5 46. g3
Kf6 47. Kg2 Ke5 48. Bf3 Kd4 49. Kg1 Bd7 50. Kf1 Kc5 51. Ke2 Bg7 52. Nb3+ Kb4
53. Nd2 f5 54. Nf1 Kc3 (54... Bb5+) 55. Ne3 Bb5+ 56. Ke1 Bd4 57. Nd1+ Kc2 58.
Ne3+ Kc1 59. Be2 (59. h4 Bc3#) 59... Bxe2 60. Kxe2 Bxe3 61. Kxe3 e5 62. Kd3 Kd1
63. Kc4 Ke2 64. Kd5 e4) (43... Bb5 44. Bd3 Bxd3 45. Rxd3 Rb5 46. Rd2 Rxb2 $2 (
46... Bxb2) 47. Rxb2 Bxb2 48. Kf1 (48. g4))) 41... bxc3 42. bxc3 Qc5 43. Qe3
Rc8 $17 44. Rc1 $4 (44. Rd3 Qc4 (44... h5 45. Bxg6) (44... Rb8 45. Nxe6+) (
44... Qa3)) 44... Bxd4 0-1

