15,15,0,-1,0,3,25,-1,-3,-3,15,13,0,0,11,3,0,0,-4,0,3,0,0,-14,-8,-16,-19,-9,0,
-3,-2,0,0,0,0,-26,0,-2,0,-33,-15,-27,-15,-16,-12,-12,-14,-21,-20,-42,-49,-48,
-7,-46,-37,-50,-61,-150,-49,-38,-41,-102,-27,-30,-40,-39,-44,-169,-199,-207,
-208,-208,-200,-256,-305,-392,-400,-405,-224,-785,-880,-979,-1038] Both sides
have equal chances in the 3+3 vs 4+2 structure. Therefore, it is a matter of
style which one you would prefer to play as. I find this analysis to be
thorough and instructive and the game to be a corner stone for learning the
structure.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 (5. Ng5 Ngf6 6.
Bc4 (6. Bd3 h6 7. Ne6 Qb6 8. Nxf8 $14) 6... e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 8. Bd3 h6 9. N5f3 c5
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Ne5 Nbd7 12. Ngf3 Qc7 13. O-O (13. Bf4 Bb4+ 14. Nd2 Bxd2+ 15.
Kxd2 Nd5 16. Bg3 O-O 17. Rad1 $6 Nc5 18. Kc1 Nxd3+ 19. Rxd3 Qc5 $11) (13. Bd2
$2 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxf2+ $17) 13... Bd6 14. Bf4 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 O-O 16. Rad1 b6 17.
Rfe1 Bb7 18. c3 Rad8 19. Bb1 Rfe8 20. Bg3 (20. Qc2 Ne4) 20... Ba8 $11 21. a3
Qb7 22. f3 (22. Nf3 Bxg3 23. hxg3 Qc7 24. Ne5 Be4 25. Bxe4 Qxe5 26. Bc2 Qc7 27.
Qe3 Kf8) 22... Qc7) 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. h3 {One problem with the
Caro-Kann Defense is that in case of Bf5, everything gets exchanged fast and
the position becomes very dry. For that reason, the famous Turkish GM chooses
another approach trying for a win} e6 (7... Bf5 8. Bd3 (8. Bc4 e6) 8... Bxd3 9.
Qxd3 e6 10. O-O Be7 11. Bg5 (11. Rb1 O-O 12. Kh1 $11) 11... O-O 12. Rad1 $11)
8. Bd3 {At the moment, it seems that White's Bd3 is more active than his
counterpart. However, such an impression is illusive since Black cannot be
stopped from playing b6, Bb7, c5 and activating his bishop} g6 9. O-O Bg7 10.
Bf4 {Indeed, White has a small advantage but that is not concerning for the
time being} (10. Bg5 $1 O-O 11. Qd2 $14) 10... b6 (10... O-O) 11. c3 O-O 12.
Be5 Bb7 13. Qe2 $14 {Again, I want to remind that we are looking at typical
middlegames and not concrete opening lines} (13. c4 $5 c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Qe2
{White has a slight edge but that is expected if he follows opening
recommendations. Black's position is very stable and yields a lot of resources}
(15. b3) (15. Bxf6 {Exploring the structure with different minor pieces left
on board} Bxf6 16. Rb1 Bg7 17. Qe2 Qc7 (17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 {Only Black can
fight for an advantage since his bishop is better} Rb8 19. b3 Qc7) 18. Be4 {
White's strategic idea: eliminating Bb7 and then applying light-squared
strategy. Bg7 appears to be very strong but is in fact idle as it does not
attack anything} Bxe4 19. Qxe4) 15... Bxf3 $11 {The start of a series of
exchanging operations: Black alleviates the pressure and obtains a great
position} (15... Nh5 $6 {After} 16. Be4 $16 {, the knight is stranded on the
side of the board and has to lose tempi to come into play. The ensuing
exchanges favor White}) 16. Qxf3 Nd7 $1 (16... Nh5 $11 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Be4
Rb8 19. Rad1 Qf6 20. b3 Qxf3 (20... Rfd8) 21. Bxf3 Nf6 22. Rd6 Rfd8 (22... Rfc8
23. Rfd1 Kf8 24. Ra6 Rc7 $14) 23. Rfd1 Rxd6 24. Rxd6 Rb6 (24... Rc8) 25. Rxb6
axb6 26. a3 $11) 17. Bxg7 (17. Bd6 $2 Ne5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 $17 {The fact that
there are opposite-colored bishops does not mean the game ends in a draw!
Black is the one with the initiative (due to his far stronger bishop) and
needs to keep the heavy pieces on board to maximize his chances. A very
important idea in such endgames is to drive a pawn to h4 and put pressure on
the opponent's monarch} 19. Qe2 Qc7 20. Rad1 h5 (20... Rad8 21. Rfe1 Bd4 22.
Bc2 Kg7 23. b3 h5) 21. b3 (21. h4) 21... h4 22. Qg4 {Black has to watch out
for a sacrifice on g6} Bf6 23. Rfe1 Rad8 {sample play} (23... Kg7 $17 24. Bc2 (
24. Rxe6 fxe6 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Qg6+ Qg7) 24... Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8
26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Qxd1 Qf4) 24. Bc2 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Kg7 26. Qe2 Rd8 27. Rxd8 Qxd8
28. Qd3 Bd4 $17 {Black will now start dancing around with the queen and bishop,
enticing White to blunder. Finally, if such strategy is not working well
enough, he might include f5, e5} (28... Qxd3)) (17. Bg3 Ne5 $3 18. Bxe5 Bxe5
$17) 17... Kxg7 $11 {Black has enough time to coordinate his pieces and occupy
the dark squares} 18. Be4 (18. Rad1) 18... Rb8 19. Rad1 Qc7 {Black has a
response to every one of White's threats} 20. b3 Nf6 (20... Rfd8 21. Rfe1 Nf6
22. Bc2 Rxd1 (22... a5) 23. Rxd1 Rd8 (23... a5 24. Qe3 $11) 24. Rxd8 Qxd8 $11
25. Qd3 $2 Qxd3 $19) 21. Bc2 Rfd8 22. Rxd8 $6 Rxd8 23. Rd1 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 Qe5
$17 {Piece activity is the most important thing in chess! The superior Q+N
combination gives Black practical chances. White does not have viable
counterplay because if he starts going after pawns, he will lose too many tempi
} 25. Bd3 h6 (25... g5 26. a3 a5 (26... h6)) (25... a5) 26. Bf1 g5 $17) 13...
Qe7 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Rfe1 c5 16. Bc4 (16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Be4 {
White seeks to transpose to a good knight vs bad bishop endgame. Black's reply?
} (18. Bc2 Rb8 19. Be4 {It is now not simple to dedide whether to keep the
bishop. In my opinion, it is a matter of style: Bc8 is a very ambitious move
that needs to be calculated carefully} Bc8 20. Nd4 Bd7 $15) 18... Bc8 $3 $17 {
Preserving the bishop pair! Black's position is very stable, and because of
that, he can afford to save the bishop and look for a better square for it in
the future} (18... Qc7 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. a4 $15)) 16... Ba8 17. Bb3 (17. Bxf6
$6 Bxf6 (17... Qxf6) 18. d5 exd5 19. Qxe7 Bxe7 20. Rxe7 dxc4 $11) (17. dxc5
Qxc5 18. Bb3 Qc8 19. a4 $2) 17... a5 {White cannot make use of the weakened
dark squares} 18. a4 $6 {Generally, a4 is a bad idea if White cannot play a5
next. It only leaves his queenside immobile and with no prospects for a passed
pawn} Rfe8 19. Bc4 Ne4 (19... Bc6 $2 20. Bb5 $16) 20. Bb5 Rf8 21. Qe3 (21. Bh2)
21... cxd4 22. Rxd4 Nd6 $11 23. Bd3 (23. Rxd6 Rxd6 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 $17 {Black
has a huge advantage- due to the bishop pair and the open character of the
position. Meanwhile,White does not have active play as the b5 square occupied
by the light-squared bishop is irrelevant to the game} 25. Qe2 Rd8 26. Bc4 h5 (
26... Bf6) 27. Bb3 Bf6 {Prepares h4 and opens up the g7 square for the king} (
27... Bxf3 {is the totally risk-free approach to the position} 28. Qxf3 h4 29.
Rd1 Qc7 30. Rxd8+ Qxd8 31. Qd1 (31. Qe2 Qg5 32. Qc2 Bf8 33. Bc4 Bc5 34. Qd1 Qf4
35. Qc2 Kf8 36. Bb5 Ke7 $17) 31... Qg5 (31... Qxd1+ 32. Bxd1 Bh6 33. Kf1 Bc1
34. Kg1 Bxb2 35. Be2 Bxc3 36. Bb5 e5 37. f3 Kg7 38. Kf1 f5 39. Ke2 Kf6 40. Be8
Kg5 41. Kf1 (41. Bb5 Kf4) 41... Bd4 (41... Kf4) 42. Ke2 Kf4 43. Bc6 (43. Bxg6
b5 44. axb5 a4 45. Bf7) 43... Kg3 44. Kf1 e4 45. fxe4 f4 46. e5 Bxe5 47. Ke2 g5
48. Kf1 b5 49. Bxb5 g4 50. hxg4 f3 51. Bc6) 32. Bc4 Bf8 33. Qc2 (33. Qe2 Qc1+)
33... Bc5 34. Qe2 Qf4 35. Qe1 Kf8 36. Bb5 Ke7) 28. Rd1 (28. Bc2 Bc6 (28... Bxf3
29. Qxf3 Kg7 30. Rd1 Qc7 31. Rxd8 Qxd8 32. g3 h4 33. g4) 29. Be4 Bxa4) 28...
Qc7 29. Rxd8+ Qxd8 30. Bc2 Qd5 $1 (30... Qc7 $2 31. Be4 Bxe4 32. Qxe4 Kg7 $11)
(30... Bxf3 $1 31. Qxf3 h4 $1 (31... Bg7 32. g3 Bf6 (32... h4 33. g4) 33. h4
Kg7 34. Kg2 $11) 32. Qd3 (32. g4 hxg3 33. fxg3 Qc7 34. Kg2 Qc8 35. Qe2 $15)
32... Qc7 $15 33. Qe4 Kg7 34. Qe2 Be7 35. Qe3 Bc5 36. Qe2 Qf4 37. Bd3 Kf8 38.
Qc2 Ke7 39. Kf1 f5 40. Bb5 e5 41. Ke1 (41. Bc6 e4) 41... e4 42. Qd2 Qxd2+ 43.
Kxd2 Bxf2 44. b4 Bg3 45. bxa5 bxa5 46. Ke3 Kd6 47. Kd2 Bf4+ 48. Kc2 Be3 49. Kd1
Bc5 50. Ke2 Ke5 51. Be8 g5 52. Bd7 Kf4 53. Bc6 g4 54. hxg4 (54. Bb7 gxh3 55.
gxh3 Ke5 56. Bc6 Bb6 57. Be8 Bc5 58. Bh5 f4 59. Bg4 Kf6 (59... f3+) 60. Bh5 Kg5
61. Bg4 Bb6 62. Ke1 f3 63. Bd7 Kf4 64. Bb5 e3 65. Kf1 Kg3 66. Bc4 Kxh3) 54...
Kxg4 $1 55. Bb7 Kf4 56. Bc6 Ke5 57. Bb7 f4 $4 (57... h3 $3 58. gxh3 f4) 58. Bc8
$1 $11 h3 59. gxh3 (59. Bxh3)) (30... Qf8 31. Qd1 Bxf3 32. Qxf3 Kg7 33. g3 $1
h4 34. g4 Qd6 35. Qe2 Qf4 36. Be4 Be5 37. Bg2 Qh2+ 38. Kf1) (30... Bxf3 31.
Qxf3 h4 32. Qd3 (32. b3 Kg7 33. Qd3 {Black avoids exchange of queens even at
the cost of a pawn. In a situation with no queens on the board, the game is a
trivial draw} Qc7 (33... Qxd3 34. Bxd3 Bxc3) 34. c4 Qf4 35. Qe2 Be7 36. Qe1 Bc5
{[%csl Yf2][%cal Yf7f5,Ye6e5] For ideas on what to do in a queens +
opposite-colored bishops endgame, I recommend studying the model games 1-0,
Kiril Georgiev- Anatoly Karpov (2002) and 1/2-1/ 2, Ioannis Papaioannou-
Rustam Kasimdzhanov (2018)}) 32... Qc7) 31. c4 $2 Qd7 $3 32. b3 (32. Be4 Bxe4
33. Qxe4 Qxa4 $19) 32... Bxf3 33. Qxf3 Be7 34. Qe2 h4 35. Qd3 Qc7 36. Qe2 Bc5
$19 37. Qd2 (37. Bxg6 $4 fxg6 38. Qxe6+ Kg7 $19) 37... Qe5 38. Qd1 Kg7 39. Bd3
