$19) (23. Bxg7) 23... Bxf3 $3 {GM Atalik showing great understanding!} 24. Qxf3
(24. Bxd6 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Qxf3 Rd8 27. Bb5 (27. Rd1) 27... h5 28. Be2 {
A random move made for illustrative purposes} (28. g3 {followed by h4, Kg2 is
what White needs to play to avoid trouble} Qc7 (28... h4 29. g4 Bf8 30. Bf1 Qe5
31. Rd1 Rxd1 32. Qxd1 Bd6 33. Bg2 Bc5) 29. h4) 28... h4 $3 {Black fixates the
kingside structure and ensures White's king becomes permanently weak} 29. Rd1
Qb8 30. Rxd8+ Qxd8 $15 31. Bb5 (31. Qc6 {Even though for the moment it looks
as if White is the active side, it is Black who has more ideas to try out} Qb8
32. Bb5 Kf8 {Black's king is safe as material is limited} 33. Qd7 (33. b4 Bf6
34. bxa5 bxa5 35. c4 $6 Qf4 $17 {Black has very unpleasant threats}) 33... Bf6
$15) 31... Bf8 32. Qe2 $6 Bc5 33. Kf1 Qg5 34. Qc2 Qf4 $17 35. Qe2 Kf8 36. Bc6
Ke7 37. Bb5 f5 38. Ke1 e5 39. Qd2 Qxd2+ 40. Kxd2 Bxf2 $17) 24... Bxe5 25. Rxe5
Nc8 {The knight temporarily steps back so that Black can occupy the d-file} 26.
Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Re1 Qh4 28. Bc2 Rd2 29. Re2 Rd5 30. Bb3 Rd6 $11 31. Re1 Kg7 32.
Rd1 Qg5 {Black moves back and forth testing his opponent} 33. Qe2 h5 $1 {
Gaining space!} 34. Bc2 {The white bishop is isolated} (34. Rxd6 Nxd6 35. h4 $3
Qc5 36. g3 $15) 34... h4 $1 35. Bb3 Qf4 $15 {The queen is free to thread on
all the dark squares} 36. Bc2 Rxd1+ 37. Qxd1 Nd6 38. Bd3 Qe5 39. Qc1 g5 {
Black intends to further extend on the kingside with f5} (39... f5 40. Qg5) 40.
Qd1 (40. Qe3 $2 Qxe3 $17 41. fxe3 Kf6 42. Kf2 Ke5 43. b4 f5 44. bxa5 (44. c4
axb4 45. c5 bxc5 46. a5 Nc8 $19) 44... bxa5 45. c4 Nb7 46. Ke2 Nc5 47. Bc2 Kf6
48. Kf2 e5 49. Ke2 e4 $1 50. Kd2 Ke5 51. Ke2 f4 52. Bd1 Ne6 53. Kd2 Ng7 $19 (
53... fxe3+ 54. Kxe3 Nd4 55. Bh5 Nf5+ 56. Kd2 Kd4 $19)) (40. b4 Kf6 41. bxa5
bxa5 42. c4 $6 Nb7 $1 $17 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Yb7c5] Black blockades the passed
pawn and simultaneously attacks a4. It is now evident that a4 was a positional
mistake!} (42... Qc5)) (40. Bb1 Kh8 41. Qc2 $2 Kg7 42. Qh7+ Kf8 43. Qh6+ Ke7
$19) 40... Kf6 41. Qf3+ Ke7 42. Qd1 (42. Qc6 {The white queen cannot do
anything on her own} Qc5 43. Qxc5 $2 bxc5 $17) 42... Qc5 43. Qf3 Qe5 44. Qd1 $6
Qd5 45. Qe2 (45. Bc2 Qxd1+ $19 46. Bxd1 Nc4 (46... f5 47. b4 Ne4 48. bxa5 bxa5
49. c4 Nc5 (49... Kd6) 50. g3 e5 (50... Kd6) 51. gxh4 gxh4 52. Kf1 e4 53. Ke2
Kf6 54. Kd2 Ke5) 47. b3 Nd6 $19) 45... Kd7 46. Qc2 Qe5 47. Qd2 Kc7 $15 {
The Black king found a safe haven} 48. Qd1 Qf4 49. Qc2 e5 50. Qd1 (50. f3 f5
51. Qd1 e4 52. fxe4 fxe4 53. Be2 $15) 50... f5 51. Bc2 $2 g4 $3 $19 {Strong
and consistent! White is in serious trouble with imminent threats on his king}
(51... e4 52. Qd4 Qc1+ 53. Bd1 Qxb2 54. Qg7+ Kc6 55. Qxg5 Qb1 (55... Qxc3 56.
Be2 Qa1+ 57. Kh2 Qxa4 58. Qxh4) 56. Qd2) 52. hxg4 fxg4 53. Qf1 Nc4 $3 54. b3
Nd6 55. Qd3 e4 (55... g3 56. fxg3 hxg3 57. Qh7+ Kc6 $19) 56. Qe3 (56. Qd4 g3
$17) 56... Qxe3 57. fxe3 g3 $3 $19 58. Bd1 (58. Kf1 Kc6 59. Ke2 Kd5 60. Kd2 h3
$19) 58... Nf5 59. Bc2 Nxe3 60. Bxe4 Nd1 61. Kf1 (61. c4 Ne3 62. Bg6 Kd6 63.
