{[%evp 0,92,27,25,29,20,55,27,40,23,77,53,60,59,33,-39,-4,-13,-30,-9,-13,14,
-23,-17,-11,-14,-31,-11,-24,-44,-24,-20,-39,-29,-26,-31,-38,-43,-43,-43,-28,
-29,-29,-46,-30,-28,-32,-21,-21,-26,-34,-27,-27,-34,-27,-26,-36,-31,-36,-46,
-39,-36,-50,-74,-45,-38,-85,-93,-91,-49,-49,-57,-49,-43,-97,-132,-125,-110,
-129,-154,-168,-187,-161,-568,-699,-718,-570,-564,-602,-641,-566,-598,-622,
-629,-634] Note: The actual game is 1-0, Papaioannou- Moiseenko (2012).
However, on move 6 I purposefully lose a tempo to "reverse" the colors and
show the game from Black's point of view for more consistency in the lecture.
A general guideline for heavy-piece endgames in this structure is that whoever
controls the d-file has the advantage. The game goes on to show how to exploit
such an edge and put pressure on the opponent} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. d4 Nf6 4.
dxc5 g6 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Be2 Bg7 7. Bb5+ $6 Bd7 8. Nd4 Bxb5 9. Ndxb5 Nc6 10. Bd2
O-O $15 11. a4 Qb4 12. Nxd5 Qxc5 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bc3 Rfd8 15. Qe2 a6 16. Nd4
Nxd4 17. exd4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Rxd4 19. c3 Rd5 20. O-O Rad8 $15 {Two factors that
make Black's position preferable- the possession of the d-file and the
convenient target on a4} 21. Rfd1 e6 22. g3 h5 23. h4 Qb6 24. Kg2 Qd6 25. Rxd5
Qxd5+ 26. Kg1 Qb3 27. Kg2 Rd7 {Black maneuvers around testing his opponent!
The key is to continue poking weaknesses on both sides of the board until the
latter cracks under the pressure} 28. Ra3 Qb6 29. a5 Qc6+ 30. Kg1 Rd5 31. Ra1
$6 Qc7 32. Qf3 Rf5 $17 33. Qe4 Rb5 34. Ra2 Re5 35. Qf3 Re1+ 36. Kh2 Qc4 37. b3
Qxb3 38. Rd2 Re5 $1 39. Rd7 $2 Rf5 $19 40. Qe3 Qb5 41. Rc7 Qf1 42. f4 Rb5 43.
Qd2 Rd5 44. Qb2 Rd1 45. Rc8+ Kh7 (45... Kg7 46. c4+ Kh7 47. Qh8#) 46. Qg2 Qd3 {
Moral of the game: the one who controls the d-file is the one pressing for a
win!} 0-1

