{[%evp 0,20,24,20,45,30,30,30,40,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,36,35,35,20,30,16,16]} 1. e4 e6
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 {The Steinitz variation is one of the most
complex in the French Defence. In this lecture, we will examine typical
middlegame ideas for White and Black in this variation. To simplify our
analysis, I found it appropriate to split the large body of Steinitz material
into three typical structures: 1) positions with blocked centre (Games 1-3) 2)
positions with fluid centre and kingside castling by White and Black (Games
4-7) 3) positions with fluid centre and opposite-side castling (Games 8-10) 
Below, I provide a brief overview of opening variations that will be discussed
in the ten model games that follow.} 5. f4 (5. Nce2 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. f4 Qb6 8.
Nf3 f6 9. a3 a5 10. b3 Be7) 5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 (6... Be7 7. Be3 b6 8. Qd2 O-O (
8... Nc6)) 7. Be3 Be7 (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 O-O (9... a6 10. O-O-O Nxd4
11. Bxd4 Qc7) 10. O-O-O a6 11. Qf2 (11. h4) 11... Nxd4 (11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 b5)
12. Bxd4 Qc7) (7... a6 8. Qd2 (8. Ne2 Qb6 9. Qc1 g5) 8... b5 9. Bd3) (7... Qb6
8. Na4 Qa5+ 9. c3 b6 (9... c4) 10. Bd2 c4) 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Be2 (9. dxc5 Nxc5 10.
O-O-O a6 (10... b6 11. Bb5) 11. h4) (9. O-O-O c4 10. f5 b5) 9... a6 (9... b6
10. O-O f5) 10. O-O b5 *

