{[%evp 0,81,40,28,28,27,17,23,23,25,25,-4,-4,-22,-13,-13,8,-3,48,46,26,14,-21,
-29,-5,-62,-3,-78,-41,-47,-28,-28,5,-20,5,1,-22,-15,3,1,59,8,32,112,169,214,
218,156,139,123,123,144,158,202,197,187,255,169,175,164,181,152,163,202,209,
218,197,215,215,244,237,235,262,237,286,200,213,376,394,423,422,433,446,461]} 
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nce2 {White plays this move to
support his centre with c2-c3. This is not the most popular move in the
position (5.f4 is the main line), but for a French player (particularly a new
one), it is essential to understand the fixed central structure that often
arises after this move.} c5 6. f4 Nc6 7. c3 Qb6 {Black has several ways to
meet White's solid setup, but this one seems to be the most principled,
putting pressure on b2 and d4 pawns.} (7... b5 $5) (7... a5 $5) 8. Nf3 {
[%csl Yc3,Yd4,Ye5,Yf4] White's central structure seems extremely solid and
provides him with a significant space advantage, so the main question for
Black is how to avoid getting gradually squeezed. The answer is:} f6 $1 {
This move increases tension in the centre and creates dynamic possibilities to
neutralize White's space advantage.} 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ge2c3] This is just
one of several reasonable developing schemes that White has at his disposal.} (
{Others are:} 9. g3 {[%cal Gf1h3]}) ({and} 9. Ng3 {[%cal Gf1d3]}) 9... Be7 10.
h4 $5 {This aggressive plan prepares a kingside attack but leaves White
seriously lagging behind in development.} O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8f1] The
combination of Qb6 and Rf8 is quite unpleasant for White as both heavy pieces
gaze at the f2-square. It is clear at this point that Black is getting ready
to blow the centre open with some sort of a sacrifice.} 11. Rh3 (11. Ng3 $2
cxd4 12. cxd4 fxe5 13. fxe5 Rxf3 $1 14. gxf3 Nxd4 $19) (11. b4 cxd4 12. cxd4
Qc7 13. Be3 b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga7a5]}) 11... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,
Gc6a5]} (11... Na5 $2 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 $1 Nc4 14. Ng3 $16 {Anand-Shirov
Frankfurt 2000}) ({I improved on Shirov's ...Na5 idea in the following game:} 
11... cxd4 $5 12. cxd4 Na5 13. b4 Nc4 14. Ng3 $2 {[%csl Rg3,Rh3]} (14. Nc3 $13
{[%csl Yc3] was more to the point. This is why White played a3-b4 in the first
place. The piece sacrifice:} fxe5 15. fxe5 Ndxe5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Ra2 $14 {
[%csl Yc3][%cal Gc3d5] doesn't work that well for Black now.}) 14... fxe5 15.
fxe5 {[#]} Ndxe5 $1 {This classical sacrifice is Black's main trump in the
position, as we will also see in the main game.} 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Ra2 Nxf3+ (
17... Ng4 $5) 18. gxf3 e5 19. Rhh2 Be6 $17 {1-0 (45) Sammour Hasbun,J (2460)
-Kuljasevic,D (2464) ICC INT 2007}) 12. b3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b5,Yc7c3] Anand:
There are two games with 12...Qd8, but this move looks much better. For a
start, there are possibilities of Qc3+ in some lines...} 13. Neg1 {[%cal Gf1d3,
Gf3g5]} a4 ({Anand recommends another good plan for Black:} 13... b6 $5 {
[%cal Gc8a6]} 14. Be3 (14. Bd3 cxd4 15. cxd4 (15. Bxh7+ $2 Kxh7 16. Ng5+ fxg5
17. hxg5+ Kg8 18. Qh5 Ndxe5 19. fxe5 Qxe5+ 20. Ne2 Ba6) 15... fxe5 16. fxe5
Nxd4 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gc7c3]} (16... Ncxe5)) (14. Ra2 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. Re2
Raa8 17. h5 Rac8 18. Bb2 b5 $17 {0-1 (46) Hartvig,O (2220)-Brynell,S (2495)
Helsingor 2011}) 14... Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 {Anand: This looks about equal.}) ({
I tried a different plan in one of my blitz games:} 13... cxd4 $5 14. cxd4 a4
15. b4 {[#]} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gc6a7,Gd7b5] Solving the issue of the passive
knight on d7, while also preparing to exchange light-squared bishops via
b5-square.} 16. Bd3 f5 17. Ne2 Bd7 18. h5 Na7 $1 19. Ng5 h6 20. Nf3 Bb5 $15 {
[%csl Gd3] 0-1 (42) Vasquez-Kuljasevic, Internet Chess Club 2015}) 14. b4 fxe5
15. fxe5 Ndxe5 $1 {Anand: In this position, such drastic measures are simply
necessary. If White can consolidate his centre, then his kingside attack will
be overwhelming.} (15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Ndxe5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Bb2 $16) 16.
dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 $1 {Anand: The best move. White's two knights would keep
tripping on each other, so it's useful to exchange one of them.} Qxe5+ 18. Qe2
Bxh4+ $2 {Anand: He played this quite fast, but it's an error.} (18... Qc7 $1 {
[%csl Re1][%cal Ge6e5] Anand: Black now follows with e5 which should give him
some play. Also, White's king isn't going to be completely safe on the
queenside either. I should add that modern engines side with Shirov,
evaluating this position as slightly better for Black!} 19. Bg5 Bd6 $15 {
[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8h3] , which is similar to my game against Sammour Hasbun.}) 19.
Kd1 $1 {Anand: Now Black has to exchange queens.} Qf6 $2 (19... Qxe2+ 20. Bxe2
Bf2 21. Be3 e5 22. Bxf2 Rxf2 23. Rg3 {I think White has a comfortable edge in
the ending. This reminds me of the ending in the Slav, where White is a piece
up (1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.Ne5 e6 7.f3 Bb4). Here
Black's centre is too loose.}) 20. Nf3 $1 Qxc3 $6 (20... g5 21. Nxh4 Qxf1+ 22.
Qxf1 Rxf1+ 23. Ke2 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 gxh4 25. Rxh4 $16 {White's rooks have all the
open files they need!}) 21. Bb2 {Now White wins a second piece.} Qb3+ 22. Kc1
e5 {The only move - otherwise Ne5 wins the queen.} 23. Rxh4 {Obviously a
pleasant choice - to win a queen or be two pieces up. I saw that I could swap
queens and go into an ending and decided not to bother with the alternative.
Still, taking the queen would have finished it earlier.} (23. Nd2 Bxh3 24. Nxb3
Rf2 (24... Bg4 25. Qxg4 Rxf1+ 26. Kc2 axb3+ 27. Kxb3 c4+ 28. Ka2 $18 {White
just collects all the pawns.}) 25. Qb5 (25. Qd1 Bg5+ 26. Kb1 Bf5+ 27. Bd3 e4
28. Bc2 axb3 29. Qxd5+ Kh8 30. Qxb3 $18) 25... Bg5+ 26. Kb1 Bf5+ 27. Bd3 axb3
28. Bxf5 Rxf5 29. bxc5 $18) 23... Bf5 24. Qd1 e4 25. Qxb3 axb3 26. Nd2 {
Harvesting all these pawns is going to take a while, but basically, the
evaluation of the position is clear - White is winning.} e3 (26... c4 27. Bd4
$18) 27. Nf3 (27. Nxb3 Bg6 28. Be2 Rf2 29. Kd1 Rxg2 30. Rg4 $18) 27... Rae8 28.
Kd1 (28. bxc5 e2 29. Kd2 exf1=Q 30. Rxf1 {Wins as well, but there is no reason
to return material.}) 28... c4 29. Be2 Be4 30. Kc1 Re6 31. Bc3 Rg6 32. Rh2 Bd3
33. Bxd3 cxd3 34. Kb2 d2 35. Kxb3 (35. Rd1 {Followed by Bxd2 just finishes it.}
) 35... Rg3 36. Kb2 {Yes, Kc2 is quicker. I guess I was getting nervous!} g5
37. Kc2 Rc8 (37... g4 38. Nd4 (38. Be5 gxf3 39. Bxg3 f2 40. Rh4 Rf5 41. Rg4+
Kf7 42. Bxf2 Rxf2 43. Kd3 $18) 38... Rf2 39. Rd1 e2 40. Nxe2 Rxe2 41. Rxd2 $18)
38. Kd3 g4 39. Be5 Rc1 40. Rh1 Rxg2 41. Nh4 {I played this and left the stage.
When I came back Alexei graciously congratulated me on becoming World Champion!
} (41. Nd4 $4 {There is one last trick in the position} d1=Q+ $1 42. Rxd1 Rd2+
$1) 1-0

