{[%evp 0,70,33,32,47,30,40,18,34,29,39,12,19,20,34,32,30,14,-5,2,4,1,-4,0,-8,
-8,-4,-75,-38,-41,-32,8,12,12,43,29,8,8,31,8,8,-52,-45,-45,-77,-131,-119,-125,
-86,-126,-124,-127,-193,-193,-190,-234,-246,-246,-220,-223,-198,-243,-292,-317,
-315,-757,-1339,-1662,-1863,-29985,-557,-582,-595]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 8. Ne2 $5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gc2c3]
Erenburg: Quite a rare continuation, whose idea is to build a strong centre
with c2-c3.} (8. Qd2 {is a much more popular line.} b5 9. Nd1 {This is a
well-known theoretical position where Black have tried many moves. In the game
against GM Ivan Saric, I improvised a bit with Morozevich's idea:} g5 $5 {
[%csl Rd4,Re5,Rf4] This was a novelty at the time and it took Saric by
surprise.} ({Among many alternatives,} 9... b4 {[%cal Ga6a5,Rc2c3,Gc8a6]
leaves the best impression in hindsight.}) 10. dxc5 ({It seems a bit
counterintuitive to play} 10. fxg5 {as it surrenders the pawn centre after}
cxd4 11. Nxd4 Ncxe5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6,Gf7] but White's lead in development more
than compensates for this and the engine still prefers white position. For
example:} 12. Nf2 Bb7 13. O-O-O Qc7 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. g3 $14 {Despite the
engine's evaluation, I quite like black position.}) 10... gxf4 11. Bxf4 Bxc5
12. Nf2 Bb7 $13 {[%csl Ye5,Rf7][%cal Ge8c8] White kept his central pawn and he
sports a better pawn structure, yet Black has managed to obtain nice piece
play in return. He will castle queenside and look for his chances in a complex
middlegame.} 13. Nd3 Be7 (13... Ba7 $5) 14. Be2 Qb6 15. a4 $6 {Saric embarks
on a wrong plan. His king will be a bit unsafe after this move.} (15. O-O-O $14
{[%csl Yc1]}) 15... Rg8 16. Bg3 b4 17. Qh6 $6 {Continuing to play risky chess
and neglecting king's safety.} O-O-O 18. Qxh7 f6 19. Bf2 d4 20. a5 Qc7 21. Nf4
Nc5 22. exf6 Bxf6 $4 {Completely misevaluating the arising endgame.} ({Instead,
Black could obtain a strong initiative in the middlegame by playing} 22... Rh8
$1 23. Qg6 Bd6 24. Nh5 b3 $1 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc6b4,Gd8g8] and White's
greedy concept is about to fall apart.}) 23. Qxc7+ Kxc7 24. Bg3 e5 25. Nh5 $2 (
25. Nd3 $16) 25... Bh8 26. O-O Ne4 $2 (26... b3 $1 $17) 27. Bd3 Nxg3 28. Nxg3
$16 Rg4 29. Nd2 Rf4 30. Nge4 Rxf1+ 31. Kxf1 Ne7 32. Nc5 Rg8 33. g3 Nd5 34. Nxb7
Ne3+ 35. Ke2 Kxb7 36. Ra4 {1-0 (36) Saric,I (2651)-Kuljasevic,D (2569) Opatija
2012}) 8... Qb6 9. Qc1 g5 $5 {This is another very important idea in positions
with a fixed centre. White's central bind can sometimes be destroyed with such
an unexpected diversion.} ({It is important to understand that in this
variation, the plan that we have seen in Anand-Shirov:} 9... Be7 10. c3 f6 11.
h4 O-O 12. h5 h6 13. Rh3 $16 {[%csl Ye1,Ye3] wouldn't work nearly as well
because white bishop on e3 covers all the important dark squares, making
sacrifices on e5 virtually impossible.}) 10. c3 {Predojevic prefers to keep
his central structure intact.} ({The engine doesn't mind parting with the
central bind, preferring} 10. fxg5 $5 cxd4 11. Nexd4 Ncxe5 12. Be2 Ng4 13. Bg1
$14 {However, from a human point of view, this seems less intuitive.}) 10...
cxd4 11. cxd4 {Following this strategy to a tee will prove to be risky.} ({
It was worth considering} 11. Nexd4 $5 gxf4 12. Bxf4 {[%csl Yd4,Yf4] when
White would not have such a strong pawn centre but his pieces would be clearly
more active than in the game.} Rg8 13. g3 Nc5 $14) 11... Bb4+ $1 {Erenburg: It
is very important to make White's monarch move to the a7-g1 diagonal.} 12. Kf2
f6 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re5,Rf4] The standard idea to undermine white center.} 13. g3
{[%csl Rc8,Yd4,Ye5,Yf4,Yg3] Erenburg: In this opening line White needs to
stabilize the situation, which will promise him a big advantage, thanks to his
strong centre, space advantage and Black's passive light-squared bishop.
However, it turns out that Black has enough dynamic resources to exploit the
vulnerable position of White's king.} g4 $1 $146 {[%mdl 8] Erenburg: Here is
another opening bomb by Alexander! It should be said that this improvement is
clearly showed by Fritz... From now on there follows a series of forced moves.}
14. Nh4 {[%csl Rh4]} (14. Ne1 {[%cal Ye1d3] is even worse:} fxe5 15. dxe5 (15.
fxe5 Rf8+ 16. Kg2 Bxe1 $1 17. Qxe1 Ndxe5 $19) 15... d4 (15... Bc5 16. Nd3) 16.
Nxd4 Bxe1+ (16... Nxd4 $2 17. Qc4 Bc5 18. b4 $16) 17. Qxe1 Nxd4 18. Qc3 Qc6 (
18... Nb5 $2 19. Qb3 $16) 19. Qxd4 Qxh1 20. Rd1 Qf3+ 21. Kg1 Qd5 $19) 14...
fxe5 {Blowing up White's centre.} 15. fxe5 (15. dxe5 $2 {loses immediately:}
Bc5 $1 {[%cal Yd5d4]} (15... d4 {doesn't work, in view of} 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17.
Qc4 $16) 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 $19 {[%cal Rc5d3]}) 15... Ndxe5 $1 {[%mdl 516] Erenburg:
This is the point! The diagonal a7-g1 is opening for Black's queen!} (15...
O-O+ {would be a huge mistake.} 16. Kg2 $16 {[%csl Gg2]}) 16. dxe5 d4 17. Bf4
Rf8 $1 {[%mdl 4] Erenburg: White's pieces are located so awkwardly that Black
has enough time to activate all his forces.} (17... d3+ 18. Be3) 18. Kg2 Bd7 $1
$40 {[%csl Re2,Rf1,Rg2,Rh1][%cal Gd7c6] The bishop is ready to occupy the long
diagonal.} 19. h3 {White tries to eliminate the g4 pawn, which will give
White's monarch the h3 shelter. This move looks like the least of the evils. I
haven't found anything better:} (19. a3 Be7 20. b4 d3 {[%cal Yb6f2]} 21. Be3
Qb5 {[%cal Yb5d5]} 22. Nc3 Qc4 $17) (19. Qc2 Nxe5 {[%cal Rd7c6]} 20. Bxe5 Bc6+
21. Kg1 d3+ 22. Bd4 Qxd4+ 23. Nxd4 dxc2 {[%cal Yb4c5]} 24. Nxe6 Rf6 $19) 19...
d3 20. hxg4 {Again the best.} (20. Be3 Qa5 21. Nf4 Nxe5 22. Kh2 Rc8 23. Qd1
Rc2+ 24. Bg2 Rxf4 $1 25. Bxf4 Nf3+ 26. Nxf3 gxf3 27. Rg1 Qd5 $17) (20. Nc3 Nxe5
21. Qe3 Bc6+ 22. Kh2 Qxe3 23. Bxe3 Bxh1 (23... Nc4 24. Bh6 Rf2+) 24. Kxh1 Rd8
$19) 20... dxe2 21. Bxe2 Nd4 $15 {Black has won the material back, and, thanks
to better-located pieces and a slightly safer king, his advantage changes from
slight to obvious.} 22. Qe3 $2 {It was not a good idea to put the queen on the
diagonal, where the dark-squared bishop is going to operate...} ({Somehow after
} 22. Bf3 $1 {Fritz doesn't show a clear way to get a big advantage:} Rc8 $1 (
22... Nxf3 $2 23. Nxf3 Bc6 24. Rh6 $1 O-O-O (24... Rc8 25. Qd1 $13) 25. Rxe6
Kb8 $2 26. Rxc6 $16) 23. Qd1 Rc2+ (23... Be7 24. Kh3 Nxf3 25. Nxf3 Qxb2 26. Rb1
Qc2 $15) 24. Kh3 Rxb2 $15) 22... Bc5 $17 {Strong and simple. Now White is in
trouble.} 23. b4 (23. Kh3 Nc2 24. Qd2 Nxa1 25. Rxa1 O-O-O 26. Bg5 (26. Rc1 Bc6
27. Qc2 Be3 28. Bxe3 Qxe3 29. Bxa6 Kb8 $19) 26... Rde8 27. Bf6 Rf7 28. g5 Bc6
29. Bh5 Rd7 $17) 23... Qxb4 24. Rhb1 $6 {White has tried to move away from the
kingside rook from the h1-a8 diagonal, but his other rook is now stuck in the
corner.} ({Better was} 24. Rab1 Bc6+ (24... Qa5 25. Kh3 Bc6 26. Rhc1 $15) 25.
Kh3 Nxe2 26. Qxe2 Qe4 $17) 24... Qa5 25. Kh3 (25. Rd1 {doesn't change too much:
} O-O-O 26. Rac1 Ba4 $1 27. Rxd4 Rxd4 28. Qc3 (28. Qxd4 Bc6+) 28... Qxc3 29.
Rxc3 Bc6+ $19) 25... Nxe2 26. Qxe2 Bd4 $19 {Winning an exchange. Black gets a
big material advantage, while White has no compensation.} 27. Bh6 (27. Qe4 Bxa1
28. Rxa1 Bc6 (28... O-O-O 29. Bg5 Rde8 30. Bf6 $17) 29. Qxh7 O-O-O $19) 27...
Rf2 28. Qe4 Bxa1 29. Rxa1 O-O-O {The rest is a matter of simple technique.} 30.
Bg5 Bc6 31. Rc1 Qd5 32. Qxh7 Qxa2 33. Rxc6+ bxc6 34. Nf3 Rxf3 35. Bxd8 Kxd8 {
and Black easily escapes from checks. A very important game for the theory of
8.Ne2 line. White will have to come up with some new idea, otherwise, they
will have to switch back to 8.Qd2.} 0-1

