{[%evp 0,140,38,35,25,25,25,40,47,7,27,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-3,9,26,17,28,29,-4,38,
-28,4,10,10,10,12,-33,-30,-26,-30,-2,0,-2,-2,-10,-20,-13,-8,-8,34,29,36,34,35,
36,35,23,23,23,23,29,29,21,21,6,6,-16,0,0,0,-57,-50,-114,-123,-175,-203,-176,
-202,-208,-208,-266,-232,-240,-243,-243,-65,-55,-54,-70,-38,-72,-75,-105,-118,
-110,-120,-110,-75,-103,-94,-103,-103,-116,-104,-113,-104,-111,-115,-110,-47,
-110,-54,-40,-42,-147,-158,-158,-178,-182,-178,-182,-178,-182,-178,-178,-182,
-182,-51,-182,-182,-222,-225,-225,-212,-221,-221,-210,-210,-1057,-1436,-29985,
-29988,-29989,-29990,-29993,-29994]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5.
f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Qb6 {This is a relatively rare variation compared to
the alternatives. Black tries to discomfort White by attacking the b2-pawn.} (
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6 {is another version of this idea, leading into the
famous poisoned pawn variation after} 9. Qd2 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5 {etc.
Theory of this variation often runs deep into the middlegame and even endgame,
but it will not be a part of our discussion due to its forcing nature.}) 8. Na4
Qa5+ 9. c3 b6 ({The main alternative is} 9... c4 $6 10. b4 $1 Qc7 {when we get
a type of position that is very similar to the game. However, it is an
inferior version because White is more flexible with his a4-knight. The
following two games are good cases in point:} 11. Be2 (11. g3 $5 Be7 12. Bh3 b5
13. Nc5 a5 14. a3 Nxc5 15. dxc5 $1 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 O-O 18. Nd4 Nxd4
19. Bxd4 Bd7 20. O-O Qc6 21. Qe1 Ra8 22. g4 Qa6 23. f5 $16 {I had to endure a
long-suffering to save half a point in ½-½ (81) Morozov, D (2354)-Kuljasevic,
D (2551) Pardubice 2010}) 11... Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Qc2 b5 {[%cal Ga4c5,Ra4b2]
Black wants to play this move eventually to obtain counterplay on the
queenside, but the problem is that White can play} 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. dxc5 $1 {
[%csl Yd4][%cal Gf3d4] which gives him a clear long-term advantage thanks to
the d4-outpost, good attacking chances on the kingside and a protected passed
pawn on the c-file. Meanwhile, Black has little to no counterplay.} a5 16. a3
Bd7 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 $16 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg2g4,Gf4f5]} axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1
20. Rxa1 Qb7 21. Qa2 Bc6 22. Qb1 f5 {Not the best decision, but Black was
suffering either way.} (22... Ra8 23. Rxa8+ Qxa8 24. f5 $16 {would be similar
to my game against Morozov.}) 23. exf6 Bxf6 24. Qd1 Ra8 25. Rxa8+ Qxa8 26. Bg4
Bd7 27. h3 Qe8 28. Qd2 Qf7 29. Qe3 Bxd4 30. Qxd4 Qf6 31. Qxf6 gxf6 32. Kf2 Kf7
33. Ke3 {1-0 (33) Caruana,F (2779)-Ivanchuk,V (2731) Elancourt 2013}) 10. Bd2
c4 11. b4 {Black had to close the centre and now White's central bind seems to
be super-solid. However, there is one more important idea that Black has at
his disposal - a piece sacrifice on b4.} Qa6 {[%cal Ra4c5] This is a patient
approach.} ({It is also possible to sacrifice the piece at once:} 11... Nxb4
12. cxb4 Bxb4 13. Qc2 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 b5 15. Nc3 b4 {Black gets two advanced
pawns in return for the piece, but practice has shown that they can be
successfully blocked after} 16. Nd1 Qb6 17. Nf3 O-O 18. a3 $1 {The key idea
for White.} b3 19. Qd2 $14 {and Black's compensation is rather static.} f6 20.
h4 $1 Nb8 21. h5 a5 22. h6 Ra7 23. Nc3 $16 {1-0 (63) Caruana,F (2796)-Fridman,
D (2629) Dortmund 2013}) 12. Nb2 $6 {[%csl Rb2] It's a bit premature to
retreat the knight.} ({The critical variation is} 12. Be2 Be7 13. O-O {when it
is not good for Black to push ...b6-b5 because of Na4-c5, as we have seen in
variation 9...c4 above.} f5 14. Qc2 (14. exf6 Nxf6 $132) 14... O-O 15. Kh1 {
[%cal Gf1g1,Gg2g4] The position is blocked and White will naturally try to
open the g-file.} Qb7 16. Rg1 Rf7 17. g4 Nf8 {[%csl Yf8][%cal Gc8d7] This is
the right defensive setup.} (17... b5 $6 18. gxf5 Rxf5 19. Nc5 Nxc5 20. bxc5
Bd7 21. Rg3 Kh8 22. Rag1 $16 {0-1 (57) Karjakin,S (2773)-Duda,J (2737) Chess.
com INT 2018}) 18. Rg3 Bd7 19. Rag1 {and now the key to Black's counterplay is}
a5 $1 20. b5 Na7 $132 {[%csl Rb5]}) 12... b5 {Now Black can play this move
safely because Na4-c5 is not an option anymore.} 13. a3 (13. a4 $6 {only helps
Black generate counterplay:} bxa4 14. Nxa4 Qb5 15. Nc5 a5 $132) 13... Qb7 14.
Be2 Be7 15. O-O a5 {Black will seek counterplay via the a-file. Moreover, this
move weakens the defence of the b4-pawn, which will become important a bit
later.} 16. Qe1 O-O 17. Rc1 f5 {[%cal Rf4f5,Gg2g4] This is a standard
defensive stance for Black in positions with a completely fixed pawn centre.
It would make less sense to play ...f7-f6 here (as we have seen in games 1 and
2) since the sacrifice on e5 is not really an option. White needs to refocus
now from preparing the f4-f5 break to g2-g4, which takes more time to prepare.}
18. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Gg2g4] Vidit follows a textbook plan for such positions -
transfer the knight to the best e3-square to support the g2-g4 break.} (18.
exf6 $6 {only helps Black activate his pieces after} Nxf6 $15 {[%cal Gf6e4,
Gc8d7,Gd7e8,Ye8h5]}) 18... Nb6 $132 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc8d7,Ga8a2]} 19. Ne3 Bd7
20. Bd1 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gg2g4] Another standard manoeuvre, but White's play
leaves an impression of being too deliberate. Duda will take advantage of that
in a very instructive manner.} axb4 21. axb4 Ra3 22. Bc2 Na4 {[%cal Ga4b2,
Gb2d3] Black's counterplay already becomes concrete. Vidit decided to stop
knight's manoeuvre to d3 with} 23. Ra1 Rxa1 24. Qxa1 {[#] but he may have
underestimated a thematic piece sacrifice} Nxc3 $1 25. Bxc3 Nxb4 {[%csl Gb5,
Gc4] On the surface, this sacrifice seems similar to the one analyzed on move
11. However, the key difference is that Black is fully mobilized here and thus
ready to support the march of his connected passed pawns.} 26. Qb1 $6 {Another
slow move. Duda obtained the initiative in a short order.} ({The engine
suggests} 26. Bxb4 Bxb4 27. g4 {which leads to a double-edged position with
mutual chances after} g6 28. Kh1 Be7 29. gxf5 exf5 30. h4 b4 31. h5 b3 $132)
26... Nc6 27. g4 g6 28. gxf5 gxf5 29. Kh1 b4 30. Rg1+ Kh8 31. Ba4 Nxe5 $1 {
[%csl Ra4] A typical French tactic.} 32. Nxe5 Bxa4 33. Bd2 Bd6 34. Qf1 c3 35.
Be1 Bb5 36. Qh3 Bxe5 $1 37. fxe5 Bd3 $19 {[%csl Yb4,Yc3][%cal Gd3e4] Black's
strategy in this game was a complete success. It's a wonderful example of
dynamic play in the French defence.} 38. Rg5 Be4+ 39. Kg1 Qe7 40. Qh6 Qxg5+ $1
41. Qxg5 Rg8 42. Qg3 Rxg3+ 43. hxg3 Kg7 {Two advanced connected passers are no
match for the passive white pieces in the endgame.} 44. Kh2 Kg6 45. Kh3 Kh5 46.
Kh2 Bf3 47. Kg1 Kg6 48. Kf2 Be4 49. Ke2 Kg5 50. Kf2 Kg6 51. Ke2 h5 52. Kf2 Kf7
53. Ke2 Ke8 54. Kd1 Kd7 55. Kc1 Kc6 56. Nd1 Kb5 57. Ne3 Ka4 58. Nd1 Kb3 59. Ne3
Bd3 60. Bf2 Ka4 61. Be1 Ka5 62. Nd1 Kb5 63. Ne3 Be4 64. Kd1 f4 65. gxf4 h4 66.
f5 h3 67. f6 h2 68. f7 h1=Q 69. f8=Q Bf3+ 70. Kc2 Qh2+ 0-1

