{[%evp 0,90,28,21,34,40,25,23,39,46,40,21,26,23,23,24,21,36,31,20,27,29,31,4,
21,22,22,22,15,-9,-6,-6,-1,-1,-1,-15,-15,-17,-17,-35,-15,-27,-28,-65,-58,-83,
-55,-60,-79,-79,-139,-131,-120,-145,-141,-141,-141,-169,-169,-169,-169,-176,
-176,-176,-176,-180,-180,-183,-185,-190,-190,-200,-188,-201,-201,-201,-201,
-201,-200,-200,-200,-200,-200,-200,-200,-212,-250,-244,-244,-248,-248,-340,
-248]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7
8. Qd2 O-O 9. Be2 {Karjakin follows a positional approach as he prepares to
castle kingside.} ({These days, the critical move is} 9. dxc5 {[%cal Ge1c1]
preparing queenside castling (see 9.0-0-0?! c4!) below to understand why 9.
dxc5 is necessary.} Nxc5 {This is the modern line.} (9... Bxc5 10. O-O-O Qa5
11. a3 $1 a6 12. Bxc5 Nxc5 13. Qe3 $1 Bd7 14. f5 $40) 10. O-O-O a6 11. h4 $1 {
This attacking move is important in many variations of the French with
opposite-side castling. In general, Black seems to struggle against White's
best play in this variation, as we can see in the following example:} Qa5 12.
Kb1 b5 13. Bxc5 $1 Bxc5 14. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7]} h6 (14... b4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16.
Qd3+ Kg8 17. Ng5 g6 18. h5 bxc3 19. hxg6 Qxa2+ 20. Kxa2 Nb4+ 21. Kb1 Nxd3 22.
Rxd3 $18) 15. g4 $40 {[%csl Rh6] 1-0 (46) Kravtsiv,M (2653)-Razin,V (2354)
Lvov 2017}) (9. O-O-O $6 {immediately is inaccurate because of} c4 $1 10. f5 b5
$40 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Nxb5 Rb8 13. Nd6 Bxd6 14. exd6 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 15.
c3 Qa5 16. a3 Rf7 $1 $19 {[%cal Gf7b7,Ga5a3] Smith,B-Kuljasevic, Miami 2008,
0-1}) 9... a6 10. O-O b5 11. Kh1 $5 {Carlsen: An interesting, quite unusual
move. 11.a3 or 11.Nd1 are the most usual moves here. The text is actually a
quite cunning waiting move, as ...b4 and a5-Ba6 (the normal reply to Nd1) can
now be met by Na4, while ...Bb7 (one of several possible replies to a3) can be
met by Nd1. Then Black will probably have to play ...b4 and a5-Ba6 anyway, but
with a tempo less. Therefore I decided to be more flexible, and make a more or
less useful waiting move.} (11. Nd1 b4 12. c3 a5 13. Nf2 Ba6 $132) 11... Qc7 (
11... b4 12. Na4 {[%csl Yc5] is the point behind White's waiting 11th move.})
12. a3 Bb7 13. Rad1 Rac8 14. Qe1 {[%csl Re1] Carlsen: A typical manoeuvre.
White intends to gradually start an attack on the kingside. Therefore I
decided to start counterplay in the centre immediately.} ({A logical
alternative is} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 16. Qe3 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Yg1a7,
Gf4f5] when White has better control over the important g1-a7 diagonal while
also preparing f4-f5.} Qb6 $1 17. Bd3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc3e2,Ye2d4] This is
the best diagonal for the bishop in these structures. It also prepares
Nc3-e2-d4 maneuver.} (17. f5 {would be premature because of} Nd7 $1 18. Qf4 Qc7
{[%csl Re5]}) 17... h6 {Making sure there are no sacrifices on h7.} 18. Ne2 {
[#] Here, Black can avoid a central blockade with a typical pawn sacrifice:} d4
$1 19. Nexd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Na4 21. b3 Nc3 22. Rde1 Rfd8 $44 {[%csl Yb7,Yc3,Yd8]
In return for the pawn, Black has obtained open files and diagonals for
virtually all his pieces. The same position with the pawn on d5 would have
been worse for Black because he would have no counterplay in the centre and
White could easily attack with f4-f5, etc.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4
Bc5 17. Qh4 $2 {Carlsen: While this move might objectively speaking not
deserve a question mark, it was definitely a turning point in the game, as
after my reply, Karjakin became very uncomfortable with his position.} (17. Qf2
{[%cal Yf2c5] or something similar was required, as the queen needs to have
more influence in the centre after I play ...f6, which is bound to happen
sooner or later.} f6 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. exf6 Qxf2 20. Rxf2 Rxf6 21. Kg1 Rcf8 22.
Bg4 $11) 17... Bxd4 18. Rxd4 f6 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4]} 19. Bd3 {This one probably
doesn't help much either, but since it was part of the plan with Qh4, I will
not attach any mark to it.} h6 20. exf6 (20. Qg4 Qb6 $1 {would not help White.}
(20... Nc5)) (20. f5 fxe5 21. Rg4 Nf6 {stops any illusions of a white attack.})
20... Rxf6 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4,Rf4][%cal Gc8f8] Carlsen: Now it is clear that
something has gone wrong for White. The rook on d4 is exposed, f4 is weak, and
he will be facing tactical problems with ...e5 quite soon. The "bad" bishop on
b7 is certainly no worse than the white knight, which has dominated it in so
many textbook games.} 21. f5 {[%csl Rd5]} (21. Rg1 Rcf8 22. Ne2 e5 23. fxe5
Nxe5 {would not have been much of a relief; the black pieces are just much
more active than their white counterparts here.}) (21. Qg3 Rcf8 22. Rf3 Nb8 $1
{leaves White on brink of disaster.}) 21... Rcf8 22. Rg1 Nc5 $1 {The most
energetic.} ({The tempting} 22... e5 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Nb6 {trapping the
rook, gives White very good drawing chances after} 25. Qe4 Nxd5 26. Qxd5+ Kh8
27. Re1 {.}) 23. fxe6 Nxe6 24. Rg4 $6 (24. Nxd5 Bxd5 25. Rxd5 Nf4 {[%csl Rf4]}
26. Rd4 Qc5 {forces White to give up the exchange with Rxf4, as} 27. c3 Nxd3
28. Rxd3 Qxg1+ 29. Kxg1 Rf1# {is mate. That being said, it would probably have
been a better try.}) 24... Nf4 25. Qg3 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Yd5d4,Rc3e2]
The last key move, after which Black is completely winning. The point is to
control e2, leaving the white knight without a good square after ...d4 next.
The tactical justification, based on a slightly surprising queen sac, is:} 26.
Rxf4 {After this Black will only have to make a couple of more good moves to
win the game, but White was probably lost in any case.} (26. h3 d4 27. Re1 (27.
Ne2 Nxe2 28. Bxe2 Bc8 $1 {wins an exchange, while}) (27. Nd1 Bc8 28. Re1 Qf7
29. Rh4 Bb7 30. Rg1 Nxg2 $1 (30... g5 {is also very good of course}) 31. Rxg2
Rf3 32. Qg4 Re8 {leaves the uncoordinated white forces defenceless against the
threat of ...Re1.}) 27... Qxe1+ $1 28. Qxe1 Nxd3 {and Black will be material
up in every line.}) 26... Rxf4 27. Ne2 (27. Qg6 R8f6 28. Qh7+ Kf7 {is
obviously not dangerous.}) 27... Rf1 (27... Rh4 {with the idea of 28.Qg6 Rxh2+,
mating was tempting, but I could not refute the considerably stronger 28.c3.})
28. Nd4 {Now Black can force a queen exchange, but} (28. h3 Rxg1+ 29. Kxg1 Qc5+
30. Kh2 d4 $1 {finally activating the bishop, was hardly much stronger.}) 28...
Rxg1+ 29. Kxg1 Re8 {With queens on the board White could perhaps have hoped to
resist, but without queens, the extra exchange is bound to count, even though
the knight on d4 is holding the position together for the moment.} 30. h4 Qe1+
31. Kh2 Qxg3+ 32. Kxg3 Kf7 33. Kf2 Kf6 34. g3 Bc8 35. c3 Bg4 36. Bc2 g5 37.
hxg5+ hxg5 38. Bb3 Ke5 39. Bc2 Rf8+ 40. Kg2 Bd7 41. Nf3+ Kf6 42. Bb3 g4 43. Nd4
Ke5 {Now the white king is cut off, and the undermining a5+b4 cannot be
prevented.} 44. Bc2 a5 45. Bd1 Ke4 {My best game in Corus 2010!} 0-1

