1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O {
Marin: A curious approach. In the traditional main lines, Black tries to
obtain some queenside counterplay before defining his intentions regarding his
king. By castling short so soon Black takes a certain risk but his plan is to
wait until White develops his king's bishop in order to exchange it with ...b6
and. ..Ba6 thus reducing the impact of White's attack.} 8. Qd2 b6 9. Nd1 ({
Karjakin's positional approach} 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O f5 $13 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e4,
Rf4f5] is considered to be fine for Black.}) ({Probably the critical move is} 
9. h4 $1 Nc6 ({Now the plan from the game} 9... a5 {seems to be too slow in
the view of} 10. O-O-O c4 (10... Ba6 11. f5 $40) 11. f5 b5 12. f6 $1 gxf6 13.
Bh6 b4 14. Qf4 Kh8 15. Nb5 $40) 10. Bb5 $5 Nxd4 (10... Bb7 11. O-O-O a6 12.
Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Ng5 $1 $40 h6 $2 14. Qd3 $18) 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Bxd4 $14) 9... a5
$5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga8a6] This is an improvement over Game 5. Black prepares an
exchange of bishops on a6. It's important to include this move to be able to
recapture with the rook so that the knight can be developed to c6.} (9... Ba6 {
is inferior in the view of} 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 {[%csl Ra6]} 11. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Yd4]
[%cal Gd1f2,Gc2c3,Rb6b5]}) 10. c3 {[%csl Yc3,Yd4,Ye5] Giri has fixed the
central structure but in this game, Harikrishna demonstrated another important
way to break it up. On a side note, it would have probably been more
appropriate to discuss this game in the section on fixed central structures,
but I decided to include it in this section to relate it more easily to
theoretical developments in the ...Be7 line (that were discussed in games 4
and 5).} ({Black is well prepared if White tries to change the character of
the position with} 10. c4 Bb7 11. Nc3 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 cxd4 14. Bxd4
{Vovk,A (2622)-Svane,R (2501) Metz 2014 (1-0, 28)} Qc7 15. Be2 Nc6 16. Nb5 Qb7
$15) 10... a4 11. Bd3 {Marin: White could have continued the half-waiting game
by delaying the bishop's development.} ({Marin: To me, the most constructive
move looks to be} 11. Nf2 $5 $146) 11... Ba6 12. O-O Nc6 13. Bxa6 $6 {Marin:
This looks like a small concession.} ({Marin: Giri must have rejected the most
natural} 13. f5 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 {because it exposes the white queen to a later ..
.Nb4.} a3 15. b3 (15. fxe6 {is a similar concession as in the game, leading to
an absolutely fine position for Black:} fxe6 16. b3 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Qe2
Nb8) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 (16. Bxd4 Nc5 17. Qc2 Ne4 $15) 16... Nb4 17. Qe2 $1 ({
The attempt to keep the pawn with} 17. Qb1 {leaves the queen too passive.} Qc8
18. Rf2 Nb8 {[%csl Gf5]} 19. f6 (19. g4 f6 $17) 19... gxf6 20. Bh6 N8c6 $1 {
A thematic exchange sacrifice and one which is already familiar to us .} (20...
Rd8 21. exf6 Bxf6 22. Ne3 N8c6 23. Ng4 Be7 24. Bg5 $40) 21. exf6 (21. Bxf8 Qxf8
$17 {Black has firm control over the dark squares and is better coordinated
despite the lost exchange.}) 21... Bxf6 22. Ne3 Nxd4 23. Qd1 Nb5 24. Rc1 Nc3
25. Qd2 Nbxa2 26. Ng4 Be7 27. Re1 (27. Qd4 f6 28. Nge5 $5 Ne2+ $1 29. Rxe2
Qxc1+ 30. Bxc1 Nxc1 $19 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge7c5,Ga3a2]}) 27... Ne4 28. Qxa2 Nxf2
29. Qxf2 Kh8 {[%csl Ga3] White's attack had come to a dead-end and the a-pawn
is very threatening.}) 17... exf5 (17... Nb8 18. f6 gxf6 19. Bh6 {offers White
a much stronger attack than with the queen on b1.}) 18. Bd2 $44 Nb8 {A typical
regrouping improving the placement of the passive knight.} 19. Ne3 $16 {
Baskin,R (2329)-Neef,M (2406) Germany 2016 (0-1, 32)}) 13... Rxa6 14. f5 b5 (
14... exf5 15. Qd3 $36 {[%csl Ga6,Gf5]}) 15. fxe6 {Marin: (?) While I was
watching the game I considered this to be a serious mistake, as White abandons
any hopes for an attack and dooms himself to play the defender's part. But
since it is the engines' favourite I have inserted my evaluation between
brackets. In fact, the question mark should apply to White's previous play,
preventing him from keeping the tension or insisting on the attack under
optimal circumstances.} (15. g4 {looks too slow:} Nb6 16. Qg2 Nc4 17. Kh1 b4
$36) ({The only consequent move was} 15. f6 $5 gxf6 16. exf6 (16. Bh6 fxe5 {
leaves Black with two pawns for the exchange.}) 16... Nxf6 17. Bh6 Ne4 18. Qe1
f5 {[%cal Gf8f6]} (18... Re8 19. Nf2 $36 {[%cal Ge1g3]}) 19. Bxf8 Bxf8 20. Nf2
{Black has wonderful compensation for the exchange but the position remains
double-edged.}) 15... fxe6 16. Qe2 Qb6 17. Nf2 {[#]} a3 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3,Rd4,Re5]
Hitting the base of White's pawn chain. Soon the pawn chain will be destroyed
altogether.} 18. b3 {[%csl Ra2]} b4 $36 {Marin: Nimzowitsch would be proud of
Black's position: he has managed to attack the pawn chain from its base. White
seems to have defensive resources, but Giri will not exploit them.} 19. dxc5 {
This helps Black in activating his pieces.} (19. cxb4 $5 Nxb4 (19... cxd4 20.
Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Ga6]}) 20. Nd3 Qb5 21. Rad1) 19... Bxc5 20. Bxc5 Nxc5 21. c4
Ne4 22. cxd5 $2 {For far from obvious reasons, White should have kept his pawn
on c4.} (22. Kh1 Nc3 ({The point is that} 22... Nxf2+ 23. Rxf2 Nxe5 $2 {
fails to} 24. c5 $1 $18) 23. Qd3 Ne7 24. Nd4 $15) 22... exd5 {[%csl Ge4,Re5,
Rg1]} 23. e6 {This looks like desperation but the e5-pawn was in trouble
anyway.} ({Now the line} 23. Kh1 Nxf2+ 24. Rxf2 Nxe5 {works perfectly for
Black.}) 23... Ne7 (23... Raa8 $5 $17 {[%cal Ga8e8]}) 24. Kh1 Nc3 {[%csl Ra2,
Gc3,Re6]} 25. Qd3 {[%cal Gf3g5]} h6 {Black is in complete control of the
position. It may be early for speaking about a decisive advantage, but in the
game White will not be able to create any complications.} 26. Nd1 Qb5 $1 {
[%csl Re6]} 27. Qxb5 Nxb5 28. Nf2 Rxe6 $19 29. Nd3 Nc6 30. Rfc1 Nc3 31. Nxb4
Nxb4 32. Rxc3 {Retrieving the pawn is a passing joy due to the second rank
invasion.} Re2 33. Rc7 Ra8 $1 $19 (33... Rxa2 34. Rxa2 Nxa2 35. Ra7) 34. Nd4
Rxa2 35. Rf1 Rd2 36. h3 a2 {The pawn is unstoppable so White resigned.} 0-1

