{[%evp 0,63,24,20,30,30,30,30,40,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,21,21,21,18,11,12,11,2,2,0,14,
-24,-15,-15,-14,-14,4,-50,-44,-41,52,50,60,67,67,80,80,80,80,56,56,154,160,55,
55,228,135,128,128,127,404,404,404,422,429,427,434,434,434,419]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4
d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 {This is
one of the sharpest variations in the Steinitz variation because it usually
leads to opposite-side castling and Sicilian-type flank attacks.} 9. Qd2 O-O
10. O-O-O {[%csl Yc1,Gg8]} a6 {This is the tabiya of this variation. White has
many options in this position. In the 1990-ies when this game was played,
Kasparov's move} 11. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh4h6,Yh3a3] was a big hit. The idea
is not only to advance the h-pawn but also to lift the rook to the third rank
from where it can participate both in the attack and in defence.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4
b5 13. Rh3 $1 b4 (13... Bb7 {is too slow in the view of} 14. Ne2 $1 {[%cal
Ge2d4,Yh3a3]} Qc7 15. h5 Rac8 16. Kb1 $36) 14. Na4 {This is White's point. He
wants to prevent Black's queenside attack by placing the knight in front of
the pawns and controlling important squares on the queenside. The h3-rook will
play an instrumental role in this plan.} Bxd4 15. Qxd4 f6 $6 $146 {Short's
reaction was not the best.} ({White's main idea can be seen in the variation} 
15... Qa5 16. b3 Bb7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7c6] [#]} 17. c3 $1 {[%cal Gh3c3,Yc3b4]
This is the key move. Instead of merely defending on the queenside, White
tries to take the initiative there.} Rfc8 18. Kb2 bxc3+ 19. Rxc3 Rxc3 20. Qxc3
$14 {Nijboer, F-Luther, T/Leuwaarden/1992/}) ({However, it seems like Black
can hold the balance with} 15... a5 $1 16. Bb5 {[%cal Rc8a6]} Rb8 17. Bd3 {
[%csl Rb8][%cal Rc8a6] This is a typical manoeuvre that prevents the exchange
of bishops via a6. Nevertheless, it seems like Black is just in time to
accomplish it in a different way:} Qc7 18. h5 Bb7 19. h6 g6 20. g4 Rfc8 21. Kb1
Bc6 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc6b5]} 22. Nc5 Nxc5 23. Qxc5 Bb5 $11) 16. Qxb4 $1 fxe5
17. Qd6 $1 Qf6 18. f5 $3 {A brilliant move that lead to a powerful attack.
Short had no chance in this game.} Qh6+ (18... Qxf5 19. Rf3 Qg4 20. Rxf8+ Nxf8
21. Nb6 $18) 19. Kb1 Rxf5 (19... Nf6 20. fxe6 $1 Ne4 21. Qxd5 Nd2+ 22. Rxd2 $1
(22. Ka1 $2 Bxe6 $1 $19) 22... Rxf1+ 23. Rd1 Rxd1+ (23... Qxe6 $6 24. Qd8+ Rf8
25. Rf3 $1 Qxa2+ 26. Kxa2 Be6+ 27. Qd5 $18) 24. Qxd1 Bxe6 25. Nc5 $18) 20. Rf3
$1 (20. Be2 $5 Qg6 (20... Rf4 21. Rf3 $1 Rxa4 $2 22. Qc6 $18) (20... Kf7 21.
Rf3 $1 $16) 21. g4 Rf8 22. g5 a5 $14) 20... Rxf3 (20... Qf6 21. Rxf5 $1 Qxf5
22. Be2 Qf7 23. Bg4 Nf6 24. Nb6 $18) 21. gxf3 Qf6 (21... Kf7 {Ftacnik} 22. Bh3
a5 $5 $14) 22. Bh3 Kf7 (22... Nf8 $2 23. Nb6 Qxf3 24. Rf1 $18) 23. c4 $1 (23.
f4 $5) 23... dxc4 (23... d4 24. f4 (24. c5 $16 {Ftacnik} Qe7 25. Qc7 Nf8 26.
Qxe5 Qxh4 27. Bg4) 24... exf4 25. Rxd4 $18) 24. Nc3 $1 (24. Qc6 Rb8 25. Rxd7+
Bxd7 26. Qxd7+ Kg6 $14) 24... Qe7 (24... Nf8 $2 25. Qc6 $1 Rb8 26. Qc7+ $18)
25. Qc6 Rb8 26. Ne4 Nb6 (26... Kf8 27. Bxe6 Qb4 28. Qd6+ Qxd6 29. Nxd6 Ke7 30.
Nxc8+ Kxe6 31. Rd6+ Kf5 32. Ne7+ Kf4 33. Rxd7 $18 {Kasparov}) (26... Nf8 {
Ftacnik} 27. Nd6+ Kg8 28. Nxc8 Qb4 29. Qxe6+ $1 Nxe6 (29... Kh8 30. Qxe5 $18)
30. Bxe6+ Kf8 31. Rd8#) 27. Ng5+ Kg8 (27... Kf8 {Ftacnik} 28. Nxh7+ Kg8 29. Ng5
Bb7 30. Bxe6+ Kh8 31. Qd6 $1 $16) 28. Qe4 g6 29. Qxe5 Rb7 30. Rd6 $1 c3 (30...
Na4 {Ftacnik} 31. Rxe6 $18 Rxb2+ 32. Qxb2) 31. Bxe6+ (31. Rxe6 $5 $18 {Ftacnik}
) 31... Bxe6 32. Rxe6 (32. Rxe6 {Ftacnik} Nc4 33. Qxc3 $1 (33. Rxe7 Rxb2+ 34.
Ka1 Nxe5 35. Rxe5 Rh2 $16) 33... Na3+ 34. Kc1 Qf8 35. Qxa3 $18) 1-0

