{[%evp 0,71,32,18,32,28,45,27,23,20,27,22,22,22,22,22,17,17,17,26,30,12,24,10,
8,8,9,-2,16,19,8,8,41,22,29,51,26,41,45,45,88,105,114,120,149,86,109,109,109,
109,336,589,606,623,602,605,605,237,458,473,848,1056,1300,606,1022,518,553,734,
1472,29988,29989,29990,29991,29990]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5.
f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O a6 {These days,
White achieve the best results with} 11. Qf2 $5 {[%cal Yf2a7] Finkel: The idea
behind 11.Qf2 is very simple and logical- white intends to develop a bishop to
d3 followed by Qh4 later on.} Nxd4 ({Another idea for Black is} 11... Bxd4 12.
Bxd4 {[%csl Yd4] On the surface, it may seem a bit strange to abandon the
fight for the g1-a7 diagonal so abruptly, but Black's idea is to speed up his
queenside expansion, followed by ...Bc8-a6 exchange.} b5 13. Be3 Qa5 $1 {
Making sure that White cannot block the queenside with Na4 after we push the
b-pawn.} 14. Kb1 b4 {[%cal Rc3a4]} 15. Ne2 Qc7 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gc8a6]} 16. Nd4
Nxd4 17. Bxd4 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga5a4] [#] Everything has been pretty logical so
far. Black would be doing very well if he could exchange the LSB's, but White
can deny him that by playing} 18. Bb5 $1 Ba6 (18... a4 19. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc2b3,
Gd1c1]}) 19. Bxd7 {The point.} (19. Ba4 $6 Rfc8 20. f5 Nc5 21. Bxc5 Qxc5 $15)
19... Qxd7 20. b3 a4 21. Rd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2a2] We have an interesting position
on the board. Black has achieved pretty much everything he hoped for, but it
is not clear whether he has a good breakthrough idea on the queenside.
Meanwhile, White can gradually improve his position on the kingside. The
position remains sharp, but White is probably for preference, as the recent GM
game showed:} Rfc8 22. h4 {[%csl Gd4,Rg8][%cal Gh4h6,Gf4f5]} axb3 23. cxb3 {
[%csl Yd4][%cal Gd4a1,Yd4g7]} Rc3 (23... Bb5 24. h5 Qb7 25. Rhd1 Rc6 26. g4
Rac8 27. f5 $40) 24. Bxc3 bxc3 25. Rd4 Qa7 26. Rhd1 Bc4 27. bxc4 Rb8+ 28. Ka1
Rb2 29. Qxb2 cxb2+ 30. Kb1 $16 {1-0 (53) Giri,A (2764)-Holt,C (2549) Chess.com
INT 2020}) 12. Bxd4 Qc7 13. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Yf2][%cal Yf2d4,Yf2h4]} b5 $6 {
Finkel: This was Radjabov's last opportunity to exchange the queens off and to
jump into a slightly worse endgame.} (13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 b5 15. Rhe1 Qb6 16.
Qxb6 Nxb6 17. Ne2 b4 18. Nd4 a5 19. b3 $14 {Pedzich,D-Aaberg,A/Copenhagen 1991}
) 14. Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rh7] Finhel: This is white's idea - to create a couple of
weaknesses on the kingside and to push pawns to open up a position of the
black king.} h6 (14... g6 {Ftacnik} 15. Ne2 Bb7 16. Kb1 $16) (14... f5 15. Ne2
$16 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 15. Ne2 f6 (15... Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc5 17. g4 f6 18. Qg3 fxe5
19. fxe5 $14) 16. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Re6,Rh6][%cal Gg4g6] Finkel: At this point,
it's pretty obvious that Kramnik won the theoretical discussion. White has
developed a very dangerous initiative on the kingside, while Radjabov is
deprived of any counterplay on the other part of the board.} Bxd4 (16... f5 17.
Qf3 (17. Qg6 {Ftacnik} Rf7 18. h3 Nf8 19. Qh5 $14) 17... Qb6 18. Qe3 $1 $16 {
[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh1g1,Gg2g4] Next g2-g4 will be coming soon with very
unpleasant threats over the g-file.}) 17. Nxd4 (17. Qxe6+ {Ftacnik} Kh8 (17...
Rf7 18. Nxd4 Nxe5 19. Qe8+ Rf8 20. Bh7+ Kxh7 21. Qxf8 $16) 18. Qf5 (18. Nxd4
Nxe5 19. Qxd5 Nxd3+ 20. Rxd3 Qxf4+ $11) 18... Be3+ 19. Kb1 g6 20. Qxg6 (20. Qh3
Nxe5 21. Qxe3 Nxd3 22. Qxd3 Bf5 $11) 20... Nxe5 21. fxe5 fxe5 22. Nc3 $14)
17... Nc5 (17... fxe5 $2 {Ftacnik} 18. Qxg7+ Kxg7 19. Nxe6+ Kf7 20. Nxc7 $18)
18. Qg6 {Forcing black to take on d3.} Nxd3+ 19. Rxd3 {[%csl Rc8,Yd4] We have
a classical good knight vs bad bishop scenario that makes most endgames
painful for Black. On top of it, White keeps his attacking ambitions in the
middlegame.} Qc4 $2 {Ftacnik: 'Only the youth has the ability to feed the hope
into desperate counterattack on the queenside. In fact white's advantage after
the correct and logical move 19...Qf7! would be rather symbolic.'} (19... fxe5
20. Nxe6 Bxe6 21. Qxe6+ Qf7 22. Qxe5 (22. Qxf7+ {Ftacnik} Kxf7 23. fxe5 Ke6 24.
Re1 Rf2 $11) 22... Qxf4+ (22... Rad8 {Ftacnik} 23. g3 $14) 23. Qxf4 Rxf4 24.
Rxd5 Rf2 25. Rd2 Raf8 26. Re1 $1 $16) (19... Qf7 $1 {Ftacnik} 20. Qxf7+ (20.
Qg3 fxe5 21. fxe5 Qf4+ 22. Qxf4 Rxf4 23. Rdd1 Bd7 $11) 20... Rxf7 21. exf6 Rxf6
(21... gxf6 $2 22. Re1 $16) 22. g3 $16) 20. Rhd1 Ra7 {It is fruitless to
attempt to win a pawn after} (20... fxe5 21. fxe5 Qxa2 22. Ra3 Qc4 23. Rg3 $1
Qc7 24. Nxe6 Bxe6 25. Qxe6+ Kh8 26. Rc3 Qf7 27. Qxf7 Rxf7 28. Rxd5 $16 {
and white emerges with a pawn up.}) (20... Qxa2 {Ftacnik} 21. Rg3 Qa1+ 22. Kd2
Qa5+ 23. Ke2 Rf7 24. exf6 $16) 21. Kb1 Qc7 22. f5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6] '!'
Ftacnik. Ftacnik: 'Kramnik is ready with all the pieces and thus it makes no
sense to wait with a direct attack. '} Qb6 $6 (22... Qf7 23. Qxf7+ Raxf7 24.
fxe6 Re7 25. Re3 Bxe6 26. Rde1 $16) 23. Rh3 $1 {[%csl Rg8] Preparing Rh6.
Black has no defence against white's mating attack.} fxe5 24. Rxh6 $1 Rf6 (
24... exd4 25. Qh7+ Kf7 26. f6 Ke8 27. fxg7 $18) 25. Qe8+ {Ftacnik: 'White
even got few words of criticism for this solution, since the banal
continuation of the attack via h file was winning more quickly. In reality, is
the choice of world champion very safe and convincing despite few more moves.'}
(25. Qh7+ {Ftacnik} Kf8 (25... Kf7 26. fxe6+ Bxe6 (26... Ke8 27. Rxf6 gxf6 28.
Qg8+ Ke7 29. Nf5#) 27. Rxf6+ Kxf6 28. Rf1+ Ke7 (28... Kg5 29. h4+ Kg4 30. Qg6+
Kxh4 31. Nf3#) 29. Nxe6 $18) 26. Qh8+ Kf7 (26... Ke7 27. Qxg7+ Rf7 28. Qg5+ Kd6
29. fxe6 $18) 27. Rh7 $18 Ke7 28. Rxg7+ Rf7 29. Rxf7+ Kxf7 30. fxe6+ Bxe6 31.
Rf1+ Ke7 32. Qxe5 $18) 25... Rf8 26. Rh8+ Kxh8 27. Qxf8+ Kh7 28. Nf3 $18 ({
Another possibility was} 28. Rd3 $5 exf5 29. Qxc8 exd4 30. Qxf5+ Kg8 (30... g6
31. Rh3+ Kg7 32. Qe5+ $18) 31. Qc8+ {and the black king has no escape - Rf3 or
Rh3 is coming next.}) 28... Qc7 29. fxe6 {The queen with the knight is the
best combination of pieces in the mating attack. Espacially when they are
attacking king which is left alone!} e4 30. Ng5+ (30. Rxd5 $5) 30... Kh6 31. h4
Kh5 32. Qf5 g6 33. g4+ Kxh4 34. Rh1+ Kg3 35. Rg1+ Kh4 36. Qf6 1-0

